INSERT INTO `v4candidates` VALUES (1,237,'','','','','','','2026-06-08 09:48:35','','',0,'',''),(2,391,'Garlin Gilchrist','','https://garlingilchrist.com/','','','2-garlin_gilchrist.png','2026-06-11 22:50:22','<p>Garlin Gilchrist is a husband, dad, a public servant, and an engineer dedicated to making government work for regular people. Now, he’s running for Secretary of State to make government work for all of us — and to protect your right to vote.</p><p>Working alongside Governor Whitmer, Garlin has a proven track record of leading and delivering for Michigan. He played a leading role in delivering free pre-k for all, increasing small business success and diversifying the state economy, protecting abortion access, bringing more high-quality jobs to Michigan, reforming our justice system to create opportunity and keep communities safe, and connecting tens of thousands of Michiganders to reliable, affordable and fast internet.</p>','1',0,'',''),(3,238,'Eli Savit','','https://www.eliformichigan.com/','','','3-eli_savit_headshot.png','2026-06-11 17:43:00','Eli Savit is running for Attorney General to fight for the rights and freedoms of every Michigander. He’ll take on corporate polluters, protect workers and consumers from exploitation, and hold powerful interests accountable. At a time when our constitutional rights are under attack, Eli will be a fearless advocate for justice, fairness, and opportunity for all.','1',0,'',''),(4,235,'Megan Cavanagh','','https://cavanaghforjustice.com/','','','4-MeganCavanagh.png','2026-06-11 22:54:37',' For more than 15 years, Megan practiced appellate law in Detroit, earning respect across the legal community for her sharp analysis and commitment to fairness.  <p>Her work extended beyond individual cases to strengthening Michigan’s judicial system—serving in leadership roles within the State Bar of Michigan and focusing on improving access to courts and the administration of justice statewide.</p>  <p>Elected to the Michigan Supreme Court in 2018, Megan has championed a justice system that is accessible, transparent, and centered on people. She has led efforts to improve child welfare outcomes, strengthen legal representation for families, collaborate with tribal courts, and ensure that courts serve every community with fairness and dignity.</p>  <p>A devoted mother and stepmother of four, Megan balances her public service with family life, serving as a primary caregiver to her mother while remaining deeply connected to her Lansing roots. Her career reflects a simple but powerful belief: justice should not be an abstract ideal—it should actively improve people’s lives.</p> ','1',0,'',''),(5,236,'Noah Hood','','https://www.noahhoodforjustice.com/','','','5-noah_hood.png','2026-06-11 23:08:40','<p>Justice Noah Hood is a lifelong Detroiter, public servant, and jurist committed to facts, fairness, integrity, and the rule of law. Born in 1986 and raised on Detroit’s east side, he grew up in a family deeply rooted in public service, faith, and community leadership. His father served on the Detroit City Council and as senior minister at Plymouth United Church of Christ, while his mother has served for decades as a federal judge after being appointed to the U.S. District Court by President Bill Clinton. His grandfather was a founding member of SCLC and contemporary of Andrew Young.<br></p><p>&nbsp;Justice Hood graduated as valedictorian of Cass Technical High School before attending Yale University, where he studied anthropology and languages. He went on to earn his law degree from Harvard Law School and began his career practicing commercial litigation in Detroit.<br></p><p>Driven by a commitment to public service, Hood joined the U.S. Attorney’s Office in Toledo, where he prosecuted complex federal cases including fraud, identity theft, money laundering, and crimes against children. His work earned recognition from federal law enforcement partners for his leadership and dedication to justice.<br></p><p>In 2019, Hood was appointed to the Third Judicial Circuit Court in Detroit, one of the busiest trial courts in the country, where he presided over high-volume criminal dockets and handled serious felony trials.<br></p><p>During his tenure, he also presided over the Veterans Treatment Court, a problem-solving court for justice-involved veterans. His experience on the bench shaped his belief that justice must be both efficient and fair, ensuring that every case receives careful attention.<br></p><p>In 2022, Hood was appointed to the Michigan Court of Appeals. There, he authored numerous opinions on nearly every aspect of Michigan law, including search-and-seizure, the Confrontation Clause, juvenile justice, family law, zoning law, construction law, and no-fault. The decisions demonstrated a commitment to high-confidence facts and our rules-based order.</p>','1',0,'',''),(6,816,'','','','','','','2026-06-08 12:05:08','','',0,'',''),(7,5694,'','','','','','','2026-06-10 10:50:38','','',0,'',''),(8,5695,'','','','','','','2026-06-10 10:50:38','','',0,'',''),(9,5696,'','','','','','','2026-06-10 10:50:38','','',0,'',''),(10,5697,'','','','','','','2026-06-10 10:50:38','','',0,'',''),(11,5698,'','','','','','','2026-06-10 10:50:38','','',0,'',''),(12,5699,'','','','','','','2026-06-10 10:50:38','','',0,'',''),(13,239,'Tiffany Tilley','','https://www.facebook.com/tiffanytilleyforstateboard/','','','13-tiffany_tilley.png','2026-06-12 10:15:54','','1',0,'',''),(14,240,'Judith Pritchett','','','','','14-judith_pritchett_blue_bkgd.jpg','2026-06-12 10:26:35','<p>I am seeking your support on November 3 to be re-elected to the Michigan State Board of Education. &nbsp;I come you today with over 25 years experience in public schools in Michigan. I have served both small and large school districts as a teacher, building administrator, central office administrator and Superintendent. &nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to my retirement in 2017 I served for 9 years at the ISD level as Chief Academic Office for the Macomb Intermediate School District. I have, over the years, been actively involved in policy decisions working with districts facing challenges from high poverty and low achievement to financial difficulties. &nbsp;</p><p>I am passionate about public education and believe it is the great equalizer for everyone. &nbsp;I believe the purpose of education is to provide equitable educational opportunities for all students. &nbsp;I believe that educators deserve support and respect in our public school classrooms and we need to improve academic achievement in Michigan for all students.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>','1',0,'',''),(15,351,'Brianna Scott','','https://www.brianna4msu.com/','','','15-Brianna_Scott.png','2026-06-12 20:05:26','<p>Attorney/entrepreneur Brianna T. Scott of Muskegon, Michigan received her bachelor’s from Michigan State University (Eli Broad College of Business) and her Juris Doctorate from Wayne State University Law School. After graduating from law school, she was hired as the first African American assistant prosecutor in the Muskegon County Prosecutor’s office, and in 2005 opened her law firm, Brianna T. Scott &amp; Associates, PLLC, in Muskegon, Michigan.&nbsp; Scott remains dually licensed to practice law in Michigan and New York.&nbsp;</p><p>Brianna Scott was elected in November 2018 to an eight-year term to the Michigan State University Board of Trustees, where she currently serves as Chair. Her focus has been Integrity, Transparency, Equity and Accountability. She has been a fearless advocate on behalf of the State of Michigan for the Spartan community, students, and taxpayers.&nbsp; Scott’s tenure has been defined by a commitment to serve as a steward of public trust by ensuring that the University serves in their best interests. Within that scope, demanding absolute accountability from the administration is the oversight responsibility that she takes most seriously. In this role she works to rectify historical oversights; ensure student access, success and well-being; and retain top talent in the classrooms, administration, services, and support staff. As she seeks re-election, her platform remains rooted in the values of inclusion, progress and integrity.&nbsp;</p>','1',0,'',''),(16,352,'Kelly Tebay Zemke','','https://www.kellyformsu.com','','','16-Kelly_Tebay_Zemke.png','2026-06-15 17:14:56','','1',0,'',''),(17,392,'Amir Makled','','https://amirmakled.com/','','','17-amir.jpg','2026-06-12 10:32:33','<p>Amir Makled is a civil rights attorney, University of Michigan–Dearborn graduate, and father who believes a public university must answer to the people it serves — not political pressure or elite interests.</p><p>A top public university must be accessible to everyone. Amir believes every campus and every student deserves equal respect, resources, and representation — regardless of zip code, income, or background.</p><p>Universities must be places where truth is pursued — not avoided or suppressed. Amir is outspoken in defending free speech and academic freedom, including the right of students and faculty to speak out against injustice without fear of retaliation or surveillance.</p>','1',0,'',''),(18,393,'Paul Brown','','https://www.facebook.com/GoBlueVoteBrown/','','','18-paul_brown.jpg','2026-06-12 10:26:35','','1',0,'',''),(19,394,'Shereef Akeel','','https://www.akeelforwsu.com/','','','19-Shereef_Akeel.png','2026-06-12 20:17:44','<p><b>Affordability and Access<br></b>Champion affordable tuition and debt reduction. Fight for increased state funding to keep higher education within reach for working families.</p><p>Expand financial aid and scholarship programs. Prioritize support for first-generation, low-income, and nontraditional students.</p><p>Invest in open educational resources (OER). Encourage faculty adoption of low-cost materials to reduce textbook expenses.</p><p><b>Academic Excellence</b><br>Advocate for stronger faculty retention through competitive salaries and modern infrastructure.</p><p>Partnerships with Detroit industries will create internships and job pipelines for graduates.</p><p>Investments in cutting-edge research facilities will boost WSU’s rankings in STEM, health sciences, and urban studies.</p>','1',0,'',''),(20,395,'Richard Mack','','https://richardmackforwsu.com/','','','20-Richard_Mack.png','2026-06-12 20:20:41','<p>I am running for Wayne State University Board of Governors, and I humbly ask for your support.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>I am a union-side (never employer side) labor and civil rights attorney, for the last 28 years. &nbsp;&nbsp;I have negotiated several dozen labor contracts for unions, with universities and other public employers across the state; including for a 27-union coalition during the Detroit bankruptcy.&nbsp;</p><p>I want to use my experience of wading through government budgets to help deliver a top-notch education for students, while fairly compensating the faculty and staff who make that education possible.</p><p>I am an active Democrat, serving on the Executive Board for the 13th Congressional District Democratic Party Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>I am a civil rights litigator, passionate about protecting the free speech rights of all on campus, and protecting academic freedoms against illegal interference from the outside.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>I am driven to help make WSU more affordable, safe, and connected to the entire state of Michigan.</p>','1',0,'',''),(21,10453,'','','','','','','2026-06-11 10:04:23','','',0,'',''),(22,6075,'','','','','','','2026-06-11 10:07:01','','',0,'',''),(23,353,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(24,364,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(25,375,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(26,385,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(27,386,'Matt Koleszar','D','https://mattformichigan.org/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Matt Koleszar is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Senate in the redrawn 5th District in the August 4, 2026 primary. A teacher by profession, Koleszar was first elected to the Michigan House of Representatives in 2019, representing a Plymouth-area district. He chaired the House Education Committee in 2023 and 2024 when Democrats held the chamber majority, making education a central theme of his legislative record and campaign.\n\nHe is running for the open 5th Senate District, which was redrawn following a 2023 federal court ruling (U.S. District Court for the Western District of Michigan) that found the Michigan Independent Citizens Redistricting Commission had drawn certain legislative boundaries predominantly on the basis of race in violation of the Equal Protection Clause. The new district encompasses Canton, Garden City, Inkster, Plymouth, Plymouth Township and Westland in Wayne County, with no incumbent senator residing within the new boundaries, leaving the seat open.\n\nOn his campaign website, Koleszar emphasizes a results-oriented approach and pledges that \\\"every vote I cast on behalf of your family will be informed by the common facts, values, decency, and sense we all share.\\\" His stated priorities include education, support for families, and the environment. Among the accomplishments he highlights are spearheading state-level protections mirroring the Affordable Care Act, creating a Downtown Business Coalition to advocate for small businesses, and introducing legislation (HB 5176) for back-to-school sales tax relief.\n\nThe campaign lists a mailing address of PO Box 6094, Plymouth, MI 48170. A public campaign phone and email were not found on the campaign website, and no direct portrait/headshot image URL could be confirmed (the site\\\'s main image appears to be a campaign banner graphic rather than a portrait). Koleszar maintains an active social media presence as \\\"Matt for Michigan\\\" on Facebook and Instagram. Identity is confirmed with high confidence based on the match of office (State Senate, 5th District), party (Democratic), and city (Plymouth, Wayne County).\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(28,387,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(29,388,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(30,389,'Dayna Polehanki','D','https://www.daynaforsenate.com/','dayna@daynaforsenate.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Dayna Polehanki is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan State Senate in the August 4, 2026 primary, running for re-election from a district that includes Livonia. A former public school teacher, she was twice named \\\"Teacher of the Year\\\" at New Haven Community Schools. She graduated magna cum laude from Central Michigan University, holds a Master\\\'s Degree in Teaching and a Michigan School Administrator Certificate, and received an honorary degree from Schoolcraft College.\n\nPolehanki was first elected to the Michigan Senate in 2018 and currently serves as Majority Caucus Chairwoman, a leadership role within the Senate Democratic caucus. Her legislative work has focused heavily on education, drawing on her classroom background. Recognitions cited by her campaign include the 2023 Brandi Award from the State Bar of Michigan, a 2021 Excellence in Education Legislative Award, 2019 Child Advocate of the Year, and induction into the 2023 Flushing High School Alumni Hall of Fame.\n\nHer campaign platform centers on five priority areas: Education (improving early literacy, protecting student safety and mental health, recruiting and retaining teachers, and expanding college access); the Economy (working to eliminate working poverty so that \\\"all Michiganders can live dignified lives\\\"); the Environment (treating clean air and water as human rights and advancing climate initiatives); Health (making quality healthcare widely accessible and affordable); and Safety (maintaining safe roads and protecting communities from violence).\n\nPolehanki is married to Jim Walkup, a manufacturing team manager at Ford Motor Company. Her campaign can be reached by email at dayna@daynaforsenate.com or by mail at PO Box 51843, Livonia, MI 48151, with online donations via ActBlue.\n\nNote: The candidate\\\'s official campaign site references \\\"District 5,\\\" while this filing lists the 8th District; this reflects Michigan Senate seat numbering and is consistent with the same incumbent senator (Polehanki currently represents a Livonia-area district). Identity is confirmed as the sitting Democratic state senator from Livonia.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/59a35ff4f7e0abd56a4ad75d/1633049075026-96I13ZV7W6XOAR7KEU9R/72432836_372996156940370_7840486644506427392_n.jpg'),(31,390,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(32,354,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(33,355,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(34,356,'Kevin Hertel','D','https://www.kevinhertelforsenate.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Kevin Hertel is the Democratic incumbent state senator for Michigan\\\'s 12th Senate District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. He resides in St. Clair Shores with his wife Ann and their two children. Hertel comes from a family with a long record of public service: his father, Curtis Hertel Sr., served as Speaker of the Michigan House of Representatives, and his grandfather was a World War II veteran and public school teacher.\n\nHertel was first elected to the Michigan Senate in 2022. Before that, he represented his community in the Michigan House of Representatives from 2016 to 2022. In the Senate he chairs the Health Policy Committee, where he has worked to protect Michiganders\\\' healthcare access, including codifying key provisions of the Affordable Care Act into state law and expanding behavioral health services.\n\nHis campaign platform emphasizes lowering costs for seniors and working families, including reducing prescription drug and health insurance costs; strengthening community safety; expanding educational opportunities for students; and protecting Michigan\\\'s water infrastructure and lakes. He has also focused on responding to the opioid crisis and on protecting children from abuse and neglect.\n\nLocally, Hertel volunteers with the St. Clair Shores Waterfront Environmental Committee and Macomb County Special Olympics, and serves on the board of directors of Macomb County Care House. His campaign maintains a website and an active Facebook presence and directs supporters to donate via ActBlue. No public campaign phone number or email is listed on his campaign site; the campaign\\\'s mailing address is P.O. Box 531, St. Clair Shores, MI 48080.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://run.imgix.net/740fd148-f5fd-4e33-80ed-df3780a60ad7/4ee7bcda-f670-4dd1-a55e-81bda648a395/4ee7bcda-f670-4dd1-a55e-81bda648a395.png?ixlib=js-3.8.0&bri=0&con=0&sat=0&high=0&shad=0&usm=0&rect=58%2C45%2C917%2C871&w=1500'),(35,357,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(36,358,'Sue Shink','D','https://www.votesueshink.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Sue Shink is the incumbent Democratic Michigan State Senator for District 14, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. District 14 includes the northern half of Ann Arbor and portions of Washtenaw and Jackson Counties (including the city of Jackson). She assumed office on January 1, 2023; her current term runs through January 1, 2027.\n\nBefore serving in the State Senate, Shink served on the Washtenaw County Board of Commissioners, including as Board Chair. She describes herself as a longtime advocate, conservationist, farmer, and public servant, and presents herself as a solutions-oriented, problem-solving legislator focused on improving everyday life for working families, students, and seniors.\n\nHer stated priorities and platform themes include advancing civil rights, investing in infrastructure, supporting working families and seniors, environmental conservation, and building inclusive and prosperous communities. She is associated with conservation and environmental work, including recognition from the Michigan League of Conservation Voters.\n\nPer her campaign materials, listed endorsements include Washtenaw County Sheriff Jerry Clayton, Ann Arbor Mayor Christopher Taylor, Ann Arbor City Councilmember Travis Radina, and Superior Township Treasurer Brenda McKinney.\n\nCampaign finance data through December 31, 2025 reportedly showed her 2026 campaign with roughly $83,810 in contributions and about $60,020 in expenditures.\n\nHer official campaign website is votesueshink.com (campaign committee \\\"Vote Sue Shink,\\\" PO Box 185, Dexter, MI 48130). No public campaign phone number or email was listed on the campaign website. Identity is confirmed as the correct candidate based on the matching office (State Senate District 14), party (Democratic), and Ann Arbor/Washtenaw location.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(37,359,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(38,360,'Deandre Barnes','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Deandre (De\\\'Andre) Barnes is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Senate, District 16, in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is listed on the Monroe County unofficial August 2026 primary candidate list with a residence in Newport, Michigan (Monroe County). The seat is currently held by Republican Joe Bellino Jr., making Barnes a challenger in a district that has leaned Republican. Beyond his candidacy filing, very little public campaign information is available online for Barnes at this time. No official 2026 campaign website, contact phone, email, or candidate-issued platform or endorsement information was located through public sources. (Note: a website at deandre-barnes.com exists but belongs to a different person, a De\\\'Andre A. Barnes running for Portsmouth, Virginia City Council, and should not be associated with this Michigan candidate.) This is a factual summary only; no detailed biography, priorities, or endorsements were found to report.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(39,361,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(40,362,'Anthony Pennock','D','https://www.pennock4misenate.com/','info@pennock4misenate.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Dr. Anthony Pennock is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Senate, District 18, in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is from Pennfield, just north of Battle Creek, and describes himself as the youngest of five children in a blended middle-class family. Before entering education, he worked a range of service-industry jobs, including retail, bartending, and as a hotel night auditor, experiences he cites as shaping his understanding of the challenges facing working-class Michiganders.\n\nPennock is an educator by profession, having taught at the elementary, middle, and high school levels with a focus on supporting students with different learning styles and special-education needs. He completed a doctorate in education/organizational leadership in 2021 and has been active since 2019 as an education advocate working on teacher working conditions and bridging gaps between educators and support staff. He identifies as a researcher, special educator, and union leader.\n\nHis campaign frames him as \\\"a true voice for hardworking people across the District,\\\" and his platform emphasizes \\\"Working People\\\'s Priorities,\\\" centered on education and support for marginalized students and staff, though detailed policy specifics were limited on his campaign site. He connects his motivation for public service to a family legacy, noting that his great-grandfather, PFC Nyal E. Pennock, died in World War II.\n\nNo current or prior elected offices are listed; this appears to be his run for public office in this district. No endorsements were found in the available sources. His campaign maintains a website (pennock4misenate.com) and a Facebook presence (\\\"Pennock for MI Senate,\\\" Battle Creek, MI). A campaign contact email (info@pennock4misenate.com) is published; no public campaign phone number was found.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/681cd39e6467423f5ff71944/6b73c3c1-07bd-4bd1-a0c4-9be155d33669/Campaign+Photo+0509.jpg'),(41,363,'Julie M. Rogers','D','https://www.juliemrogers.com/','julie@juliemrogers.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Julie M. Rogers is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Senate in the 19th District, running in the August 4, 2026 primary for the Kalamazoo-area seat being vacated by Sen. Sean McCann. She currently serves in the Michigan House of Representatives, where she was first elected in 2020 and is in her third term representing the 41st House District, which includes parts of the cities of Kalamazoo and Portage as well as Kalamazoo Township and Comstock.\n\nRogers has a healthcare background, earning a master\\\'s degree in physical therapy from Marquette University and working as a practicing physical therapist. She has family roots in Kalamazoo County. Her civic and professional service includes the National Association of Counties Health Steering Committee, the West Michigan Cancer Center Board, and the Bronson Hospital Patient & Family Advisory Council.\n\nHer campaign platform emphasizes healthcare access, including new supports for pregnant individuals and opposition to Medicaid work requirements; public education funding, including universal free school breakfast and lunch programs; environmental protection through lead service line replacement; community mental health services; and infrastructure improvements such as work on the US 131 business loop to reduce neighborhood truck traffic. She frames her candidacy around advocating for \\\"an economy and government that works for everyone, not just a select few,\\\" with a stated focus on healthcare, education, housing, environmental protections, infrastructure, and safer communities.\n\nIdentity is confirmed as the correct person by the match of party (Democratic), office (19th District State Senate), location (Kalamazoo), and the August 2026 primary. No campaign phone number was published on her official site; the public contact email is julie@juliemrogers.com, with a campaign mailing address of P.O. Box 19097, Kalamazoo, MI 49019.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d6536ef981f160001041d94/3f1c80ad-7791-4769-80ce-035b1fdb926c/3N2A9067.JPG'),(42,365,'Dale Murney','D','https://www.murney4senate.com/','dale@murney4senate.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Dale Murney is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Senate in the 20th District, running in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is based in Paw Paw, Michigan, with a campaign mailing address at 125 N. Kalamazoo St., P.O. Box 26, Paw Paw, MI 49079.\n\nMurney positions himself as a political outsider rather than a career politician, framing his campaign around a personal philosophy of \\\"if you don\\\'t like it, change it.\\\" He cites family principles of addressing problems through change, fixing broken systems, and committing full effort.\n\nProfessionally, Murney describes a background in social services, having worked with issues including crime, child abuse, child neglect, and family support systems. He says this experience showed him a \\\"slow and steady decline in funding and programming to meet the needs of the least of us,\\\" which motivated his run.\n\nHis platform centers on several priorities:\n\nEducation and teachers: He proposes raising teacher salaries to competitive living wages to combat the teacher shortage, noting Michigan\\\'s average starting salary (around $41,600) falls roughly 12% below the national average. He also supports implementing Young 5\\\'s early-childhood programs statewide, adding a \\\"life-skills\\\" graduation requirement to prepare students for adulthood, and expanding vocational training.\n\nEconomic and housing issues: He advocates increasing affordable housing options, pointing to a gap between median incomes and homeownership costs, and proposes working with builders and zoning boards to streamline development and incentivize affordable housing.\n\nBroader goals: He frames his candidacy around giving \\\"the working class a fighting chance\\\" and expanding the middle class, and notes Michigan\\\'s competitive disadvantages relative to other states.\n\nThe campaign maintains an ActBlue donation page (Committee to Elect Dale Murney) and an official website. No public campaign phone number or endorsements were found in available sources. The campaign contact email is dale@murney4senate.com.\n\nNote: Biographical detail beyond his stated social-services background and platform is limited in publicly available sources. This summary synthesizes content from his official campaign website.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/698380d299ead90c7c8821b3/95f033e5-d51f-41c6-986e-de6849ad7b58/FullSizeRender.png'),(43,366,'Sarah Anthony','D','https://www.votesarahanthony.com/','info@votesarahanthony.com','(517) 234-3050','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Sarah Anthony is the Democratic incumbent State Senator for Michigan\\\'s 21st District, based in Lansing, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. A native of Lansing with roughly two decades of public service, she made history as mid-Michigan\\\'s first African American woman elected to both the Michigan House of Representatives and the Michigan Senate. In 2023 she became the first Black woman to chair the powerful Senate Appropriations Committee, a role she continues to hold.\n\nAnthony\\\'s path to the Senate began in local government, where she became one of the youngest Black women in the U.S. to serve on a county commission, later serving as chair and vice chair of the board. Before her legislative career, she spent close to a decade with the Michigan College Access Network, including roles as Deputy and Interim Executive Director, focused on expanding college access. She earned a bachelor\\\'s degree from Central Michigan University and a master\\\'s degree from Western Michigan University, and previously served in the Michigan House, including a stint chairing the House Democratic Caucus.\n\nHer campaign platform emphasizes education and college affordability, healthcare access and expansion, criminal justice reform, support for workers and small businesses, workforce development, veterans, and housing. She presents herself as an effective lawmaker, skilled budget negotiator, and community-oriented leader committed to improving quality of life for mid-Michigan families.\n\nCampaign contact information includes a mailing address of PO Box 12267, Lansing, MI 48909, email info@votesarahanthony.com, and phone (517) 234-3050. No specific 2026 endorsements were identified in the sources reviewed. Identity is confirmed by the match of office (State Senate, 21st District), party (Democratic), and city (Lansing).\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/3fc37f_0e5fc14c5d5242dba660c4a168644dad~mv2.jpg/v1/fill/w_435,h_654,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/6G9A8062_edited.jpg'),(44,367,'Robert Hower','D','https://robhower.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Rob (Robert) Hower is a Democratic candidate for Michigan\\\'s 22nd District State Senate seat in the 2026 election. A resident of Green Oak Township in Livingston County, he was the first Democrat to declare his candidacy for the seat being vacated by term-limited Republican Sen. Lana Theis. The 22nd District includes Livingston County and portions of Genesee, Ingham, Oakland, and Shiawassee counties.\n\nHower describes himself as an engineer, teacher, small-business owner, and union member. According to local news coverage and his campaign, he teaches electrical engineering at Wayne State University, works as a research engineer at the University of Michigan, and owns a small business, Numed Technologies, LLC. He has said he felt he \\\"needed to step up and do something,\\\" framing his candidacy around a desire to address education, health care, and economic challenges in the region.\n\nHis campaign centers on three core priorities: Education, Innovation, and Economy. On education, he emphasizes reform and support for trade programs and community colleges, as well as ensuring children have the tools and resources they need to succeed. On the economy, he focuses on strengthening Michigan\\\'s foundation through skilled workers, opportunity, and innovation. He has also emphasized expanding access to and affordability of health care.\n\nBased on available reporting, Hower would face Livingston County Sheriff Mike Murphy, the presumptive Republican nominee, in the November 2026 general election, assuming neither faces a contested primary.\n\nNo public campaign phone number or email address was found on his campaign website. This summary is synthesized from his official campaign site and local news coverage (WHMI 93.5, Blue Water Healthy Living, and Livingston County Democrats).\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://i0.wp.com/robhower.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Rob_Dogs.jpg?resize=683%2C1024&ssl=1'),(45,368,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(46,369,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(47,370,'April L. Osentoski','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'April L. Osentoski is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan State Senate, 25th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary. She is from Bad Axe in Michigan\\\'s Thumb region (Huron County area). Osentoski previously ran for the Michigan House of Representatives in District 98 as a Democrat, losing in the November 5, 2024 general election. According to Ballotpedia, she was born in Detroit, attended Great Lakes Junior College, and has career experience as a chef. Her primary online campaign presence appears to be a Facebook page (originally created for her 2024 House District 98 run), and she is listed among Michigan Democratic Party candidates on voter-guide aggregators. Detailed 2026 platform specifics, endorsements, and contact information were not directly accessible from the sources reviewed (her Facebook and Ballotpedia bio pages could not be fully retrieved, and the Blue Voter Guide endorsements page returned an access error). As a Democrat running in the heavily Republican-leaning 25th Senate District, she faces a challenging general-election environment. This summary is based on limited publicly accessible information; no campaign-specific phone, email, official campaign website (beyond social media), or direct headshot image URL was confirmed. Identity is confirmed via the consistent match of name, Democratic affiliation, Bad Axe residence, and Michigan legislative candidacy across multiple sources.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(48,371,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(49,372,'John D. Cherry','D','https://www.cherryformichigan.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'John D. Cherry is the Democratic incumbent seeking reelection to the Michigan State Senate\\\'s 27th District, which covers Flint and Genesee County. He is running in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary. Cherry has served in the Michigan Legislature, first in the state House and then in the Senate, where he currently chairs the Senate Labor Committee and serves as Assistant President Pro Tempore. He is part of a prominent Genesee County political family; his father, John D. Cherry Jr., served as Michigan\\\'s Lieutenant Governor.\n\nHis campaign, under the theme \\\"Fighting for workers, families, and the places we love,\\\" organizes its platform around workers\\\' rights, families, conservation, and community engagement. Cherry\\\'s stated agenda for the next term emphasizes putting workers first, protecting Michigan\\\'s outdoors, investing in children, and strengthening Flint and Genesee County.\n\nThe campaign highlights several legislative accomplishments. On families and children, Cherry secured initial funding (reported as $16.5 million) to pilot a prenatal and infant cash-assistance program in Flint, which the campaign says has delivered over $12 million to more than 2,000 Flint families since January 2024. On education, he points to securing $248 million in the 2026 state budget to continue free breakfast and lunch for Michigan public school students. On conservation, he cites funding for wetland restoration across Genesee County in partnership with Ducks Unlimited. On worker safety, he authored Senate Bill 43, signed into law, requiring concrete safety barriers to protect road construction workers on Michigan freeways. He has also publicly emphasized agricultural research at Michigan State University as important to the state\\\'s farm economy.\n\nCherry has received an endorsement from the Michigan Education Association (MEA) in the 27th District, according to his campaign site. His official website is cherryformichigan.com, which includes an ActBlue donation link, indicating an active fundraising operation. The site did not list a public contact phone number or email, and the candidate\\\'s headshot on the site is embedded rather than available as a direct downloadable image URL. This summary is synthesized from his campaign website, Ballotpedia, the Michigan Senate Democrats site, and related news coverage.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(50,373,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(51,374,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(52,376,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(53,377,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(54,378,'Rebecca Amidon','D','https://www.rebeccaamidon.com','vote@rebeccaamidon.com','765-702-9003','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Rebecca Amidon is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Senate District 32 in the August 4, 2026 primary. She lives in the Manistee National Forest area near Manistee with her husband Ryan and their two young children.\n\nProfessionally, Amidon is an adjunct communication professor at Mid Michigan College with more than 10 years of experience in higher education. She holds a Master\\\'s degree in Organizational Leadership from Trine University and an undergraduate degree in Media and Public Communication from Purdue University Fort Wayne.\n\nHer community and political involvement includes serving as Vice Chair of the Manistee County Democratic Party (2021-2024), Vice President of the children\\\'s nonprofit NoMi Forest Explorers, and membership in the Michigan Northwest Regional Child Care Planning Coalition and the Early On Steering Committee.\n\nAmidon\\\'s campaign platform emphasizes rural-focused priorities, including protecting healthcare access and rural hospitals, strengthening public education and childcare support, supporting workers and small businesses, ensuring rural communities receive equitable state investment, and addressing rising costs and affordability for families. She frames her approach as differing from traditional politics, emphasizing listening, accessibility, honesty, and a focus on outcomes over talking points.\n\nAccording to reporting, she has received endorsements from EMILY\\\'s List, Teamsters Local 406, and the Mason and Manistee Democratic parties (endorsements reported via Michigan Advance, not independently confirmed on her campaign site at the time of research).\n\nContact: campaign phone 765-702-9003, email vote@rebeccaamidon.com, mailing address P.O. Box 183, Manistee, MI 49660.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/b66d8e_72b48210fa12489a8c7a1ae0cfad92f9~mv2.jpg'),(55,379,'Stan Opal','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Stan Opal is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Senate in the 33rd District, on the ballot for the August 4, 2026 primary. Opal is listed at White Cloud, in Newaygo County, which falls within the 33rd District. The district is an open seat for 2026 because the incumbent, Republican Rick Outman, is term-limited; the district spans portions of Kent, Ottawa, Newaygo, Montcalm, Ionia, Lake, and Muskegon Counties.\n\nBased on the limited public material located, Opal appears to be trained as a computer scientist and is associated with a company described as IronFortress LLC, and is identified in coverage of 2026 transgender candidates in Michigan. The platform references emphasized in available sources include protecting constitutional and civil rights, treating digital rights as essential to freedom, preserving national forests/natural areas, and supporting clean, renewable energy.\n\nNote on confidence and disambiguation: very little campaign-specific information was found for this candidate, and some online references conflate the name with the 2026 U.S. Senate race rather than this State Senate District 33 race. The office, district (33), party (Democratic), and city (White Cloud, Newaygo County) given in the task are internally consistent with the open District 33 seat, so the candidacy itself is plausible, but the biographical/platform details above are drawn from sparse, partly secondhand sources and should be treated as best-effort rather than confirmed. No official campaign website, contact phone, contact email, or headshot photo could be verified. Voters seeking authoritative confirmation should consult the Michigan Bureau of Elections official 2026 primary candidate listing.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(56,380,'Tyler Landgraf','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Tyler Landgraf is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan State Senate, 34th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is listed as residing in Chippewa Lake, Michigan, which is located in Mecosta County in the central/west part of the state, consistent with the 34th Senate District. Beyond the official candidate filing, very little public information about Landgraf or his campaign could be found online. No official 2026 campaign website, public contact phone number, contact email, or candidate headshot/portrait was located through web searches. No published platform, list of priorities, endorsements, or biographical detail (such as current or prior elected offices) could be confirmed from available sources. As a result, this is a factual summary only and does not include a synthesized platform. Voters seeking more information may wish to consult the Michigan Bureau of Elections official candidate listing or local Mecosta County news and party sources as the 2026 primary approaches.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(57,381,'Chedrick Greene','D','https://chedrickgreene.com/','info@chedrickgreene.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Chedrick Greene is the Democratic candidate for Michigan\\\'s 35th District State Senate seat in the 2026 election, seeking the full four-year term. He is the current incumbent: Greene won a May 2026 special election for the 35th District, defeating Republican Jason Tunney with roughly 60% of the vote, and was sworn into the Michigan Senate on May 21, 2026. His win allowed Democrats to retain control of the chamber. The 35th District covers portions of Saginaw, Bay, and Midland counties.\n\nGreene is a Saginaw-based U.S. Marine veteran with about 30 years of decorated military service and a recently retired Fire Captain. He has been a union member for roughly 31 years and frames his candidacy around being a working-families advocate. His platform emphasizes lowering household costs (housing, groceries, and healthcare), creating better job opportunities, strengthening public safety, protecting healthcare and public schools, supporting free school meals, defending reproductive rights, and standing up for Michigan veterans. In office, he has pointed to finalizing a state budget that prioritizes increased public safety funding and free school meals.\n\nHis campaign has reported endorsements from Michigan labor unions, Governor Gretchen Whitmer, Congresswoman Kristen McDonald Rivet, State Representative Amos O\\\'Neal, and local leaders from across the district\\\'s counties.\n\nCampaign contact is via info@chedrickgreene.com and mailing address P.O. Box 3442, Saginaw, MI 48605; no public campaign phone number was listed on his website. Identity is confirmed by the match on Michigan, the 35th Senate District, Saginaw, and the Democratic affiliation.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://i0.wp.com/chedrickgreene.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/photo-credit-Riley-Murdoch-for-mlive.com-1.png?resize=4269%2C2400&ssl=1'),(58,382,'Mark W. Yonkman','D','https://www.yonkmanforsenate.org/','Mark@MarkYonkman.com','989-269-5599','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Mark W. Yonkman is the Democratic candidate for Michigan\\\'s 36th State Senate District in the August 4, 2026 primary. A resident of Boon (Wexford County), he announced his candidacy on May 14, 2026, and is running as the lone Democrat in the primary, positioning himself to challenge Republican incumbent Sen. Michele Hoitenga (R-Manton) in the November general election.\n\nYonkman describes himself as a sixth-generation farmer, former Fortune 500 executive, and community leader. His agricultural roots in Wexford County trace to the 1870s, when his family immigrated from the Netherlands. After careers in law and banking, he returned to Michigan in 2018 following the deaths of his parents, restarting the family farm. He became active in local agriculture and politics, joining the county Farm Bureau Board of Directors and serving as Chair of its Policy Development Committee. He has also served as a foster home for children from Detroit and adopted two children.\n\nAccording to his campaign, Yonkman was recruited to run by local agricultural leaders, local Republicans, and the local Democratic Party. His platform centers on rural representation and \\\"common-sense\\\" governance, emphasizing that \\\"rural voices are overlooked in Lansing, and that needs to change.\\\" Core priorities include protecting Michigan\\\'s agricultural heritage, strengthening local economies, and advancing practical solutions for farmers, small businesses, and families. His campaign materials also reference issues such as agriculture, energy, efficiency, education, and resilience.\n\nContact information from his official campaign website includes email (Mark@MarkYonkman.com), phone (989-269-5599), and a mailing address of P.O. Box 23, Boon, MI 49618.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/291491_42c8eecafb63423d91b7ba5617b14f5f~mv2.jpg'),(59,383,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:53','','',0,'',''),(60,384,'Kelli J. Van Ginhoven','D','','Kellifordistrict38@gmail.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Kelli J. van Ginhoven is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan State Senate, District 38, in the August 4, 2026 primary and November 3, 2026 general election. The district covers the Upper Peninsula. Van Ginhoven is the sole Democrat in the primary; she is expected to face Republicans Beau LaFave and David Prestin (and fellow Democrat Chris Mapps was also reported in the field) in the broader 2026 contest.\n\nA near life-long resident of Delta County, van Ginhoven is a 1998 graduate of Escanaba High School and a 2005 graduate of Bay College. She worked as a preschool teacher and at a credit union before opening her downtown Escanaba bakery, \\\"For The Love of Cupcakes\\\" (roughly 2016-2024). She has served on the Escanaba Downtown Development Authority and the planning commission, and was chair of the Delta County Democratic Party.\n\nShe currently serves as vice chair of the Delta County Board of Commissioners, representing District 4. She first assumed office in May 2024 (via a recall election) and was elected in November 2024. On the county board she has chaired the Personnel Committee and served on bodies including the Airport Advisory Board and an opioid task force.\n\nVan Ginhoven launched her Senate campaign in August 2025, framing it around Upper Peninsula representation. She has said the citizens of the U.P. \\\"deserve to be heard in Lansing\\\" and that she will \\\"stand up and speak out\\\" when leadership disregards U.P. needs. Her stated priorities include raising wages for local and county employees to retain and attract residents, addressing housing through state support, and building \\\"back a better middle class for the U.P.\\\" She has expressed strong support for local labor unions and public schools, and emphasizes listening to constituents, noting that many U.P. residents are \\\"not red or blue, they\\\'re Yoopers.\\\"\n\nThe campaign\\\'s public contact email is Kellifordistrict38@gmail.com. She maintains an X (Twitter) account, @KVGforMi2026, and accepts donations via ActBlue (secure.actblue.com/donate/kvgforsenate2026). No dedicated standalone campaign website was identified in available sources. Identity is confirmed by the matching office (Michigan Senate District 38), party (Democratic), and city (Escanaba).\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://ogden_images.s3.amazonaws.com/www.dailypress.net/images/2025/08/17105058/Kelli-van-Ginhoven-580x840.jpeg'),(61,637,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(62,396,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(63,402,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(64,403,'Hillary Scholten','D','https://hillaryscholten.com/','info@hillaryscholten.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Hillary Scholten is the Democratic incumbent U.S. Representative for Michigan\\\'s 3rd Congressional District (Grand Rapids and West Michigan), running for re-election in 2026. She is filed in the Democratic primary on August 4, 2026, with the general election on November 3, 2026.\n\nScholten is a former U.S. Department of Justice attorney and a Grand Rapids native. In 2022 she won Michigan\\\'s 3rd District, becoming the first Democratic woman to represent West Michigan in the U.S. House and flipping a district that had been held by Republicans for roughly 50 years. She has served in Congress since January 2023.\n\nHer campaign messaging emphasizes bipartisan, common-sense problem-solving and constituent service, positioning herself as a representative willing to work across the aisle on the region\\\'s most pressing issues. She frames her candidacy around continued effective advocacy and leadership for West Michigan.\n\nIdentity is confirmed: this is the sitting MI-3 Democratic congresswoman based in Grand Rapids, matching the office, district, and city in the candidate record. Note: although the source record listed incumbency as unknown, Scholten is in fact the incumbent. Per Ballotpedia, Zachary Ketchum is also reported as a 2026 Democratic primary candidate in the district. No campaign phone number was published on her official site; the public contact email is info@hillaryscholten.com and the campaign mailing address is PO Box 6233, Grand Rapids, MI 49516. No clean direct headshot image URL was located on the campaign site (the available image was a splash/background crop rather than a portrait).\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(65,404,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(66,405,'Christian Vukasovich','D','https://www.christian4michigan.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Christian Vukasovich is a Democratic candidate for U.S. Representative in Michigan\\\'s 5th Congressional District in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is based in Galien, in the southwest corner of the district. By profession he is a college professor and a labor organizer, and he describes his areas of expertise as foreign policy, health communication, and the study of extremist discourse. He is the son of immigrant parents and frames his campaign around bringing integrity and working-class values to Washington.\n\nVukasovich\\\'s platform emphasizes government accountability and reducing self-dealing in Congress. He has publicly stated support for banning members of Congress from trading individual stocks, summarizing his view as \\\"Public service is not self-service.\\\" Immigration policy is another central theme of his campaign, including expressed concerns about ICE enforcement activity within the district. His messaging centers broadly on representing working people and restoring public trust in elected office.\n\nHe is challenging the seat held by long-serving Republican incumbent Rep. Tim Walberg, who has represented the district through multiple terms. Michigan\\\'s 5th is rated as a strongly Republican-leaning district (Cook PVI of roughly R+13), so Vukasovich is widely regarded as running an uphill, underdog campaign, a framing reflected in local coverage of his bid. He has been engaged in grassroots petition-signing and meet-and-greet events organized through Michigan Democratic Party channels.\n\nThis summary is synthesized from search-result snippets and his campaign\\\'s public description. Direct campaign contact details (phone, email) and a headshot image could not be retrieved because the campaign website and several news sources returned access-blocked (HTTP 403) responses; those fields are left null. Identity is confirmed by the match on Michigan, the 5th Congressional District, Democratic Party affiliation, the Galien hometown, and the 2026 election cycle.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(67,406,'Debbie Dingell','D','https://debbiedingellforcongress.com/','info@debbiedingellforcongress.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Debbie Dingell is the Democratic incumbent U.S. Representative for Michigan\\\'s 6th Congressional District, running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. She has represented southeast Michigan in Congress since 2015, originally winning the seat (then numbered the 12th District, later redrawn to the 6th) that her late husband, longtime Congressman John Dingell, held for decades. She resides in the Ann Arbor area, and the 6th District covers parts of Washtenaw and Wayne counties.\n\nDingell describes herself as \\\"a tireless fighter for working families in Michigan\\\" and frames her platform around working collaboratively across divides on critical issues. Her stated top priorities include protecting the Great Lakes and the environment (she emphasizes climate change as a real problem requiring proactive solutions), lowering healthcare costs (asserting that everyone in America has a right to quality healthcare), improving infrastructure, and creating and protecting manufacturing jobs and supporting labor amid economic uncertainty. She positions herself as a leader in improving civility in public discourse, stating that people can \\\"disagree with one another without being disagreeable.\\\"\n\nBefore serving in Congress, Dingell had a long career in business and Democratic Party politics in Michigan, including work with General Motors and leadership roles in the state and national party. According to reporting, her 2026 campaign has highlighted endorsements such as from The Committee to Protect Health Care.\n\nHer official campaign website is debbiedingellforcongress.com, and she also maintains a separate official congressional office website (debbiedingell.house.gov). A public contact email is info@debbiedingellforcongress.com; no campaign phone number was listed on the campaign site.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://debbiedingellforcongress.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/20140626_Dingell-0575-1-scaled-e1593461775708.jpg'),(68,407,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(69,408,'Kristen McDonald Rivet','D','https://kristenmcdonaldrivet.com/','info@kristenmcdonaldrivet.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Kristen McDonald Rivet (D) is the incumbent U.S. Representative for Michigan\\\'s 8th Congressional District, running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary. She has held the seat since January 2025, when she won the race to succeed retiring Rep. Dan Kildee.\n\nBorn in Portland, Michigan, in 1970, McDonald Rivet grew up in a working-class Catholic family; her father was a construction worker. She earned a B.A. in history from Michigan State University (1992) and a master\\\'s in public administration/education from the University of Michigan-Flint (2010). Before elected office she worked extensively in public service and the nonprofit sector, including as executive director of Michigan Head Start, in the Michigan Department of Human Services, as chief of staff to the State Superintendent, vice president of the Skillman Foundation, and president/CEO of Greater Midland Inc.\n\nHer elected career began on the Bay City Charter Commission and the Bay City Commission (2nd Ward). In 2022 she was elected to the Michigan Senate, becoming the first Democrat in over a decade and the first woman to represent the Great Lakes Bay Region in that seat, defeating Republican Annette Glenn. She vacated that seat upon election to Congress.\n\nHer campaign centers on lowering costs and expanding opportunity for working families, framed around a \\\"fair shot\\\" for Michigan workers. Consistent with her House and Senate record, her priorities emphasize cost-of-living relief, economic opportunity, and delivering results for the Great Lakes Bay Region and mid-Michigan. Her campaign has highlighted endorsements including the Michigan Fraternal Order of Police and support from local editorial boards, and she has been backed by EMILYs List. She and her husband, Joseph Rivet, a former state legislator, live in Bay City and have six children.\n\nCampaign contact is via kristenmcdonaldrivet.com (Kristen for Michigan, P.O. Box 854, Bay City, MI 48707); the email above is inferred from the campaign domain and should be verified. No public campaign phone number was located.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/ca/McDonald_Rivet_Kristen_119th_Congress%28crop2%29.jpeg'),(70,409,'Ray Pooley','D','https://www.pooley4congress.com','Pooley4Congress@gmail.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Ray Pooley is a Democratic candidate for U.S. Representative in Michigan\\\'s 9th Congressional District in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is based in Highland, Michigan. Pooley describes himself as a third-generation manufacturer and a CNC machinist and computer programmer with roughly 15 years of hands-on experience in the trade. His campaign, branded \\\"Not Bought, BUILT,\\\" centers on his blue-collar background, noting his family\\\'s history producing rubber gaskets, O-rings, plastic components, and car parts. He grew up in a rural area surrounded by small farms and credits hunters and fishermen in his family with teaching him environmental stewardship.\n\nHis platform emphasizes reviving American manufacturing and bringing back \\\"good paying, high skilled manufacturing jobs\\\" that pay what he calls \\\"dignity wages.\\\" Additional priorities include making healthcare affordable so that it \\\"doesn\\\'t bankrupt\\\" people, holding corporations accountable, and conserving the environment. He frames his candidacy around the argument that current representatives are \\\"too out of touch\\\" with working people and that Congress needs someone with direct, working-class manufacturing experience.\n\nPooley is running in a contested Democratic primary; reporting indicates Wyatt Clark is also seeking the Democratic nomination in the district. The 9th District seat is held by Republican incumbent Lisa McClain. No campaign phone number, endorsements, or detailed policy positions beyond the themes above were found in available public sources. The contact email listed on his campaign site is Pooley4Congress@gmail.com, and his campaign accepts donations through ActBlue.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/65ce28_915f7fd1632346909a6d65449835418f~mv2.webp'),(71,397,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(72,398,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(73,399,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(74,400,'','','','','','','2026-06-15 14:41:57','','',0,'',''),(75,622,'','','','','','','2026-06-16 13:21:33','','',0,'',''),(76,415,'','','','','','','2026-06-16 13:21:59','','',0,'',''),(77,416,'','','','','','','2026-06-16 13:21:59','','',0,'',''),(78,1896,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(79,1897,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(80,1898,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(81,1899,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(82,1900,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(83,1901,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(84,1902,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(85,1903,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(86,1904,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(87,1905,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(88,1906,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(89,1907,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(90,1908,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(91,1909,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(92,1910,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:13:27','','',0,'',''),(93,241,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(94,263,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(95,274,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(96,285,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(97,296,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(98,307,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(99,318,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(100,329,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(101,340,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(102,242,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(103,253,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(104,255,'Kimberly L. Edwards','D','https://www.facebook.com/JointeamEdwards/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Kimberly L. Edwards is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 12th House District, which covers northeast Detroit, Eastpointe, and St. Clair Shores. A Detroit native and Eastpointe resident, Edwards has a professional background as a social worker. She is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary and is currently serving her second term in the Michigan House of Representatives, having defeated Randell Shafer in the November 2024 general election.\n\nIn the House, Edwards serves on the Appropriations Committee and on the Appropriations subcommittees for Human Services (where she is Minority Vice Chair) and for State and Local Transportation. According to her official Michigan House Democrats biography, her stated legislative priorities include defending reproductive freedom, protecting the environment, and ensuring access to a quality education for every Michigan student.\n\nEdwards maintains an official legislative presence through the Michigan House Democrats and a campaign Facebook page (\\\"Kimberly Edwards for State Representative\\\" / JointeamEdwards). No standalone dedicated campaign website, direct campaign phone, campaign email, or direct headshot image URL was confirmed during this research; the campaign Facebook page appears to be her primary campaign-facing online presence. Voters seeking constituent contact information can typically reach her legislative office through the Michigan House of Representatives directory. This summary is a factual synthesis from her official House biography, Ballotpedia, and related public sources; specific contact details could not be verified and are reported as null.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(105,256,'Mai Xiong','D','https://www.voteformai.com/','mai@voteformai.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Mai Xiong is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 13th House District (covering Warren, Roseville, and St. Clair Shores) and is running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary and the November 2026 general election. A first-generation American and the daughter of Hmong refugees, she grew up in a large family that relied on food assistance, an experience she cites as shaping her focus on economic security and support for working families.\n\nBefore her election to the Michigan House, Xiong served as a Macomb County commissioner. As State Representative, she has highlighted accomplishments tied to the FY25 state budget, including $133 million for student mental health support and school safety, free breakfast and lunch for all public school students, and tuition-free two-year college for high school graduates and adults.\n\nHer campaign platform emphasizes being a champion for all families: addressing the cost of living and affordable housing, combating food insecurity, ensuring access to childcare, and expanding services that help seniors maintain independence. She also stresses neighborhood safety through fully funding police and fire services, protecting workers\\\' rights, connecting small business owners to public resources, improving healthcare through bipartisan legislation, infrastructure investment, and environmental protection.\n\nAccording to her campaign website, Xiong has received endorsements from EMILY\\\'s List, Sheet Metal Workers Local Union 80, the Michigan Regional Council of Carpenters and Millwrights, The NewDEAL, and MI List. Her contact email is mai@voteformai.com; no public campaign phone number was listed on her website at the time of research.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.voteformai.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CD157-0719-rev1-2500.jpg'),(106,257,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(107,258,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(108,259,'Stephanie A. Young','D','','StephanieYoung@house.mi.gov','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Stephanie A. Young is the incumbent Democratic state representative for Michigan\\\'s 16th House District and is running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. The 16th District covers northwest Detroit—including the Brightmoor, Castle Rouge, West Outer Drive, and Grandmont-Rosedale communities—along with southern portions of Livonia and Redford Charter Township, in Wayne County.\n\nYoung is serving her third term in the Michigan House of Representatives. She was first elected in 2020 and was re-elected in 2024 with roughly 73.5% of the vote. In her current term she has held several leadership roles, including chair of the Detroit Caucus, chair of the House Democratic Caucus, and chaplain for the Michigan Legislative Black Caucus.\n\nA Detroit native, Young graduated from Cass Technical High School and earned her degree from Michigan State University\\\'s James Madison College. Her career in public service began as a legislative aide to a former state representative. Over the years she has worked with multiple former state representatives, several Detroit mayoral administrations, and community advocacy organizations including the Detroit Area Agency on Aging, where she focused on constituent service, community advocacy, and relationship-building on behalf of her neighbors.\n\nSpecific 2026 platform planks, endorsements, and a dedicated campaign website were not located in the sources reviewed. Young maintains an active public and official presence through the Michigan House Democrats website and official social media accounts (Facebook and X/Twitter under the handle @RepStephYoung). Her campaign committee, \\\"Stephanie A. Young for State Representative,\\\" is registered with the Michigan Secretary of State\\\'s campaign finance system. As a Detroit Democrat representing a heavily Democratic district, her record and caucus leadership reflect a focus on Detroit-area constituent priorities and Democratic legislative goals, though no detailed 2026-specific issue statement was found online at the time of research.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(109,260,'Laurie Pohutsky','D','http://www.lauriepohutskyformichigan.com/','LauriePohutsky@house.mi.gov','(517) 373-1530','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Laurie Pohutsky is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 17th House District, which covers Livonia, northern Redford, and parts of northwest Detroit in Wayne County. She is running for reelection in the August 4, 2026 primary.\n\nPohutsky was born in Livonia in 1988 and grew up in Redford. She earned a Bachelor of Science in Microbiology from Michigan State University and worked as a laboratory technician in food safety, toxicology, and health care before entering politics. She was first elected to the Michigan House in 2018 (then representing the old District 19), reelected in 2020, and won the redrawn 17th District in 2022, winning reelection again in 2024. From January 2023 to January 2025 she served as Speaker Pro Tempore of the Michigan House.\n\nPohutsky has been a prominent advocate on reproductive rights, including efforts to repeal Michigan\\\'s dormant 1931 abortion ban, as well as LGBTQ+ equality and public health issues. Her broader platform has emphasized protecting reproductive freedom, expanding access to health care, and supporting working families.\n\nPublic contact information available through her official state legislative office includes phone (517) 373-1530 and email LauriePohutsky@house.mi.gov. Her campaign committee operates under the name \\\"Pohutsky for Michigan\\\" with a campaign website. Note: the state office phone/email are her official legislative contacts rather than dedicated campaign contacts; a campaign-specific email was not located. No direct headshot image URL could be confirmed because the campaign website was unreachable at research time, though official portraits exist on the Michigan House Democrats site.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(110,261,'Kelly Garrett','D','https://voteforkellygarrett.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Kelly Garrett is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 18th District in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district encompasses Farmington, Farmington Hills, Lathrup Village, Oak Park, and Southfield in Oakland County. The seat is open, as the incumbent representative is reported to be vacating it to seek a Michigan Senate seat.\n\nGarrett currently serves as Mayor Pro Tem of Lathrup Village and previously served as the city\\\'s Mayor. In local office, her work focused on public safety, infrastructure, and community engagement. Her campaign messaging emphasizes affordability—keeping families from being \\\"priced out of their community\\\"—and protecting community members from intimidation.\n\nHer platform centers on a set of progressive priorities: defending reproductive freedom, expanding access to affordable healthcare, securing affordable housing, strengthening neighborhood and public safety, and fighting for fair wages. She has also spoken about protecting women\\\'s rights (including reproductive and voting rights), protecting transgender individuals from violence and discrimination, and ensuring all children have access to quality education, framing these views in part through her Christian faith.\n\nGarrett previously ran for U.S. Congress; her current campaign social media accounts retain \\\"For Congress\\\" branding from that prior effort. Coverage from a progressive outlet notes she has drawn endorsement support in her state House race, though specific endorsement details could not be fully confirmed across sources. Her official campaign website (voteforkellygarrett.com) and Ballotpedia profile provide the primary record of her candidacy.\n\nNo public campaign phone number or email was listed on her campaign website; the site offers only a contact form. This summary reflects information available as of mid-2026 and may be incomplete.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://content.campaignpartner.net/images/cdn_queue/148220/f35374b14fdf44e285c19965ec1ad558.jpg'),(111,262,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:42','','',0,'',''),(112,264,'Noah Arbit','D','https://noahformi.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Noah Arbit is the Democratic incumbent state representative for Michigan\\\'s 20th House District, which covers parts of Oakland County including West Bloomfield, Commerce Township, and the Lakes area. First elected in 2022 and re-elected in 2024, he is running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary, with his current term ending January 1, 2027.\n\nBorn and raised on West Bloomfield\\\'s east side, Arbit holds degrees in comparative politics and Jewish studies. Before his election he worked on Democratic campaigns including Hillary Clinton\\\'s and Governor Gretchen Whitmer\\\'s, founded the Michigan Democratic Jewish Caucus in 2019, and served as Director of Communications for the Oakland County Prosecutor\\\'s Office in 2021. He says he ran because he was frustrated that Greater West Bloomfield had been represented by what he describes as extremist legislators and wanted his community to have a stronger voice in Lansing.\n\nHis stated priorities and platform areas include expanding mental health access; combating hate crimes and extremism; protecting the environment and the region\\\'s inland lakes and water; gun violence prevention; reproductive and LGBTQ+ rights; voting rights and democracy; education; economic development and jobs; support for seniors; and criminal justice reform (\\\"smart justice\\\"). According to his campaign materials, his legislative work has included securing over $5 million in state funding for local infrastructure during the 2023-24 term and introducing hate-crime legislation, bills addressing AI-driven disinformation, and mental health practitioner regulations.\n\nHis campaign website is noahformi.com, and his campaign mailing address is listed as PO Box 253005, West Bloomfield, MI 48325. No public campaign phone number or email was found on the campaign site. Specific endorsements were not located in the sources reviewed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://noahformi.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/meet_noah_3.jpg'),(113,265,'Kelly Breen','D','https://www.votekellybreen.com/','hello@kellybreen.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Kelly Breen is the Democratic incumbent state representative for Michigan\\\'s 21st House District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary and November 2026 general election. She has represented the district since 2020 and is serving her third term. The 21st District covers parts of Novi, Farmington, Farmington Hills, Northville, and South Lyon in Oakland County. Breen is based in Novi.\n\nBefore her legislative service, Breen worked as an attorney and community activist and served as a member of the Novi City Council. She is a mother of two.\n\nIn the Michigan House, Breen has chaired the House Judiciary Committee. According to her campaign and the Michigan House Democrats, her record emphasizes bipartisanship and finding common ground. She has highlighted work on criminal justice reform, protections for seniors and children, and expanding economic opportunity. As Judiciary chair, she has been associated with legislation codifying reproductive rights, advancing LGBTQ+ protections, and enacting firearm-safety measures.\n\nHer 2026 campaign website (votekellybreen.com) was a placeholder at the time of research, noting an updated site was forthcoming, so a detailed 2026-specific platform was not available there. The summary above reflects her established legislative record and stated priorities from official sources. Identity is confirmed as the correct person by the match on Michigan, the 21st House District, Oakland County, Novi, and Democratic affiliation. Note: her office\\\'s name suggests she is the incumbent, contrary to the \\\"incumbent: unknown/no\\\" field provided.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(114,266,'Lisa McIntyre','D','https://www.mcintyreformichigan.com/','info@mcintyreformichigan.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Lisa McIntyre is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, District 22, in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district covers Northville, Plymouth, and western Livonia in Wayne County. The seat is open because the incumbent, Rep. Matt Koleszar, is reported to be running for the state Senate.\n\nMcIntyre has served on the Northville Public Schools Board of Education, to which she was elected in 2020, including a role as board treasurer. By profession she is a clinical mental health counselor with roughly 30 years of experience, with much of her work focused on youth and families. According to her own account, she ran for school board to help address a growing youth mental health crisis, to build more inclusive school environments, and to strengthen safety and security in schools.\n\nHer state House campaign frames its platform around the idea that \\\"hard work should earn a living wage, a safe environment, and healthcare people can afford,\\\" and she describes a goal of building \\\"a Michigan that is safe, prosperous, and works for every family.\\\" Her stated priorities emphasize fair wages, affordable and accessible healthcare, community safety, environmental protection, and education. Her campaign website references an endorsements section, but specific endorsers were not confirmed in the sources reviewed.\n\nNote: Lisa McIntyre is a relatively common name. Identity here is confirmed by the matching office (Michigan House District 22), geography (Northville/Plymouth/Livonia), her documented Northville school board service, and her dedicated 2026 campaign website. No public campaign phone number was found; the campaign contact email is info@mcintyreformichigan.com.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/69dda412dbcc587824c72024/53863bae-c501-44ef-8627-52b1a9dfa63f/McIntyre%2CLisa_112+%281%29.jpg'),(115,267,'Jason Morgan','D','https://www.votejasonmorgan.com/','votejasonmorgan@gmail.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jason Morgan is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 23rd District, which covers the Ann Arbor area in Washtenaw County. He first assumed office on January 1, 2023, and won reelection in the November 2024 general election. He is running for reelection in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary.\n\nMorgan grew up in a small town in Northern Michigan in a working-class family; he describes his father as a commercial fisherman and his mother as a school lunch aide. Before serving in the state Legislature, he served as a Washtenaw County Commissioner, first elected in 2016 and reelected twice. In 2019, he became the county\\\'s first openly LGBTQ+ chair of the Board of Commissioners.\n\nHis campaign platform emphasizes progressive priorities, including strengthening public schools, protecting Michigan\\\'s natural resources, ensuring access to quality health care, investing in modern infrastructure, and defending voting rights. He frames his mission as fighting for \\\"a Michigan that works for everybody,\\\" regardless of race, gender, sexual orientation, gender identity, disability status, or socioeconomic status.\n\nHis campaign contact email is votejasonmorgan@gmail.com, and his listed campaign address is 2860 Gladstone Avenue, Ann Arbor, MI 48104. No public campaign phone number was found on his website.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/065759_8a162f53df5a45658796573387f62995~mv2.jpg'),(116,268,'Ranjeev Puri','D','https://www.voteranjeev.com/','Ranjeev@VoteRanjeev.com','(734) 604-8775','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Ranjeev Puri is the incumbent Democratic Michigan State Representative for House District 24, which represents Canton, Belleville, and Van Buren Township in Wayne County. He is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. Puri was first elected to the Michigan House in 2020 and won re-election in 2022 and 2024. In November 2024, he was chosen by his Democratic colleagues to serve as House Democratic Leader for the 2025-2026 term of the 103rd Michigan Legislature.\n\nPuri describes himself as the son of immigrants, with a mother who worked as a Registered Nurse and a father who was an Engineer. He holds an MBA and previously worked in the automotive industry with the Big Three automakers, as well as serving in the Obama administration. He is a Canton homeowner and a father of three sons.\n\nHis campaign platform centers on protecting Michigan\\\'s automotive industry and manufacturing jobs, investing in high-quality public education across all communities regardless of zip code, environmental protection including clean water and air, and infrastructure development with expanded regional transit. He frames his candidacy around the theme \\\"My family\\\'s American Dream is the story of Michigan,\\\" emphasizing inclusion, equity, and building solutions that work for all Michigan residents while keeping jobs and economic strength within the state.\n\nHis campaign mailing address is PO Box 871007, Canton, MI 48187. As of campaign finance reporting through March 31, 2026, his committee reported activity consistent with an active 2026 re-election effort.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d3cf8b93d78b80001676ada/1574304638076-ACNG792CY0O672H8CX7V/_29A1989.jpg'),(117,269,'Peter Herzberg','D','https://votepeterherzberg.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Peter Herzberg is the Democratic incumbent state representative for Michigan\\\'s 25th House District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. He first assumed office on April 30, 2024 after a special election and won a full term in the November 2024 general election, defeating Josh Powell. The 25th District covers parts of Westland (his home city), Wayne, NW Dearborn Heights, and portions of Canton in Wayne County.\n\nBefore serving in the state legislature, Herzberg was a member of the Westland City Council, on which he served beginning in 2016. He is a graduate of John Glenn High School and holds a bachelor\\\'s degree in finance from Wayne State University, giving him a local background in the community he represents.\n\nAccording to his campaign materials, Herzberg\\\'s district priorities include securing adequate and reliable funding for Michigan\\\'s public schools, protecting reproductive health freedom and the right of individuals to make their own health care decisions, and advocating for working families in the 25th District. As a sitting legislator he has been tracked by groups such as the Michigan League of Conservation Voters on environmental and conservation issues.\n\nHerzberg campaigns as a locally rooted Democrat focused on education funding, working-class economic concerns, and personal freedoms. Additional contact details (campaign phone and email) were not publicly listed on his campaign website, which directs supporters to a contact form and lists a Westland mailing address. This summary is a best-effort synthesis of his official legislative page, campaign website, and Ballotpedia; specific endorsements were not confirmed and are not claimed here.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://votepeterherzberg.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/signimage.jpg'),(118,270,'Dylan Wegela','D','https://www.dylanwegela.com/','wegela.dylan@gmail.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Dylan Wegela is the Democratic incumbent state representative for Michigan\\\'s 26th House District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. He has served in the Michigan House of Representatives since 2023 and was re-elected in 2024. The 26th District includes the Garden City/Wayne County area.\n\nWegela identifies as a democratic socialist and is a former public school teacher with roughly 7.5 years of classroom experience in Arizona, Michigan, and South Korea. He served as a teacher union president and was involved in organizing a 2018 teacher strike that, according to his campaign, helped secure increased school funding. His campaign emphasizes grassroots organizing and working-class movements under the message \\\"Together WE Will\\\" and the theme that \\\"a better world is possible, but only if we fight for it.\\\"\n\nHis stated platform priorities include:\n- Healthcare: enacting \\\"Medicare for All\\\" universal healthcare legislation.\n- Workers\\\' rights: expanding collective bargaining protections and raising the minimum wage to $30 per hour by 2030.\n- Tax reform: progressive taxation to fund education and infrastructure.\n- Community investment: expanding affordable housing and public transportation.\n- Corporate accountability: removing corporate influence from politics and regulating artificial intelligence and AI data centers.\n- Civil rights: defending voting rights and opposing what his campaign describes as fascist policies.\n\nHis campaign committee is \\\"People for Dylan Wegela,\\\" with a campaign address listed as P.O. Box 346, Garden City, MI 48135/48136. A publicly listed campaign email is wegela.dylan@gmail.com. No public campaign phone number was found.\n\nIdentity confirmed: the campaign site, the Michigan House Democrats official page, Ballotpedia, and Wikipedia all consistently identify Dylan Wegela as the Democratic representative for Michigan\\\'s 26th House District in the Garden City/Wayne County area, matching the candidate record.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/69778f6a9605b422d7b9a676/45d2c178-fb53-4a4c-b264-8534220f4832/IMG_9354.JPG'),(119,271,'Jaime Churches','D','https://www.jaimechurches.com/','jaime@jaimechurches.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jaime Churches is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in House District 27 in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district covers the Downriver Wayne County communities of Gibraltar, Grosse Ile, Trenton, Riverview, Wyandotte (her listed city), and part of Southgate.\n\nChurches is a career educator, having taught for roughly ten years across multiple Downriver school districts, and currently teaches fifth grade. She has been active in organized labor, serving as a vice president within the Michigan Education Association (MEA), and identifies as a teacher and union leader.\n\nShe is a former member of the Michigan House of Representatives, having first won the District 27 seat in 2022 (with about 50.8% of the vote) and served beginning in January 2023. She narrowly lost reelection in 2024 by roughly four points. In 2026 she is running to reclaim the seat, which is regarded by Democratic groups (including the DLCC and Michigan Democratic Party) as a key flip opportunity in their effort to retake a House majority.\n\nAmong the accomplishments she highlights from her prior term is securing approximately $20 million for repairs to the Grosse Ile free bridge. Her platform emphasizes public education and support for educators, workers\\\' rights, clean energy, and civil rights protections. State campaign-finance data referenced in coverage indicated total contributions of about $11,350 as of March 31, 2026, in the early phase of her campaign.\n\nHer official campaign website is jaimechurches.com, and her listed campaign contact email is jaime@jaimechurches.com. No public campaign phone number was found.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/6101dc1a09bece69014087ae/dfdb9695-2407-4e6b-9135-3376aabb92f0/bench+photo.jpg'),(120,272,'Sherry A. Berecz','D','','supervisor@brownstown-mi.org','734-675-0071','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Sherry A. Berecz is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 28th District in the August 4, 2026 primary. She lives in Brownstown Township in Wayne County and is a longtime local official.\n\nBerecz currently serves as Brownstown Charter Township Supervisor and has represented Brownstown residents in public office for over 25 years. Her local government record includes serving as Township Clerk for 16 years (2000-2016) and being elected to the Board of Trustees in 2020 before becoming Supervisor. She is a lifelong Downriver resident who graduated from Woodhaven High School, earned an English degree from Madonna University, and completed a Master\\\'s in Public Administration (with a focus on state and local government) from Central Michigan University in 2019.\n\nHer professional career began in 1991 as Alternative Work Force Department director with the Wayne County Department of Corrections. As a township official, she has emphasized maintaining one of Wayne County\\\'s lowest tax rates while supporting business expansion and manufacturing job growth. Her community involvement includes membership in the Wayne County Women\\\'s Commission, past presidency of the Woodhaven-Brownstown Rotary Club, and service as a school board member at Gabriel Richard High School.\n\nBerecz has prior experience seeking state legislative office, having been a 2016 Democratic candidate for a Michigan House district (reported as District 23 under the prior district map).\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located in this research. A \\\"Sherry Berecz for Trustee\\\" Facebook page exists from a prior local campaign, but no current 2026 state-representative campaign site, platform document, or endorsement list was found, so specific 2026 policy priorities could not be confirmed beyond her established record as a local fiscal-conservative-leaning township administrator. The phone and email listed above are her official Brownstown Township Supervisor office contacts (public-facing), not a confirmed campaign line.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.brownstown-mi.org/_newsite_setup/membersimages/Berecz (1).jpg'),(121,273,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(122,275,'Omar G. Ferdin','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Omar G. Ferdin is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 30th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary election. He is listed on the Monroe County, Michigan unofficial 2026 primary candidate list with a residence in Monroe. Beyond his official candidate filing, very little public information is available online about Ferdin: no campaign website, contact details, biography, platform, or endorsements could be located through public web searches as of this research. The 30th District covers part of the Monroe area in southeast Michigan. No further verified details about his background, occupation, or campaign priorities were found. This is a brief factual summary reflecting the limited information currently available; the candidate appears to have minimal online or media presence at this stage of the race.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(123,276,'Shannon Dare Wayne','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Shannon Dare Wayne is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 31st District, running in the August 4, 2026 primary. She is a resident of Milan and currently serves on the Milan City Council, having previously run for a Milan City Council At-large seat in 2025. Her local civic roles have included Chairperson of the Milan Beautification Commission and Secretary of Milan\\\'s Downtown Development Authority / Milan Main Street.\n\nProfessionally, Wayne has worked for Ford Motor Company for over 20 years, serving as a Supervisor in Global Product Planning & Strategy, with prior experience in production supervision, process engineering, and product development. She completed Ford\\\'s Manufacturing Leadership Program and participated in UAW-Ford negotiations in 2007. She holds a Ph.D. in Industrial Engineering and an M.S. in Manufacturing Engineering from Wayne State University, along with a B.S. in Industrial Management and M.S. in Industrial Operations from Lawrence Technological University, and ASQ certifications as a Certified Manager of Quality and Certified Quality Auditor.\n\nAccording to her campaign messaging, her stated priorities include lowering costs, investing in public schools, and delivering for working families. She is seeking the seat currently held by Rep. Reggie Miller (D-Van Buren Township), who is not seeking reelection; reporting indicates Wayne received Miller\\\'s endorsement (noted from campaign/news sources rather than independently verified here).\n\nNote on contact info: No dedicated campaign website was located. The campaign maintains a Facebook presence (\\\"Shannon Dare Wayne for State Representative\\\") and an ActBlue donation page (secure.actblue.com/donate/shannon-wayne-1). No public campaign phone, email, or direct headshot image URL was found in available sources.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(124,277,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(125,278,'Morgan Foreman','D','https://www.forwardwithforeman.com/','MorganForeman@house.mi.gov','(517) 373-0820','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Morgan Foreman is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 33rd House District, which covers Ann Arbor, Saline, and the townships of Bridgewater, Saline, York, Pittsfield, Lodi, and Scio in Washtenaw County. She is running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary under the campaign banner \\\"Forward with Foreman.\\\"\n\nForeman first won the District 33 seat in 2024, defeating Rima Mohammad in the Democratic primary and winning the November general election. She assumed office on January 1, 2025. A longtime community organizer and Ann Arbor resident, Foreman describes herself as coming from a working-class background. Before running for office, she spent her career working in community spaces across Washtenaw County and served roughly three years as legislative staff (Director of Constituent Services) for State Representative Felicia Brabec, the prior holder of the 33rd District seat, in Lansing.\n\nHer stated priorities have centered on improving the daily lives of constituents through local advocacy and responsive policy, with particular emphasis on consumer protection (notably around utility issues), support for seniors, and mental health care. Her campaign maintains an active presence on Facebook, Twitter/X, Instagram, and TikTok under the handle @forwardwithforeman, and accepts donations via ActBlue.\n\nIn her initial 2024 bid she was endorsed by Rep. Felicia Brabec (D-33) and Washtenaw County Commissioner and former State Representative Yousef Rabhi. Her campaign address is listed as 2860 Gladstone Ave., Ann Arbor, MI 48104.\n\nNote on contact details: the phone number and email provided here are Foreman\\\'s official Michigan House legislative office line and government email, as her campaign website does not publish a separate campaign phone or email; campaign contact is primarily handled through her social media channels and website contact form. The endorsements listed are from her 2024 campaign; any updated 2026 endorsements were not confirmed in the sources reviewed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/61f9c854a8d35679d6fc612c/1ba74cd5-ab6d-475c-acaf-9677adb0cd58/IMG_8016-2.jpg'),(126,279,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(127,280,'Jeff Cooley','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jeff Cooley is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 35th District, seeking a two-year term in the August 4, 2026 primary. The 35th District covers the Hillsdale area of southern Michigan, a predominantly rural and Republican-leaning region. Beyond his party affiliation, candidacy, and the office sought, little public campaign information could be located online. No official campaign website, public contact phone, email, or candidate headshot was found through web searches. He does not appear to have an established public profile, news coverage, or detailed platform statement available as of this research. This is consistent with a first-time or lower-profile candidate filing for a state legislative seat in a smaller county. Voters seeking more information may consult the Michigan Bureau of Elections official candidate listing, the Hillsdale County Clerk\\\'s candidate filings, or the Hillsdale County Democratic Party. Note: identity could not be fully confirmed against a verified candidate profile, and the common name \\\"Jeff/Jeffrey Cooley\\\" returns multiple unrelated individuals; this summary is limited and factual due to the scarcity of available sources.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(128,281,'Cole Slaski','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Cole Slaski is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 36th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary election. The 36th District includes the Three Rivers area in southwest Michigan (St. Joseph County region). Based on available information, Slaski filed to seek the two-year term seat. The district is currently represented by Republican Steve Carra of Three Rivers, who defeated Democrat Erin Schultes in 2024, making the 36th a Republican-leaning seat that Slaski would be challenging.\n\nBeyond the candidate\\\'s filing with the Michigan Bureau of Elections, very little public information was found. No campaign website, official campaign social media account, candidate biography, platform statement, or endorsements could be located through web searches. No public campaign phone number, email address, or headshot photo was found.\n\nThis is a best-effort factual summary; substantive details about Slaski\\\'s background, professional history, prior public service, policy priorities, or reasons for running were not available in the sources searched. Voters seeking more information may wish to consult the Michigan Bureau of Elections candidate listing, the St. Joseph County Clerk\\\'s office, or local news outlets such as Watershed Voice as the 2026 primary approaches and campaign materials become available.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(129,282,'Angela M. Jones','D','https://electangelajonescom.wordpress.com/','hello@electangelajones.com','(269) 235-9656','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Angela Jones is a Democratic candidate for Michigan House of Representatives, District 37, in the August 4, 2026 primary. She is a resident of Niles, Michigan, in the district that covers parts of Berrien and Cass counties, including Niles, Buchanan, and Dowagiac. Jones previously ran for the same seat in 2024, winning the Democratic primary on August 6, 2024, before losing the general election on November 5, 2024, to Republican incumbent Brad Paquette. She is again challenging for the seat in 2026.\n\nHer campaign platform centers on three main priorities. First, labor and workers\\\' rights, which she describes as central to ensuring a fair and just society and protecting the dignity of the workforce. Second, protecting agriculture in Southwest Michigan, emphasizing the economic importance of the region\\\'s farming sector and its role in preserving local identity and natural resources. Third, equity, advocating for fair and equal access to healthcare, education, and economic security for all residents of Southwest Michigan.\n\nJones maintains an active campaign presence, including a campaign website and Instagram account (@electangelajones). Her campaign lists a contact phone of (269) 235-9656, an email of hello@electangelajones.com, and a mailing address of PO Box 135, Niles, MI 49120. The Michigan Democratic Party and a Blue Voter Guide page reference endorsements for her candidacy, though specific endorsers were not confirmed in the sources reviewed here. Detailed biographical information such as education and prior professional background was not available in the sources accessed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://electangelajonescom.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/img_0941.jpeg'),(130,283,'Joey Andrews','D','https://andrewsformichigan.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Joey Andrews is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 38th House District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district spans the Lake Michigan shoreline across parts of Berrien, Van Buren, and Allegan counties. Andrews lives in St. Joseph and is a fourth-generation small business owner and attorney. He earned dual bachelor\\\'s degrees in History and Music and a law degree from Wayne State University, and is credited with revitalizing his family business during the Great Recession.\n\nAndrews was first elected in 2022 and won re-election in November 2024, defeating Republican Kevin Whiteford. He is currently serving in the Michigan House Democratic caucus.\n\nHis campaign platform emphasizes: supporting the Palisades Nuclear Energy Project restart and related economic development along the shoreline; addressing the housing supply and short-term rental issues affecting lakeshore communities; shoreline erosion protection and coastal preservation; defending reproductive rights and personal medical freedom; and worker protections, including his work to repeal Michigan\\\'s \\\"Right to Work\\\" laws and advance paid family and medical leave and prevailing wage. His campaign site highlights an endorsement from UNITE HERE Local 24, a hospitality workers union.\n\nHis listed campaign mailing address is 1288 Vineland Rd, St. Joseph, MI 49085. No public campaign phone number or email was found on his campaign website. Identity is confirmed as the correct candidate: Michigan, 38th District, State Representative, Democratic, based in St. Joseph, matching all provided details.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://andrewsformichigan.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/joey_home.jpg'),(131,284,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(132,286,'Matt Longjohn','D','https://mattlongjohn.com/','info@mattlongjohn.com','269-290-1263','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Matt Longjohn (Dr. Matt Longjohn, MD) is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 40th House District, which includes Portage and Oshtemo and Texas Townships in Kalamazoo County. He is seeking reelection in 2026 to a second two-year term, having announced his campaign in early January 2026 after roughly twelve months in office.\n\nA physician by training, Longjohn is described as the only physician serving in the Michigan Legislature and brings more than 25 years of experience in medicine, public health, policy development, coalition building, nonprofit management, and small business ownership. In his first term he served on the Appropriations Committee—noted as the only freshman Democrat on that committee—with assignments on the Higher Education and Human Services subcommittees.\n\nAccording to his campaign and news coverage, his legislative work has focused on lowering prescription drug costs, Michigan\\\'s immunization policies, gun violence prevention, and promoting primary care medical careers. His stated reason for running again is to return to Lansing to continue working on issues that matter most to residents of the 40th District and to earn the continued support of voters in Portage, Oshtemo, and Texas Townships.\n\nNote: This is the same Matt Longjohn who was the 2018 Democratic nominee for Michigan\\\'s then-6th Congressional District. Campaign contact details (info@mattlongjohn.com; 269-290-1263; PO Box 1404, Portage, MI 49081) were drawn from search-result summaries of his campaign site; the campaign homepage rendered with minimal extractable content, so a direct headshot image URL was not captured. No additional specific endorsements were located in the sources reviewed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(133,287,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(134,288,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(135,289,'Alan Swank','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Alan Swank is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, District 43, in the August 4, 2026 primary election. According to official Michigan candidate filing records, he filed for the seat on December 12, 2025, listing an address (PO Box 364) in Delton, Michigan (49046). The seat is a two-year term with one position. Michigan\\\'s 43rd House District covers an area in the southwest/central part of the state.\n\nBeyond the official candidate filing, very little public information about this candidate is currently available online. No 2026 campaign website, campaign social media presence, public contact phone number, email address, or candidate headshot could be located through web searches. No published platform, policy priorities, endorsements, or biographical details have been found in news coverage or candidate questionnaires as of the research date.\n\nThis is a factual summary based primarily on state and county candidate-listing records; specifics about his background, qualifications, or campaign positions could not be verified and are therefore not included. Confidence that this is the correct individual is moderate: the Democratic Party affiliation, District 43, and Delton location match the provided candidate details, but no independent biographical source was found to further confirm identity.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(136,290,'Jim Haadsma','D','https://haadsmaformichigan.com/','info@haadsmaformichigan.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jim Haadsma is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 44th District, which covers northern Calhoun County including Battle Creek. He is seeking the seat in the August 4, 2026 primary, in which he is reportedly running unopposed on the Democratic side, setting up a likely November 2026 general-election rematch against Republican incumbent Rep. Steve Frisbie.\n\nHaadsma is a longtime Battle Creek resident, having lived in the city for nearly four decades after originally hailing from Muskegon. He spent 38 years practicing labor law. He previously served as the State Representative for District 44 from 2019 to 2024 before narrowly losing the November 2024 election to Frisbie by 79 votes following a recount. He announced his 2026 comeback bid at an event in downtown Battle Creek.\n\nHis campaign platform emphasizes economic development and expanding access to well-paying jobs that help families build financial security; reinvesting in public education, including adequate school resources and competitive teacher compensation; and healthcare access, including continued Medicaid expansion. In announcing his campaign, he also cited priorities such as restoring steady, competent leadership, standing up for workers, fixing roads and infrastructure, protecting reproductive freedom, and ensuring Calhoun County has a representative who delivers results in Lansing. He frames his candidacy around securing fair treatment and equal opportunity for working families and building on his prior legislative record.\n\nThe 44th District contest is considered competitive and potentially pivotal to control of the Michigan House. No specific endorsements were listed on his campaign website.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://haadsmaformichigan.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/JHHeadshot2Square@0.25x.jpg'),(137,291,'Randy Davis','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Randy Davis is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 45th District in the August 4, 2026 primary. According to official county candidate listings (Kalamazoo and Calhoun counties), he resides at 576 Lyon Lake Rd, Marshall, MI 49068, and filed his candidacy on March 10, 2026 by paying the $100 filing fee. The 45th House district covers portions of Calhoun, Kalamazoo, and Jackson counties in south-central Michigan.\n\nVery little public campaign material was found online for this candidate. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, public contact phone number, public campaign email address, or candidate headshot could be located through web searches. A separate social-media reference to a \\\"Dr. Randy Davis, Superintendent of Marshall Public Schools\\\" appears in search results, but it could not be confirmed that this is the same person as the State Representative candidate, so no biographical claims based on that reference are included here.\n\nBeyond confirming his party (Democratic), district (45), city of residence (Marshall), and filing details, no platform, priorities, endorsements, prior offices held, or stated reasons for running were found in available sources. This summary is intentionally limited to verified, factual details from official candidate-listing documents; no additional claims have been fabricated. Voters seeking more information may consult the Michigan Secretary of State voter information portal (mi.gov/vote) or the county clerk candidate listings closer to the election.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(138,292,'Jan Maino','D','https://mainoformichigan.com/','info@mainoformichigan.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jan Maino is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 46th District, running in the August 4, 2026 primary. Based in Jackson, she has lived in the area for over 50 years. She is a licensed social worker who has worked as a therapist and nonprofit executive, building a career focused on direct service to families and community leadership. She has served on a local school board (reported as the East Jackson school board) and has been active in community volunteer work.\n\nHer campaign platform, \\\"Service. Solutions. People First,\\\" centers on practical, family-focused priorities: lowering everyday costs for families, strengthening public schools, expanding access to mental health care, and creating good-paying jobs. She frames her candidacy around bringing experience, dedication, and proven leadership to the district, with a stated goal of making \\\"life work better for families in Jackson.\\\"\n\nNote on context: the 46th District seat has been held by Democratic incumbent Carrie Rheingans, so Maino may be running in a contested Democratic primary; this should be verified against final filing lists. No endorsements were listed on her campaign website at the time of research.\n\nContact for the campaign is available by email (info@mainoformichigan.com) and through a mailing address (PO Box 1285, Jackson, MI 49204); no public phone number was listed. The campaign maintains Facebook, X/Twitter, and Instagram (@janmainoformichigan) accounts.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://mainoformichigan.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/P1123479-scaled.jpg'),(139,293,'Carrie A. Rheingans','D','https://www.carrierheingans.com','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Carrie A. Rheingans (Democratic) is the incumbent Michigan State Representative for the 47th House District and is running for re-election in 2026. The district spans parts of Washtenaw and Jackson counties, including portions of Ann Arbor, Dexter, Scio Township, Manchester, and surrounding communities. She was first elected in 2022 and won re-election in November 2024, defeating Teresa Spiegelberg and Aaron Wright in the general election.\n\nRheingans is a health policy expert, educator, and community organizer. She holds three degrees from the University of Michigan: a bachelor of science, a Master of Public Health, and a Master of Social Work. Her professional background centers on improving health outcomes and reducing health disparities through systems-level work bringing organizations and communities together.\n\nHealthcare access is the signature issue of her platform; her campaign highlights advocacy for \\\"MiCare,\\\" a proposal for universal healthcare coverage in Michigan. Her broader record and priorities reflect a progressive agenda. Her campaign and record cite endorsements and ratings including a 100% rating from the Michigan League of Conservation Voters, a \\\"Gun Sense Candidate\\\" designation from Moms Demand Action, and support from pro-choice organizations.\n\nContact information for the campaign was limited online; the campaign lists a mailing address of P.O. Box 3241, Ann Arbor, MI 48106, and accepts contributions via ActBlue, volunteer sign-ups, yard sign requests, and newsletter subscriptions through carrierheingans.com. No direct campaign phone or email and no standalone direct-link headshot image file were found on the public pages reviewed. Identity is confirmed with high confidence based on the match of party, office, district (47), and city (Ann Arbor).\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(140,294,'Jennifer A. Conlin','D','https://www.conlinforstaterep.com/','info@conlinforstaterep.com','734-904-6389','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jennifer A. Conlin is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan House District 48, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district covers Ann Arbor and surrounding Washtenaw and Livingston County townships, including Waterloo, Lyndon, Dexter, Genoa, Hamburg, Webster, Northfield, and Ann Arbor townships, as well as parts of Pinckney and the city of Ann Arbor. She was first elected in 2022.\n\nA lifelong Washtenaw County resident, Conlin spent decades working as a journalist, including roughly twelve years covering Michigan topics such as small business, tourism, healthcare, arts and culture, and economic development. She describes herself as a wife, mother, daughter, and caregiver, with family members who have served in city, county, and state government. She has said her journalism career, which involved meeting and sharing the stories of people around the world, shaped her approach to public service.\n\nIn the legislature, Conlin has worked on legislation related to the criminal justice system, children\\\'s services, gun safety, environmental protection, highways, and healthcare. Her stated campaign priorities include creating good-paying jobs, improving education, protecting the environment, expanding access to affordable healthcare, and safeguarding the rights of all Michiganders.\n\nCampaign finance records (via Transparency USA) indicate active fundraising for the 2026 cycle, with roughly $113,724 in total contributions and $162,070 in total expenditures reported as of December 31, 2025. No specific endorsement list was identified in the sources reviewed for this summary.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/437a5b_1273cbb8a0d445e5a35febcfe713a60a~mv2.jpg/v1/crop/x_1869,y_0,w_4518,h_5504/fill/w_339,h_413,al_c,q_80,usm_0.66_1.00_0.01,enc_avif,quality_auto/CD167-0542.jpg'),(141,295,'Dan Pelchat','D','https://danpelchat.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Dan Pelchat is the Democratic candidate for Michigan House of Representatives District 49 in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is a lifelong resident of the district, which includes the city of Brighton plus Brighton and Green Oak townships in Livingston County, and Walled Lake, Wixom, Novi, and parts of Commerce and Lyon townships in Oakland County. He has spent his career working in local public education, serving as an IT technician for South Lyon Community Schools since 1998.\n\nPelchat is best known for his public service as Mayor of South Lyon. He was first elected mayor in 2017 after winning a write-in campaign in a crowded field, and was re-elected twice before choosing not to seek another term in 2023. He launched his 2026 House campaign as the Democratic entrant for the 49th District seat and held a campaign kickoff fundraiser in spring 2026 in Brighton.\n\nHis campaign platform emphasizes protecting democratic values and defending democracy, supporting strong public schools and improving education for children and adults, investing in infrastructure and local communities, ensuring economic opportunity for working families, protecting women\\\'s rights, and protecting Michigan\\\'s environment. He frames his candidacy around the district\\\'s growing and diversifying population, arguing it needs representation that understands local residents, their challenges, and their shared opportunities.\n\nAccording to his campaign materials, Pelchat has received endorsements from former South Lyon DDA/Economic Development Director Bob Donohue Jr. and former South Lyon Fire Chief Robert Vogel, both of whom cited his leadership during his time as mayor.\n\nNo public campaign phone number or email was listed on his official website; the site provides a mailing address (South Lyon, MI) and a contact form. This summary is synthesized from his campaign website and local Democratic Party reporting on his entry into the race.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://danpelchat.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/Copy-of-Dan-Pelchat.png'),(142,297,'Cassie Canedo','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Cassie Canedo is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 50th House District, filing to compete in the August 4, 2026 primary election. She is listed as residing in Fowlerville, in Livingston County, and filed her candidacy with Livingston County for the two-year term seat. Beyond the official candidate filing record, very little public information about Canedo or her campaign could be located online as of June 2026. No campaign website, social media presence, candidate biography, platform statement, or endorsement information was found in available public sources. As a result, details about her background, professional experience, policy priorities, or reasons for running are not available from the sources reviewed. This is a brief factual summary; a fuller profile would require direct campaign materials or local Livingston County news coverage that has not yet been published or indexed. Voters seeking authoritative confirmation of her filing can consult the Livingston County Elections Division candidate filing lists for the 2026 cycle.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(143,298,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(144,299,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(145,300,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(146,301,'Sarah Pounds','D','https://electsarahpounds.com/','Campaign@ElectSarahPounds.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Sarah B. Pounds is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 54th House District in the August 4, 2026 primary. A resident of Orion Township (Lake Orion area) in Oakland County, she has lived there for about a decade with her husband Nate and their four daughters. She graduated from Clarkston High School and earned a bachelor\\\'s degree in History and a Paralegal Certificate from Oakland University. Pounds worked as a paralegal for roughly 15 years, specializing in construction and surety law, before transitioning toward community service and civic involvement around 2020.\n\nIn August 2020 she was elected Precinct Delegate for Orion Township\\\'s 6th Precinct. According to her campaign, she has served on several Oakland County boards and chairs a nonprofit focused on addressing the local housing crisis.\n\nHer campaign platform centers on three core themes: strong public schools (including school safety and support for colleges and universities), good jobs and economic opportunity (investing in small businesses and the workforce), and affordable communities (creating pathways to homeownership for working families). She also emphasizes working across the aisle and bringing transparency to government. She describes her motivation as inspired by seeing neighbors come together to support one another, which prompted her shift from a legal career to public service.\n\nNote on disambiguation: the \\\"About\\\" page of her campaign site contains some legacy text referring to a run for Oakland County Commissioner (6th District), but the campaign homepage, her LinkedIn profile (\\\"Candidate for Michigan State House District 54\\\"), and her social media accounts confirm her current 2026 candidacy is for State Representative in District 54. The 54th District covers the Lake Orion/Orion Township area of Oakland County, consistent with the candidate record.\n\nPublic contact is via email (Campaign@ElectSarahPounds.com) and a mailing address of PO Box 80086, Rochester, MI 48308. No campaign phone number was found online.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/62ca0f9eac2ee66ef23fff61/8ff6e59e-4559-4550-b042-28eb9a309070/sarah-pounds.jpeg'),(147,302,'Alex Hawkins','D','https://www.alexhawkins.org/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Alex Hawkins is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in House District 55 in the August 4, 2026 primary, with the general election on November 3, 2026. The 55th District covers Rochester, Rochester Hills, and part of Oakland Township in Oakland County. Hawkins is running unopposed in the Democratic primary and is expected to face Republican incumbent Mark Tisdel in the general election. The district is considered a competitive battleground.\n\nHawkins is a Rochester-area native who grew up in Waterford Township, raised by his single mother. He cites his grandfather, a Vietnam veteran who served as a Florida state legislator, as an influence on his interest in public service. He is a U.S. Army veteran who served as an Explosive Ordnance Disposal (bomb disposal) technician for nearly nine years, and he remains an active National Guard EOD officer. He also serves as an Oakland County Sheriff\\\'s Office reserve deputy.\n\nAfter active duty, Hawkins worked as a congressional fellow for then-U.S. Rep. Elissa Slotkin, handling constituent services and veterans\\\' casework, and briefly worked in U.S. Sen. Gary Peters\\\' office. He has been completing a master\\\'s degree in public administration.\n\nThis is not his first run. Hawkins ran for the 55th state House seat in 2024 but lost the Democratic primary. In early 2025 he announced a campaign for Michigan\\\'s 10th Congressional District challenging U.S. Rep. John James, then pivoted back to the 55th state House race in September 2025.\n\nHis platform centers on strengthening public education (increased school funding, support for teachers, and expanded STEM, arts, and humanities curriculum), healthcare access, housing affordability, and government accountability. He has stated support for labor unions, opposition to local law enforcement ICE contracts, and opposition to Republican proposals to eliminate property taxes.\n\nReported endorsements include Planned Parenthood Advocates of Michigan, VoteVets, former Congressman Mark Schauer, U.S. Rep. Jason Crow, and Michigan state House Democrats.\n\nNote: A public campaign phone, email, and direct headshot image URL could not be confirmed because the official campaign website (alexhawkins.org) blocked automated retrieval; these may be available directly on the site.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(148,303,'Sharon MacDonell','D','https://www.electsharonmac.com/','electsharonmac@gmail.com','248-469-8112','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Sharon MacDonell is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 56th House District, which covers parts of Troy, Birmingham, Bloomfield Township, Clawson, and Royal Oak in Oakland County. First elected in 2022 and re-elected in 2024 (defeating Dave Kniffen), she is running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary.\n\nBackground: MacDonell was born in Bethpage, New York, moved to Michigan at age 8, and has lived in Troy for over two decades (a 32-year resident of District 56). She earned a B.A. in History from the University of Michigan and worked across broadcasting, automotive, journalism, marketing, and video production, including four years in Tokyo with a television production company. Diagnosed with rheumatoid arthritis as a child, she cites perseverance as a formative value.\n\nCivic and political record: Before holding office, MacDonell was a longtime grassroots organizer in Troy. She co-founded and led Troy Indivisible, served as chair of the Troy Democratic Club, and founded the \\\"Keep Troy Strong\\\" blog. She is widely associated with the 2010-2012 effort to save the Troy Public Library from closure and helped lead a successful 2012 recall of Troy\\\'s mayor. She has also pressed for government transparency, including in a case involving a city manager accused of embezzlement and bribery.\n\nPlatform and priorities: Her campaign frames her work around building \\\"a safer, more affordable future,\\\" emphasizing community-focused, grassroots representation. As a sitting House Democrat she aligns with the caucus on issues affecting her suburban Oakland County district.\n\nContact for her 2026 campaign is via electsharonmac.com, email electsharonmac@gmail.com, phone 248-469-8112, and mailing address P.O. Box 99221, Troy, MI 48099. (Note: a search snippet listed an alternate phone of 248-397-5403; the number above is taken directly from her current campaign site.) No direct headshot image URL was captured from the campaign site; her official portrait is available on the Michigan House Democrats site.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(149,304,'Tom Turner','D','https://www.turner4mi.com','tom@turner4mi.com','(248) 560-7129','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Tom Turner is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 57th House District, running in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district covers portions of Sterling Heights, Troy, and Madison Heights and is currently held by Republican incumbent Rep. Thomas Kuhn (R-Troy). According to reporting, Turner faces no primary challenger and is expected to advance to a general-election matchup against Kuhn.\n\nTurner is a lifelong Michigan resident, attorney, and U.S. Army veteran who currently serves in the Army Reserves. He earned a law degree from the University of Michigan and worked as a lawyer before accepting a commission in the U.S. Army as a judge advocate (JAG officer) in 2019. According to news coverage, he announced his campaign after leaving a military position over disagreements with Trump administration policies at the Department of Defense.\n\nHis campaign centers on economic quality of life for working families, with the message that \\\"Every Michigander deserves a good quality of life that they can afford.\\\" He frames himself as part of a new generation of leadership and describes himself as \\\"a fighter for Michigan\\\'s working families,\\\" emphasizing showing up, listening, and advocating for district residents. His public campaign materials do not list specific detailed policy planks or formal endorsements.\n\nContact information from his campaign site (turner4mi.com): email tom@turner4mi.com and phone (248) 560-7129.\n\nNote: Specific platform details beyond the general working-families economic message and named endorsements were not available in the sources reviewed; this summary reflects only what was found and avoids attributing claims not present in those sources.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/69a5e51b2cad430dcb353537/7c7ef055-8826-405a-a963-e07c0eb4853f/DSC01244_mobile_v3.jpg'),(150,305,'Katrina Manetta','D','https://katrinamanetta.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Katrina Manetta is the Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 58th District (Macomb County, covering much of Sterling Heights) in the 2026 election. A Macomb County native, she attended Utica schools and graduated from Oakland University. She has worked as a server for roughly eight years and describes herself as a community organizer who entered the race because she was tired of watching decisions about working families\\\' lives be made without people like them in the room.\n\nHer platform centers on affordability and the cost of living, lowering everyday costs, and holding monopoly utility companies accountable. On public safety, she supports funding for police, fire, and EMS while expanding mental health response and strengthening community-based approaches. Additional priorities include healthcare access and reducing prescription drug costs, protecting workers\\\' rights to bargain for better wages and benefits, government accountability and transparency, strong public schools and job training, civil rights, and infrastructure and clean energy development. Her campaign emphasizes being \\\"100% funded by people like you, not corporations and billionaires.\\\"\n\nShe has been endorsed by state Rep. Mai Xiong (D-Warren), as well as MI LIST and EMILYs List, organizations dedicated to electing Democratic, pro-choice candidates. In District 58, the reported field includes incumbent Republican Ron Robinson, making Manetta the Democratic challenger.\n\nHer campaign lists a mailing address of P.O. Box 180085, 8785 Hall Road, Utica, MI 48317, and directs supporters to a contact form on her website. No public campaign email, phone number, or direct headshot image URL was found on the site. Donations are accepted via ActBlue.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(151,306,'Jason Robbins','D','https://www.jason4mihouse.com','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jason Robbins is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 59th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary. The 59th District covers part of Macomb County, including Shelby Township, and is currently held by Republican incumbent Douglas Wozniak.\n\nRobbins appears to be running through the campaign website \\\"Jason 4 MI House\\\" (jason4mihouse.com), though the candidate\\\'s surname could not be fully verified from publicly indexed pages. According to that site\\\'s description, the candidate presents himself as a pastor, father, and military war veteran who was awarded a commendation for valor. He frames his campaign around serving the Michigan community \\\"with integrity and compassion\\\" and is running as a Democrat to unseat the Republican incumbent.\n\nThe platform described on the campaign materials emphasizes Christian values of fairness and justice, and lists priorities including LGBTQ rights, reproductive rights, support for small farms and rural/farm communities, economic development, and renewable energy. The campaign positions these stances as grounded in inclusivity and representation for the district.\n\nBeyond the campaign site, very little independent coverage of this specific candidate was found online as of mid-2026. No public campaign phone number, email address, or direct headshot image URL could be located through web searches. As an early-cycle, non-incumbent legislative candidate, his online footprint is limited, and major nonpartisan trackers (e.g., Ballotpedia\\\'s District 59 page) had not yet published a detailed candidate profile at the time of research.\n\nNote on identity confidence: the connection between the name \\\"Jason Robbins\\\" (as filed with Macomb County for the 59th District) and the jason4mihouse.com website is inferred from a strong match of first name, party (Democrat), district (59), county (Macomb), and the stated goal of unseating the Republican incumbent. The website\\\'s \\\"About\\\" page was not directly accessible to confirm the exact surname, so this association is reported with medium confidence.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(152,308,'Amy Gray','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Amy Gray is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 60th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary election. The 60th District covers part of Macomb County. Beyond her appearance in Michigan\\\'s official 2026 candidate filings, very little public information about Gray could be located online. No campaign website, social media presence, contact information, headshot, or candidate biography was found through web searches. As of this research, no platform statements, endorsements, prior offices held, or background details have been published in accessible public sources. This is typical of a first-time or newly-filed candidate who has not yet established an online campaign presence ahead of the primary. The 60th District seat was most recently held by Republican Joseph Aragona, who won the 2024 general election; the Democratic nominee in 2024 was Shelly Fraley. Note: the limited search results make it difficult to fully confirm details specific to Amy Gray as distinct from others sharing this common name, so this summary is intentionally factual and minimal. Additional verification via the Macomb County Clerk\\\'s candidate listings or local Macomb County news coverage would be needed to confirm her platform and background.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(153,309,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(154,310,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(155,311,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(156,312,'Ken Heuvelman','D','https://heuvelman64th.com/','heuvelman64thdistrict@gmail.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Ken Heuvelman is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in District 64, seeking the seat in the August 4, 2026 primary. He resides in Lakeport (St. Clair County) with his partner Carrie and their two sons, and was born in 1982.\n\nHeuvelman is a Licensed Professional Counselor with more than a decade of experience in behavioral health and substance use treatment. He holds a bachelor\\\'s in Psychology from the University of Michigan–Flint, a master\\\'s in Psychology from Montana State University–Billings, and a master\\\'s in Clinical Mental Health Counseling from Walden University. Professionally, he has served as Substance Use Disorder Director for Region 10 PIHP (overseeing a four-county area), as a SUD Family Support Program Supervisor across the five-county Thumb region, and as coordinator of the Mobile Overdose/Outreach Response Team (MORT) with Port Huron Odyssey House. Earlier in his career, he worked as a radio broadcaster at WSAQ \\\"Q Country 107\\\" (2010–2014). In 2025 he was recognized as Certified Advanced Alcohol and Drug Counselor of the Year.\n\nHis campaign centers on behavioral health expansion and opioid crisis response, themes drawn directly from his professional work. According to his campaign materials, his MORT program contributed to reducing Port Huron overdoses from 102 in 2022 to 54 in 2023, distributed more than 5,300 naloxone kits, and secured $25,000 in MDHHS funding. He chaired the St. Clair County CSCB Substance Use workgroup (2019–2025). His campaign slogan is \\\"Leading the way with social and fiscal responsibility.\\\"\n\nHeuvelman previously ran for this same District 64 seat in 2024, finishing behind John Anter and Mathew Castillo in the Democratic primary held August 6, 2024. He is again running as a Democrat for the seat in 2026.\n\nCampaign contact is via email (heuvelman64thdistrict@gmail.com); donations are handled through ActBlue. No public campaign phone number was found. No endorsements were listed on his campaign site at the time of this research.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://i0.wp.com/heuvelman64th.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/64th-District-Headshot-2024-1.png'),(157,313,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(158,314,'Ned Zimmer','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Ned Zimmer is a Democratic candidate who filed to run for Michigan State Representative in the 66th District (a two-year term) in the August 4, 2026 primary election. He is listed with a residence in Oxford, Michigan. Michigan House District 66 is located in Oakland County and covers the Oxford and Lake Orion area in the northern part of the county.\n\nBeyond the official candidate filing record, no campaign website, contact information, candidate biography, platform, endorsements, or news coverage could be located through web searches. As a result, no details about his background, professional experience, prior offices held, or top priorities and platform positions are available at this time. This is a brief, factual summary because little public information about this candidate is currently online; the campaign may not yet have an established web or media presence ahead of the primary.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(159,315,'Leslie Getz','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Leslie Getz is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 67th District in the August 4, 2026 primary, as recorded in the Michigan Bureau of Elections official 2026 candidate listing. The 67th House District includes portions of Lapeer, Genesee, and Tuscola counties; Getz is listed with a Lapeer-area connection. The seat is a two-year term.\n\nVery little campaign-specific information about Getz is available online as of mid-2026. No official 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, campaign email, or candidate headshot could be located through web searches. A Lapeer, Michigan resident named Leslie Getz is the owner of Teacher\\\'s PET Resources LLC, an educational-materials and tutoring business serving teachers, students, and parents; this appears likely to be the same individual given the shared name and Lapeer location, but it could not be definitively confirmed as the candidate, and no campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements have been published in sources reviewed.\n\nBecause of the limited online footprint, this summary is intentionally brief and factual. Her candidacy is confirmed via the state\\\'s official filing record, but details about her background, platform, top priorities, and reasons for running were not found in available public sources and are not asserted here to avoid fabrication.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(160,316,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(161,317,'Jasper Ryan Martus','D','https://www.jaspermartus.com/','jasper@jaspermartus.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Jasper Martus is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 69th House District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. A lifelong Flushing, Michigan resident with family roots in Genesee County spanning more than a century, Martus was first elected in 2022 and won re-election in 2024. He is among the youngest members of the Michigan House.\n\nMartus graduated from Michigan State University\\\'s James Madison College with a degree in international relations and a minor in world religions. Early in his career he worked for then-Congressman Dan Kildee, helping constituents with federal benefits and veteran services, and later held legislative roles overseeing constituent services and drafting legislation in the Michigan House.\n\nThe 69th District covers Flushing and Flushing Township, Clayton Township, Clio, Flint Township, Mount Morris and Mount Morris Township, Swartz Creek, Montrose, and parts of Montrose Township and Vienna Township in Genesee County.\n\nIn the legislature, Martus has served as vice chairman of the Health and Human Services and the Labor and Economic Opportunity committees, where he has advanced mental health funding in schools and expanded healthcare access. He highlights support for repeal of the state\\\'s pension tax, an expanded Earned Income Tax Credit, repeal of \\\"Right to Work,\\\" codification of abortion access, and climate action among his record.\n\nHis stated ongoing priorities include enacting paid family and medical leave, lowering prescription drug costs, creating good-paying jobs, improving infrastructure, and reducing the influence of money in politics, framed around addressing decades of underinvestment in Genesee County. During his 2022 campaign he emphasized retail, door-to-door outreach, reporting having walked over 1,000 miles knocking on doors across the district.\n\nContact for his campaign is available via email at jasper@jaspermartus.com, with a mailing address of P.O. Box 165, Flushing, MI 48433. No public campaign phone number was found.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(162,319,'Cynthia R. Neeley','D','https://cynthianeeley.com/','cynthia@cynthianeeley.com','(810) 458-3936','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Cynthia Renay Neeley is a Democratic state representative for Michigan\\\'s 70th House District, which covers Flint and surrounding areas in Genesee County. She is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary as the incumbent. Neeley first won election to the Michigan House in a March 2020 special election (then representing the 34th District) and was reelected to the redrawn 70th District in 2022 and 2024, defeating primary and general-election challengers each cycle. She is married to Flint Mayor Sheldon Neeley.\n\nIn the Legislature, Neeley has served in a leadership role on tax policy and describes herself as a product of a union family. According to her campaign, she has introduced and co-sponsored more than 200 pieces of legislation and has secured millions of dollars in state and federal funding for her district. Her stated priorities include public education and support for teachers, labor and workplace protections (including healthcare access and prevailing wage), criminal justice and gun-violence reduction through bipartisan collaboration, community and economic investment, women\\\'s equality, protection of Medicare and Social Security, and budget accountability.\n\nVoters can reach her campaign at (810) 458-3936 or cynthia@cynthianeeley.com, and her campaign website is cynthianeeley.com. Identity is confirmed as the sitting 70th District representative from Flint/Genesee County; this is high confidence. (Note: a direct, verified headshot image URL could not be confirmed — the campaign site image found was a logo rather than a portrait — so headshot_url is left null.)\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(163,320,'Stephen Schlaack','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Stephen Schlaack is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 71st District in the August 4, 2026 primary. He lives in Owosso, in Shiawassee County, which falls within the 71st District. Schlaack was born in Owosso and earned a Bachelor of Arts from Alma College in 2012, double-majoring in Business Administration and Theatre Performance. In 2020 he completed an MBA with an emphasis in Supply Chain Management from the Eli Broad College of Business at Michigan State University. He works in industry, having relocated back to Michigan in 2022 after accepting a remote role with an Ann Arbor-based semiconductor manufacturer, and chose to make Owosso his home. According to his LinkedIn profile, he has also been involved with the Owosso Farmers Market. Schlaack has been active in local Democratic politics and has served as chairperson of the Shiawassee County Democratic Party. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone, email, or candidate headshot was located in public sources at the time of this research. Specific policy priorities, endorsements, and platform details for his 2026 State Representative campaign were not found online; this is a brief factual summary based on the limited public information available. Identity is confirmed via the consistent Owosso/Shiawassee County and local Democratic Party associations matching the 71st District.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(164,321,'Thomas Ryan','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','\'Thomas Ryan is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 72nd House District in the August 4, 2026 primary election. He filed his candidacy on February 19, 2026, and lists a residence in Holly, Michigan (Oakland County). Michigan\\\'s 72nd House District covers parts of Oakland and Genesee counties in the Holly/Fenton area.\n\nBeyond the basic filing record from the Michigan Bureau of Elections official 2026 primary candidate listing, little public information was found about this specific candidate. No campaign website, social media presence, public contact phone or email, candidate biography, platform/priorities statement, or headshot photo could be confirmed through available public sources at the time of research. A Ballotpedia stub page exists for \\\"Thomas Ryan (Michigan)\\\" but contained no substantive 2026 campaign content.\n\nNote: \\\"Thomas Ryan\\\" is a common name, and several unrelated public figures share it (including a Michigan attorney, a former U.S. Representative, and a Minnesota legislator), so caution was applied to avoid attributing their details to this candidate. Identity here is confirmed only to the extent of the official filing record matching the office, district, party, and city specified. No campaign-specific public outreach materials were located, so this summary is intentionally limited to verified filing facts rather than synthesized platform claims.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(165,322,'Julie Brixie','D','https://www.juliebrixie.com','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Julie Brixie is the incumbent Democratic member of the Michigan House of Representatives seeking re-election in 2026 in the 73rd District, which covers the Okemos/Meridian Township area of Ingham County. She first won a seat in the Michigan House in 2018 (then representing the 69th District) and, following redistricting, has represented the 73rd District since January 2023, winning re-election in 2024 against Joshua Rockey.\n\nBrixie was born in 1966 in Chicago to two teachers. She holds a bachelor\\\'s degree in physical geography from the University of Illinois and a master\\\'s degree in crop and soil sciences with a specialization in environmental toxicology from Michigan State University. Before entering the legislature she built a career as an environmental scientist, working as an environmental chemist and consultant and running a mobile laboratory that investigated and cleaned up contaminated sites across Michigan.\n\nShe has a long record of local public service in Meridian Township: she sat on the Zoning Board of Appeals (1998) and Planning Commission (1999), served as a township trustee (2000-2008), and was township treasurer beginning in 2008. In total she spent roughly eighteen years in Meridian Township government before and during her early legislative career.\n\nIn the Michigan House, Brixie\\\'s legislative focus has emphasized environmental protection and public health, drawing on her scientific background. She has been active on legislation addressing PFAS contamination, working to ensure that Michigan\\\'s water, soil, and household products are safe from these \\\"forever chemicals.\\\" She received the Environmental Stewardship Award from the Meridian Township Environmental Commission in 2015 and has been recognized by conservation and climate-focused organizations. Her broader priorities have included clean water, environmental safeguards, and constituent services for the mid-Michigan/greater Lansing area she represents.\n\nNote: This summary synthesizes biographical and record information from official legislative, encyclopedic, and nonpartisan sources. Specific 2026 campaign platform statements, endorsements, and direct contact details (campaign phone/email) were not located on accessible pages; her listed campaign website is JulieBrixie.com.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(166,323,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(167,324,'Penelope Tsernoglou','D','https://www.votepenelope.com','PenelopeTsernoglou@house.mi.gov','517-373-2668','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Penelope Tsernoglou is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 75th House District, which includes East Lansing and surrounding areas at the intersection of Clinton, Ingham, and Shiawassee Counties. She is seeking reelection in the August 4, 2026 primary and general election. First elected in 2022 and reelected in 2024, she describes herself as a mother, attorney, small business owner, former Ingham County Commissioner, and Democratic activist.\n\nTsernoglou grew up in Southfield in Metro Detroit and attended Southfield Public Schools. She earned an undergraduate degree from the University of Michigan with majors in psychology and sociology, and later became an attorney. Before joining the Legislature, she served as an Ingham County Commissioner, where her campaign materials credit her with spearheading economic-development initiatives that helped create jobs and attract significant investment to the county.\n\nHer stated legislative priorities include expanding fair access to the ballot and voting rights; advocating for labor unions, workers, and working families; increasing access to health care; reforming the criminal justice system; protecting Michigan\\\'s water and air; addressing gun violence, particularly as it affects children; and supporting public education. She has been recognized by the Michigan League of Conservation Voters for her environmental record. Her campaign frames her candidacy around continuing to fight for Democratic values and delivering for her district.\n\nHer official campaign website is votepenelope.com, with a campaign mailing address of PO Box 4310, East Lansing, MI 48826. The phone and email listed here are her Capitol office contacts (517-373-2668; PenelopeTsernoglou@house.mi.gov); a campaign-specific contact form is available on her website, and her campaign maintains social media presences on Facebook and X under the handle VotePenelope. This summary synthesizes publicly available information from her official legislative page, campaign site, Ballotpedia, and Wikipedia.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/ed8000_1ceea7da76cb4d7ab4e0a7ad509e29dc~mv2.jpg'),(168,325,'Angela Witwer','D','https://voteforangela.com/','Info@VoteforAngela.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Angela Witwer is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 76th House District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district covers Eaton County areas including Delta Township and the Lansing region. Born and raised in Michigan and rooted in a farming family, Witwer is a small business owner and community leader. Before serving in the Legislature, she was a member of the Waverly Schools Board of Education. In the Michigan House she has served two terms on the House Agriculture Committee.\n\nWitwer frames her candidacy as \\\"An Independent Voice for Eaton County,\\\" emphasizing a desire to unite the community and \\\"put people before politics.\\\" Her stated priorities include advocating for a fair tax system that supports small businesses, families, and vulnerable residents; championing local family farms and agriculture in Eaton County; strengthening support for teachers, students, and parents in education (drawing on her school board background); and protecting senior citizens. On her campaign site she highlights sponsoring and passing legislation to repeal Michigan\\\'s pension tax, which she notes was AARP\\\'s top priority in the state.\n\nIn May 2026, the Lansing Regional Chamber of Commerce\\\'s political action committee endorsed Witwer for re-election to the 76th House District, reportedly its third consecutive endorsement of her.\n\nNote: due to Michigan\\\'s 2022 redistricting, Witwer has at various points been associated with both the 71st and 76th House District numbering; this candidacy is for the 76th District as listed in the 2026 Eaton County filing. The campaign website lists an email and mailing address (PO Box 80221, Lansing, MI 48908) but no public phone number.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://voteforangela.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/cropped-AngelaWitwer_StateRep_2C.png'),(169,326,'Emily Dievendorf','D','https://www.emilydievendorf.com/','emily@emilydievendorf.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Emily Dievendorf is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 77th House District, which covers the Lansing area. First elected in 2022, she is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. A Lansing resident of 25 years, she holds a bachelor\\\'s degree in social relations from James Madison College at Michigan State University.\n\nBefore her election to the Michigan House, Dievendorf built a more than two-decade career in advocacy and community organizing. She served as Executive Director of Equality Michigan, President of the Lansing Association of Human Rights, Vice President of the Firecracker Foundation board, and a board member of the Lansing Area AIDS Network and the Ingham County Women\\\'s Commission. She was also a federally appointed co-chair of the Michigan Advisory Committee to the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights.\n\nIn the Legislature, her stated priorities center on progressive policy, with particular emphasis on LGBTQIA equality, racial justice and equality, addressing sexual and domestic violence, women\\\'s rights, and ending HIV/AIDS. According to her House Democratic profile and committee assignments, she has served on committees including Agriculture, Criminal Justice, Judiciary, and Economic Development/Small Business.\n\nShe campaigns on bringing her long record of grassroots organizing and advocacy experience to legislative work on behalf of the Lansing community. Contact for her campaign is available via email at emily@emilydievendorf.com, with a mailing address of PO Box 16026, Lansing, MI 48901. No public campaign phone number was found.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/7e8cec_3d49f4dcb12d481cb4158c6ff213bac8~mv2.jpg'),(170,327,'Rachel Gross','D','https://www.votegross.com/','info@votegross.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Rachel Gross is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 78th House District in the 2026 election. The district covers rural communities including Ionia, Lowell, Portland, Hastings, Lake Odessa, and Saranac. She is running for what her campaign describes as a newly open seat.\n\nGross was born and raised in Portland, Michigan, and graduated from St. Patrick Catholic School (St. Patrick\\\'s High School). She is a registered nurse with more than 25 years of experience and earned her Bachelor of Science in Nursing in 2024. She is married to Scott Gross (for over 28 years) and is a mother of four adult children. She has described being deeply rooted in rural Michigan, including childhood memories of her grandparents\\\' farm in Pewamo, Michigan. In fall 2024, she founded \\\"We Are Community,\\\" a grassroots organization focused on bringing people together around shared values.\n\nHer campaign platform centers on empowering rural voices in state policy, protecting constitutional rights, expanding access to healthcare, and supporting families, farms, and small businesses. Her stated motivation is to ensure rural communities in the 78th District have effective representation and are \\\"heard and respected in Lansing,\\\" with the campaign tagline \\\"Go with Gross.\\\" Her candidacy is framed around returning community-focused advocacy to state government and serving the rural population of the district.\n\nNo specific endorsements were found on her campaign website. Michigan\\\'s primary is August 4, 2026, with the general election on November 3, 2026. Contact for the campaign is info@votegross.com; the campaign address listed is in Portland, MI. No campaign phone number was published on the site.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://run.imgix.net/11afe04d-6e24-4b27-9504-d1d77904224f/f4ccd169-46bb-4908-a01e-07f62fec3a38/f4ccd169-46bb-4908-a01e-07f62fec3a38.jpeg?ixlib=js-3.8.0&bri=0&con=0&sat=0&high=0&shad=0&usm=0&rect=0%2C0%2C5824%2C4160&w=1500'),(171,328,'Zach Abbott','D','https://zachabbottformi.runtogether.us/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Zach Abbott is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 79th District in the August 4, 2026 primary. The 79th District covers southern Kent County along with portions of Allegan and Barry counties; Abbott is based in Caledonia. He is running for an open seat after the incumbent Democrat, Rep. Phil Skaggs, opted not to seek re-election to the House.\n\nAbbott\\\'s background includes military service as a weather forecaster in the United States Air Force. His campaign emphasizes personal familiarity with the financial pressures facing working families, including rising grocery prices, childcare costs, and medical expenses.\n\nHis platform is organized around three themes. \\\"Prosperity\\\" focuses on lowering the cost of living and making basic necessities such as housing and healthcare more affordable. \\\"Opportunity\\\" centers on expanding pathways into the middle class, including workforce training and the creation of good-paying jobs within Michigan. \\\"Progress\\\" frames his goal of ensuring the next generation has a brighter future, with attention to innovation and clean energy. Across these pillars, his stated priorities include affordable housing, workforce training, healthcare reform, and clean energy, aimed at a more inclusive and affordable Michigan.\n\nNo public campaign phone number or email was found on his campaign website; the site directs supporters to a contact form. No specific endorsements were identified in the sources reviewed. Confidence in identity is high: the campaign website, Caledonia location, 79th District, party affiliation, and 2026 primary candidacy all match the candidate record.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://runtogether-public-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/194/thumbnail_IMG_4541.jpg'),(172,330,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(173,331,'Stephen Wooden','D','https://www.stephenwooden.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Stephen Wooden is a Democratic candidate for re-election to the Michigan House of Representatives from the 81st District, which covers northeast Grand Rapids, Ada Township, most of Grand Rapids Township, and southern Plainfield Township in Kent County. He is the incumbent, having first been elected to the seat in 2024.\n\nWooden moved to Grand Rapids in 2005 for high school after an early childhood in New York City, where he witnessed the September 11 attacks at age ten, an experience he cites as shaping his belief in community solidarity. He graduated from Grand Rapids Catholic Central High School and Michigan State University, and earned the rank of Eagle Scout. He lives in the Creston neighborhood with his wife, Adelyn, and their son, Sam.\n\nBefore entering the Legislature, Wooden served as a Kent County Commissioner beginning in 2018 (becoming Minority Vice-Chair in 2022) and worked for roughly seven years at Dwelling Place of Grand Rapids, a major regional community and economic development organization. In that work he describes helping develop or renovate approximately 1,000 affordable housing units and assisting residents in lowering utility bills through energy efficiency and solar investments.\n\nHis platform centers on three themes: reducing costs for Michigan families (housing affordability and lower energy/utility bills), strengthening communities (safe neighborhoods, good schools, and family support), and bipartisan leadership. As a county commissioner he highlights securing $17.5 million in federal funding for an affordable housing loan program that grew to $58.3 million, and advancing initiatives on lead poisoning prevention, mental health services, and broadband expansion.\n\nHis campaign committee is \\\"Friends of Stephen Wooden\\\" (PO Box 3684, Grand Rapids, MI 49501). The campaign website lists a \\\"Contact Me\\\" page but no public email or phone was found on the pages reviewed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/65a9eeeb8b9eb60ea4ed11fe/0671b4d1-8476-40db-87d6-fb584a178871/StephenWooden_DVDP_069.jpg'),(174,332,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(175,333,'John Fitzgerald','D','https://johnformi.com/','fitzgeraldformi@gmail.com','616-690-3352','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'John Fitzgerald is the Democratic incumbent seeking re-election to Michigan\\\'s 83rd House District, which covers the city of Wyoming and parts of southwest Grand Rapids in Kent County. He is currently serving his second term and holds the position of Democratic Floor Leader in the Michigan House of Representatives.\n\nFitzgerald was born September 26, 1990, in Lansing, Michigan, and earned a bachelor\\\'s degree from Michigan State University in 2013. His professional background is in the insurance industry, where he spent most of his career working in commercial property and liability insurance. He entered elected public service in 2020, when he was elected to the Wyoming City Council. He was first elected to the state House in 2022 and won re-election in 2024, defeating Republican Tommy Brann in the November 2024 general election.\n\nAs a legislator, Fitzgerald has focused his priorities on supporting community services, public safety, economic growth, and job development for his district. As Democratic Floor Leader, he holds a recognized leadership role within his caucus.\n\nHe maintains an official 2026 campaign presence under the \\\"John Fitzgerald for State Representative\\\" / \\\"Fitzgerald for Michigan\\\" banner (johnformi.com), along with a campaign Facebook page (@JohnForMI) and an ActBlue donation page. His state office contact is (517) 373-0835 and JohnFitzgerald@house.mi.gov; his campaign contact is listed as 616-690-3352 and fitzgeraldformi@gmail.com.\n\nNo specific 2026 endorsements were located in the sources reviewed, and a direct headshot image URL could not be confirmed (his campaign website was not reachable at the time of research, though it is his confirmed official campaign site). This summary is a best-effort synthesis of publicly available official and campaign sources.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(176,334,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(177,335,'Richard Abraham','D','https://abrahamfor85.com/','Info@abrahamfor85.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Richard Abraham is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 85th District, which includes the Hudsonville/Ottawa County area, running in the August 4, 2026 primary.\n\nAccording to his campaign website, Abraham was born in Urbana, Illinois and moved frequently as a child (Colorado, Florida, Pennsylvania) before his family settled in Saline, Michigan during his teenage years. He attended an alternative high school, which he credits with teaching him accountability and ownership over his future, and graduated from the Specs Howard School of Broadcast Arts. He met his wife online in 2001 and they married in 2005. Early in their marriage the couple relied on government assistance programs such as WIC and food stamps while building toward financial stability. Abraham has worked at Haworth (a West Michigan furniture manufacturer) for over 20 years and has raised two children, now ages 18 and 19.\n\nAbraham frames his candidacy around giving back to the community and the opportunities that helped his family move from struggle to stability. His stated platform priorities include strengthening families, encouraging accountability, and ensuring equal opportunity for others to succeed. His website references local issues ranging from \\\"water rights to affordability,\\\" with more detailed positions on his policies page. The campaign accepts donations via ActBlue.\n\nNo current or prior elected offices are listed on his campaign materials, suggesting he is a first-time or non-incumbent candidate. No endorsements were found in the sources reviewed. This summary is a best-effort synthesis of the candidate\\\'s own campaign website; independent reporting on his candidacy was limited at the time of research.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://abrahamfor85.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/richcoat2.jpg'),(178,336,'Joseph McClusky','D','https://www.mccluskyformi.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Joseph McClusky is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 86th District, running in the August 4, 2026 primary. The 86th District includes the city of Holland and Holland, Park, and Laketown townships in the Ottawa County area, and is currently represented by Republican Nancy DeBoer. McClusky, reported to be in his late twenties, is a Hope College graduate (Political Science) who chose to remain in West Michigan after college and has spent roughly the past decade in the region. His professional background spans political and nonprofit work, including roles as a campaign manager and as Development and Communications Associate Director at the Holland Museum.\n\nMcClusky\\\'s campaign is organized around the themes of accountability, affordability, and action. His stated priorities include lowering the cost of living for families, holding politicians and special interests accountable, and making government more responsive to ordinary constituents rather than special interests. His messaging frames government as something that should \\\"make life easier, not harder,\\\" and emphasizes that residents should be able to live with dignity, stability, and hope. He describes his motivation for running in terms of addressing rising costs and political dysfunction and standing up for the everyday issues families in the district face. The campaign\\\'s mailing address is listed as PO Box 1101, Holland, MI 49422.\n\nNo public campaign phone number or email address was found on his official website at the time of research; the site lists a mailing address and links to an endorsements section, though specific endorsements were not visible on the pages reviewed. Local outlets, including the Ottawa News Network and The Hollander, have covered his candidacy, and the Ottawa County Democratic Party has featured him in candidate spotlights.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/6834a7739c03d721959a7c07/9530f65f-c270-41a1-8957-039ae7348425/bio_website_photo.jpg'),(179,337,'Will Snyder','D','https://www.electwillsnyder.com','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Will Snyder is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 87th House District and is running for re-election in 2026. The 87th District covers Greater Muskegon, including portions of Norton Shores, Muskegon Heights, Roosevelt Park, the city of Muskegon, North Muskegon, Muskegon Township, Laketon Township, and most of Dalton Township.\n\nSnyder is serving his second term in the Michigan House. Before being elected, he spent roughly six years working as a staffer for his predecessor, former state Rep. Terry Sabo. In his most recent term he served as chair of the House Appropriations Subcommittee on Labor, Economic Development, and Lifelong Learning. He was the lead sponsor of seven bills that became law during his first term, with public acts addressing issues including economic development and health care access. He has officially filed to run again in the 87th District for the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary.\n\nIn the November 5, 2024 general election, Snyder won re-election, defeating Republican challengers including Chip Chipman and Rich McClain.\n\nHis public-facing priorities, consistent with his committee work and legislative record, center on economic development and job growth in the Muskegon area, expanding access to health care, supporting working families and labor, and investing in education and lifelong learning. His campaign maintains an endorsements page, though the specific endorsing organizations could not be retrieved at the time of research.\n\nNote: A public campaign or contact phone number, email address, and a direct headshot image URL could not be confirmed from accessible sources during this research (the campaign site\\\'s homepage redirects to a donation page, and the about/endorsements subpages returned errors; the official Michigan House Democrats bio page content was truncated). His official legislative bio and campaign site remain the best sources for current contact details and a portrait.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(180,338,'Kiel Reid','D','https://kielreid.com/','reid4rep@proton.me','1-616-414-4865','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Kiel Reid is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in House District 88, which covers the Norton Shores area of West Michigan. He is running in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary, where he is the sole Democrat seeking to challenge Republican incumbent Rep. Greg VanWoerkom in the November general election. Reid officially launched his campaign at a kickoff event in early May 2026.\n\nReid is a small business owner and community leader who started his first venture at age 27. He currently owns and operates The Griffin\\\'s Rest, a local gathering space in West Michigan. He frames his candidacy around bringing \\\"steady, practical, and results-driven leadership to Lansing,\\\" and summarizes his motivation with the line, \\\"Because no one said life would be easy, but it shouldn\\\'t be this hard.\\\"\n\nHis platform centers on three main priority areas. On housing, he advocates for affordable homes that do not sacrifice community character, along with protecting local water resources. On healthcare, he supports expanding access to local care, telehealth, mental health services, prescription drug affordability, and home health care. On the economy, he emphasizes skilled trades and well-paying local jobs, small business support, and expanding broadband infrastructure.\n\nNo endorsements or prior elected offices were identified in the available sources. This summary is synthesized from his campaign website and local news coverage of his campaign launch.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://i0.wp.com/kielreid.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/unnamed-4.jpg?fit=1024%2C1536&ssl=1'),(181,339,'Meegan Zickus','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Meegan Zickus is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 89th District in the August 4, 2026 primary. She is a resident of Allendale, Michigan, in the Grand Rapids/Ottawa County area. The seat is open in 2026, as the Republican incumbent, Bryan Posthumus, is not seeking re-election; news and reference sources indicate Zickus is competing for the Democratic nomination while Patrick Kapenga has been identified on the Republican side.\n\nBy profession, Zickus is an attorney and a bioethics educator. She operates a law practice (Meegan Zickus, P.C. / Meegan Pope Zickus) based in Allendale and teaches bioethics at Grand Valley State University, with roughly two decades of experience in higher education, including prior affiliations with Davenport University and Kaplan University. She holds a Master of Public Health degree. She has authored work on contemporary issues in bioethics.\n\nIn local civic life, Zickus completed about ten years of service on the local Board of Education and has been involved with community advocacy efforts in Allendale, for which she has received recognition (a WGVU \\\"Making a Difference in Education\\\" award is associated with her advocacy work). She lives in Allendale with her family.\n\nA specific 2026 campaign platform, list of endorsements, or policy priorities could not be confirmed from the public sources reviewed, and no dedicated campaign website, public campaign phone, email, or headshot image was located. This summary is therefore a factual profile based on her professional and civic background rather than a detailed campaign platform. Note: identity is corroborated by the match of name, Democratic affiliation, the 89th District open-seat race, and her Allendale residence; her attorney/educator background appears in legal-directory and LinkedIn listings under the same name and location.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(182,341,'Rachel Crowther','D','https://www.rachelcrowthermi.com/','info@rachelcrowthermi.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Rachel Crowther is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in House District 90, which covers parts of Kent County including the Rockford area. She is competing in the August 4, 2026 primary ahead of the November 3, 2026 general election.\n\nCrowther is a small business owner, community leader, and current elected official with deep roots in the Rockford area and Courtland Township. She serves as a Courtland Township Trustee. Her community involvement spans the Rockford Area Community Foundation, the Rockford\\\'s Got Talent fundraiser, the Courtland Township Parks Committee, Experience Grand Rapids, and the Kent County Lodging Association. In 2016 she was named the Joe Tomaselli Hotelier of the Year.\n\nHer campaign emphasizes the themes of \\\"Leadership, Collaboration, and Community.\\\" She frames her candidacy around being a representative for everyone in the district, stating she is backed by the people rather than a family name or a large corporation. Her platform centers on supporting local leadership that puts every voice at the table, transparent and accountable governance grounded in collaboration, strengthening local economies, and building vibrant communities.\n\nCrowther has earned a range of endorsements. Individual endorsers include State Representative Stephen Wooden (81st House District), former Rockford Mayors Neil Blakeslee and Ed Ross, former Kent County Commissioner Ivan Diaz, City Council Member Charles Baker, and former Courtland Township Trustee Mary Ann Andersen. Organizational endorsers include MI List (pro-choice Democratic women), MI Rural PAC, the MDP Rural Caucus, and Planned Parenthood Advocates of Michigan.\n\nHer campaign can be reached at info@rachelcrowthermi.com, with a mailing address of P.O. Box 342, Rockford, MI 49341. The campaign maintains a presence on Facebook, Instagram (@electrachelcrowther), and LinkedIn. No public campaign phone number was located.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://run.imgix.net/983aebba-4c3a-43d3-93bd-f8a5f7081293/b5beab94-536b-4c7e-a38d-b71058eae6d4/b5beab94-536b-4c7e-a38d-b71058eae6d4.jpg'),(183,342,'Frank Lafata','D','https://www.franklafata.com/','franklafataworks@gmail.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Frank J. Lafata is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, District 91, in the August 4, 2026 primary (and November 3, 2026 general election). He is a retired union carpenter with decades of skilled-trades experience, having worked on infrastructure projects across Michigan, including bridges in Greenville, a power plant in Carson City, and the S-curve in Grand Rapids. A roughly 30-year resident of the 91st District and longtime Greenville resident, he is married (about 35 years) with three children and five grandchildren, and presents himself as a working-class candidate rooted in trades and rural-community values.\n\nLafata says he is running because he believes politicians have lost touch with everyday constituents, and he wants to redirect government\\\'s focus toward working families rather than special interests. He frames his candidacy in practical terms: \\\"I\\\'m not running for the 91st to build a legacy. I want to build roads, schools and power plants in our district.\\\"\n\nHis stated priorities include: addressing the economy and rising food and gas prices; supporting agriculture and small family farms (noting that a majority of District 91 is farmland); protecting local hospitals and doctors from federal budget threats; ensuring fast 911 emergency response in rural areas; and creating good-paying jobs. He has also raised newer-technology issues, calling for a moratorium on data centers over their impact on water and electricity costs, and for a Michigan citizens\\\' bill of rights addressing AI and privacy. Local coverage describes him as focused on challenges facing rural towns and farming communities, including rising costs, limited healthcare access, job creation, and improved school funding.\n\nHis campaign headquarters is listed at 504 E Pearl Street, Greenville, MI 48838, and the campaign maintains a Facebook presence (facebook.com/votefrankjlafata). No public endorsements were found in the reviewed sources. No campaign phone number was published on the sources reviewed; the public contact email is franklafataworks@gmail.com.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.franklafata.com/gallery_gen/4050136803179dda2413acdbf8ab5af3_1242x828_fit.jpg'),(184,343,'Luke Del Castillo','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Luke Del Castillo is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 92nd District, in the August 4, 2026 primary. Michigan\\\'s 92nd House district covers parts of Isabella and Gratiot counties, including Mount Pleasant, the candidate\\\'s listed home city. According to coverage of the 2026 Michigan House elections, the 92nd District seat is held by Republican incumbent Tim Kelly, and Del Castillo is one of multiple Democrats who filed for the seat (another reported Democratic filer is J. Aaron Bailey, described as a reverend and activist), setting up a contested Democratic primary.\n\nBeyond confirming his party affiliation, district, and home city, very little public information about Del Castillo was found online. No official 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, public campaign email address, or candidate headshot/portrait could be located through web searches at the time of this research. No detailed biography, prior elected office, policy platform, or endorsements were available from the sources reviewed.\n\nThis is a deliberately short, factual summary because limited information is available. The candidate appears to be a relatively low-profile, first-time-noted contender whose campaign metadata (contact details, website, photo, and platform) had not yet surfaced in indexed public sources as of June 2026. Identity is matched to the correct person via the Michigan 92nd District / Democratic primary context, but confidence is reduced by the scarcity of corroborating candidate-specific sources.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(185,344,'Serenity Hope Salak','D','https://www.serenityhope4mi.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Serenity Hope Salak is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 93rd District (Saginaw area) in the August 4, 2026 primary. A lifelong Michigan resident, she grew up in Albee Township and Burt and now lives in Saginaw Township with her family. Her professional background includes serving as a caseworker with the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (MDHHS) for roughly 11 years, as well as work in education as a substitute teacher and paraprofessional in the Saginaw area, and as a softball coach.\n\nEarlier in the 2026 cycle, Salak ran in a special Democratic primary for Michigan State Senate District 35 (held February 3, 2026), which she did not win; she subsequently filed (March 31, 2026) to run for the 93rd State House District. Her campaign website domain and branding still reference the earlier Senate run, but current site content and her ActBlue donation link (\\\"serenity-hope-93\\\") reflect the State Representative race in District 93.\n\nHer campaign platform centers on three main areas. On child care, she advocates expanding day care assistance programs, broadening Pre-K For All to include three-year-olds, and building out before- and after-school programs so families can work or pursue job retraining. On healthcare, which she frames as a human right, she supports increasing Medicaid income eligibility, using state tax credits to offset marketplace insurance premium costs, and reducing prescription drug costs. On cost of living, she calls for making officials \\\"accountable to their voters—not corporations,\\\" capping utility rates for seniors and disabled residents, and fully funding schools without raising taxes on the working class (which she argues would help avoid costly school bonds and property tax hikes).\n\nNo public campaign phone number or email was found on her website; the site directs supporters to social media (Instagram @serenity_hope_salak, TikTok @salaksix, and Facebook) and an ActBlue donation page. No endorsements were confirmed in the sources reviewed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/6903e0caa3eb66660fa823a7/0a4d6f04-fbd2-499c-b656-dbf471b6f37d/Serenity_Hope_Salak_Headshot.jpeg'),(186,345,'Amos O\'Neal','D','https://www.electamosoneal.org/','Amossam@charter.net','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Amos O\\\'Neal is the Democratic incumbent State Representative for Michigan\\\'s 94th House District, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary. Born July 17, 1961 in Saginaw, Michigan, O\\\'Neal represents the city of Saginaw and surrounding areas, including portions of Saginaw Township, Carrollton Township, Buena Vista Charter Township, and Bridgeport Charter Township. He was first elected to the Michigan House in 2022 and was reelected in 2024, making the 2026 cycle his bid for a third full term in the seat. According to local reporting, he filed for reelection in early 2026 and is the sitting representative for the district.\n\nHis campaign, branded \\\"Re-Elect Representative Amos O\\\'Neal, Saginaw,\\\" emphasizes strong, experienced leadership and frames his platform around Michigan\\\'s role in innovation, progress, and freedom, positioning the state as a leader in those areas. The campaign site does not enumerate detailed policy planks or formal endorsements beyond these general themes. He maintains an active social media presence as @ElectAmosONeal94 (Instagram), StateRepAmosONeal (Facebook), and @AmosONeal1 (Twitter/X).\n\nThis summary is a best-effort synthesis from his campaign website, Ballotpedia, Wikipedia, and local news coverage. Detailed committee assignments and specific legislative priorities were not fully captured because the official Michigan House Democrats bio page content was not retrievable during research; no formal endorsements were confirmed in the sources reviewed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(187,346,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(188,347,'Christopher R. Girard','D','https://girardformichigan.com','info@girardformichigan.com','989-318-3879','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Christopher \\\"Chris\\\" R. Girard is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 96th House District in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is the sitting Mayor of Bay City, having been elected mayor in 2023 after serving roughly a decade on the Bay City Commission across two stints. In April 2026 he filed his nominating petition with the Bay County Clerk\\\'s Office, becoming the first candidate to enter the race. The 96th District covers Bay City, Essexville, and ten of Bay County\\\'s fourteen townships. The seat is currently held by Republican incumbent Tim (Timmy) Beson, first elected in 2021, who has indicated he plans to seek reelection.\n\nGirard\\\'s campaign, branded \\\"Rooted in Service. Driven by Solutions,\\\" frames him as a longtime Bay City resident and community leader. His background includes leadership in disability-services organizations and fostering more than 40 children. His stated platform priorities include infrastructure and roads, mental health and family services, public safety, affordability and good-paying jobs, commerce and small business, and workforce training and development. On infrastructure he has specifically highlighted Bay City\\\'s bridges, arguing the state should cover toll costs for drivers forced onto private bridges when state-owned bridges are closed. He has summarized his core focus areas as infrastructure, economic stability, and community health.\n\nNo endorsements were identified in the sources reviewed. Campaign contact information (website, phone, and email) comes from his official campaign site, girardformichigan.com.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/69d57484d65c6c402f9d4dbf/d5570bc6-55b6-48e1-9a72-4a5b2ead7d6b/iso+headshot+2.png'),(189,348,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(190,349,'Keith Brusseau','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Keith Brusseau is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 98th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary election. He is listed with a residence in Lexington, Michigan. Michigan\\\'s 98th House District covers all of Huron County and parts of Lapeer, Sanilac, and Tuscola counties (the \\\"Thumb\\\" region); Lexington is located in Sanilac County. The seat\\\'s current incumbent is Republican Gregory Alexander, who took office in January 2023, so Brusseau would be running as a Democratic challenger in a district that leans Republican.\n\nBeyond his name, party, district, and city of residence as listed in candidate filings, very little public information could be found about Keith Brusseau. No campaign website, social media campaign presence, candidate biography, platform statement, endorsements, or contact information surfaced in web searches. This is common for newly filed candidates in down-ballot legislative primaries who have not yet established an online campaign footprint, particularly in rural districts.\n\nThis summary is intentionally brief and factual because no substantive biographical or platform details were located. No specific policy positions, professional background, prior offices held, or endorsements are reported here, as none were found in available sources. Voters seeking more information may wish to consult the Michigan Bureau of Elections official 2026 candidate listing, the Sanilac County or Huron County clerk\\\'s offices, local Thumb-region news outlets (such as the Sanilac County News), or any campaign materials the candidate may publish closer to the primary.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(191,350,'David Forgione','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'David Forgione is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 99th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary election. The 99th District covers a mid-Michigan area that includes Clare County and the city of Harrison, where the candidate is based. The seat is currently held by Republican Mike Hoadley, who was elected in 2024 after defeating Democrat Jon LeRoux; Forgione appears to be a Democratic challenger for the 2026 cycle.\n\nVery little public information about this candidate was found through web research. Forgione appears in the Michigan Bureau of Elections official 2026 candidate filing listing but does not have a discoverable campaign website, public campaign contact information, candidate biography, platform/policy statements, or endorsements published online as of June 2026. No Ballotpedia candidate profile, local news coverage, or campaign social media presence specific to this race could be confirmed. Because of the lack of corroborating sources tying biographical details to this specific person, no background, priorities, or platform claims are asserted here to avoid fabrication.\n\nThis is a best-effort factual summary based on the limited information available; the candidate\\\'s identity beyond the official filing (name, party, district, and Harrison/Clare County location) could not be independently confirmed.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(192,243,'Tracy Ruell','D','https://www.ruellforrep.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Tracy Ruell is a Democratic candidate for Michigan House of Representatives, District 100, in the August 4, 2026 primary. She is a lifelong Michigander from Big Rapids who grew up on a third-generation family farm; her family\\\'s farm was forced to close after PBB chemical contamination affected Michigan cattle feed. She built a long career in business operations, working more than 20 years at McDonald\\\'s (rising from crew member to Area General Manager and Shift Manager) and later serving as an Operations Manager for customer contact at Meijer Inc. She is married to Rob and supports his insulation business, International Insulation Fabricators Inc., and has two children who are public-university graduates.\n\nRuell previously ran for the same District 100 seat in 2024, winning the Democratic primary before losing the November 2024 general election to Republican incumbent Tom Kunse. She has launched a 2026 campaign for the seat under the committee \\\"Friends to Elect Tracy Ruell.\\\"\n\nHer campaign, branded \\\"Right Here, Right Now - Together\\\" and \\\"Rooted in Michigan soil, driven by Michigan grit,\\\" emphasizes her small-business and agricultural background. Per her campaign materials, her platform centers on three areas: Affordable Living (rewriting utility legislation, reducing corporate influence in politics, and promoting housing development); Education Investment (early-education funding, permanent free school lunches, and career pathways beginning in middle school); and Healthcare Reform (a proposed \\\"MiCare\\\" model featuring no deductibles and shared funding, plus expanding affordable healthcare options to relieve financial pressure on families and small businesses).\n\nShe is active in her community as a member of the Big Rapids Rotary Club and is involved with the Angels of Action organization, and has also been associated with AAUW. Her campaign maintains a website and social media presence on Facebook, Instagram (@electtracyruell), and TikTok (@electtracyruell). A public campaign phone and email were not listed on her website; the committee lists a mailing address of PO Box 1473, Big Rapids, MI 49307.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://static.wixstatic.com/media/439b33_57fcb6551cf5414cb832bb2f1f62623b~mv2.jpg'),(193,244,'Christopher R. Crain','D','https://chrisformi101.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Christopher R. Crain is a Democratic candidate for Michigan\\\'s 101st District seat in the State House of Representatives in the 2026 election. He is a resident of the northern Michigan region; the 101st District covers Wexford County (which includes Manton), along with Newaygo County, parts of Lake County, and slivers of Mason and Oceana counties. Crain previously ran for the same seat as the Democratic nominee in 2024, when he was defeated by Republican incumbent Joseph Fox; he appears to be running again in 2026.\n\nAccording to local reporting from his 2024 campaign, Crain holds a bachelor\\\'s degree in Psychology and Philosophy/Religion from Spring Arbor University, a Master of Divinity from Calvin Theological Seminary, and a teaching certificate from Western Michigan University. His career has spanned work as a missionary, teacher, principal, pastor, and director of a county Commission on Aging in Newaygo County, reflecting a background in education, ministry, and community/social services.\n\nOn policy, Crain has emphasized economic hardship facing district residents, citing data that a large share of households in the district fall below the ALICE (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed) threshold, meaning many struggle to afford basic needs. He has expressed support for local rent controls and short-term rental regulations as tools to address housing affordability while potentially generating local revenue from the area\\\'s tourism economy.\n\nHis campaign maintains a website at chrisformi101.com under the banner \\\"Everyone in Michigan\\\'s 101st District Deserves Responsible, Fair, and Effective Representation in Lansing,\\\" though as of this research the public-facing site appears to contain template/placeholder content rather than fully developed platform details, and lists no contact email, phone number, or candidate photo.\n\nNo campaign phone, email, or direct headshot image URL could be confirmed from public sources. Endorsements and specific 2026-cycle priorities were not available beyond the carryover of his prior platform. Information here is synthesized primarily from 2024 local news coverage and a voter guide profile, as detailed 2026-specific materials were limited at the time of research.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(194,245,'Angel Coon','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Angel Coon is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives in the 102nd District, running in the August 4, 2026 primary. The district covers parts of Manistee, Mason, Muskegon, and Oceana counties along Michigan\\\'s west/lakeshore region; Coon is based in Whitehall in the Muskegon County area. She is challenging the seat currently held by Republican incumbent Curt VanderWall.\n\nOutside of politics, Coon is the owner and operator of Earthwise Studio & Shop, a small business and creative space (located on 3rd Street in the Muskegon area) offering services such as professional photography, event and party planning, graphic design, and intuitive/tarot readings. Her background as a local small-business owner and artist is the foundation of her public profile.\n\nA central theme of her campaign is rejecting corporate money in politics. At a candidate meet-and-greet covered in local media, when asked whether she would refuse contributions from corporate political action committees (PACs), she gave a firm commitment to do so, framing her candidacy around representing constituents rather than corporate interests. This good-government / clean-money positioning has been the most consistently reported plank of her platform.\n\nBeyond the campaign-finance pledge, detailed policy positions, a formal platform, endorsements, and campaign organization details were not found in publicly available sources at the time of research. No official 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, or campaign email address could be located, and no direct headshot/portrait image URL was found. A LinkedIn profile associated with her business (Earthwise Studio & Shop) exists but was not accessible for additional verified details.\n\nNote: Public information on this candidate is currently limited, and much of what is available comes from a single local readers\\\'-forum/opinion piece and business listings. The identity match to the correct person (Democrat, Michigan 102nd District, Whitehall/Muskegon area, Earthwise Studio owner) is well supported, but campaign infrastructure and contact details appear minimal or not yet published online.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(195,246,'Betsy Coffia','D','https://www.betsyformichigan.com','BetsyCoffia@house.mi.gov','231-794-2387','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Betsy Coffia is the Democratic incumbent state representative for Michigan\\\'s 103rd House District, which covers Grand Traverse, Leelanau, and Benzie counties in northern Michigan, including Traverse City. She first assumed office on January 1, 2023, won re-election in November 2024, and is seeking another term in the August 4, 2026 Democratic primary and the November 2026 general election.\n\nBefore serving in the legislature, Coffia earned an associate degree from Northwestern Michigan College and a bachelor\\\'s degree in social work from Ferris State University. Her career has included work as a newspaper reporter and weekly newspaper editor, and as a social worker with Head Start. She also previously served as a Grand Traverse County commissioner before her election to the state House.\n\nCoffia is known for a strong environmental record; the Michigan League of Conservation Voters credits her with a 100% environmental voting record for the 2023-2026 period. In her prior campaigns she received endorsements from figures and organizations including Michigan Secretary of State Jocelyn Benson and EMILY\\\'s List, reflecting support tied to environmental protection, reproductive rights, and women\\\'s representation in office.\n\nHer platform and legislative focus have emphasized local and northern Michigan priorities such as protecting the Great Lakes and natural resources, supporting working families, affordable housing, public education, and access to health care. As a former social worker and journalist, she has framed her public service around community advocacy and constituent engagement.\n\nNote: Detailed 2026-specific campaign platform statements could not be fully retrieved (her campaign site returned an access error), so this summary draws on her official legislative bio, Ballotpedia, and conservation/news sources rather than a current campaign manifesto. Voters seeking her latest 2026 priorities should consult her campaign website directly.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(196,247,'Mitchell Ryan Distin','D','https://www.mitch4michigan.com/','Contact@Mitch4Michigan.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Dr. Mitchell Ryan Distin is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 104th District in the August 4, 2026 primary. He is a scientist by training, holding a Ph.D. in Ecology, Evolutionary Biology, and Biodiversity from the Universitat de Valencia (Spain) with an international mention from the University of Cambridge, a B.Sc. in neuropsychology from Michigan State University, and an M.Sc. in history and philosophy of science from University College London. He presents himself as a political outsider who applies a scientist\\\'s root-cause approach to public problems, and he authored a political pamphlet titled \\\"Common Enemy: The Falsity of the Left-Right Divide in America.\\\"\n\nDistin\\\'s central campaign message is that the political system has been \\\"hijacked by an elite ruling class,\\\" reframing politics as \\\"the 99% vs. the 1%\\\" rather than a left-versus-right contest. His stated top priorities include getting money out of politics and reducing billionaire influence on government, bridging political divides, protecting residents from Big Tech and large data centers (opposing corporate surveillance and consolidation), rebuilding local economies and community self-sufficiency, and putting Michiganders ahead of corporate interests. He emphasizes community-based solutions, human connection, and rebuilding governance around local needs.\n\nHis campaign has had local engagement in northern Michigan, including a meet-and-greet hosted by area Democrats. No formal endorsements were listed on his campaign website at the time of research. Public contact is via email (Contact@Mitch4Michigan.com for general inquiries, Press@Mitch4Michigan.com for press); no campaign phone number was published. The campaign maintains Facebook and YouTube presences under \\\"Mitch for Michigan.\\\" Identity is confirmed as the correct candidate through his official campaign website, which matches the Michigan 104th District State Representative race.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://run.imgix.net/a2c71aca-a541-452a-b49e-31bdc0928f93/b3230c37-24c0-4abf-bd86-76a0069d1638/b3230c37-24c0-4abf-bd86-76a0069d1638.jpg'),(197,248,'Rachel Longendyke Teeter','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Rachel Longendyke Teeter of Grayling is a Democratic candidate for Michigan\\\'s 105th State House District (Crawford, Missaukee, Otsego, Roscommon and parts of Antrim, Kalkaska and Oscoda counties) in 2026. No campaign website or detailed public profile was located.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(198,249,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(199,250,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 18:34:43','','',0,'',''),(200,251,'Rachel M. Keys','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Rachel M. Keys is a Democratic candidate for the Michigan House of Representatives, 108th District, in the August 4, 2026 primary election. She is from Brimley, Michigan, a community in Chippewa County in the eastern Upper Peninsula. The 108th District covers portions of the eastern U.P., which is geographically consistent with her listed hometown.\n\nBeyond her candidate filing, no campaign website, social media presence, contact information, headshot, or platform statement could be located through public web searches as of June 2026. Searches of Ballotpedia, Politics1, the Chippewa County Democratic Party site, and general web/Facebook queries did not surface independent campaign materials, biographical details, endorsements, or policy positions for this candidate. This is common for newly filed candidates in smaller, rural Upper Peninsula districts who may not yet have established an online campaign footprint ahead of the primary.\n\nNo verified background, current or past offices held, priorities, or endorsements were found, and none should be assumed. The record above reflects her candidacy as registered with Michigan election authorities (the source of this candidate record). Additional detail may become available closer to the primary as the campaign develops.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(201,252,'Anna Aho Rink','D','https://annaahorink4mi.com/','AnnaAhoRink@gmail.com','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Anna Aho Rink is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in the 109th House District in the August 4, 2026 primary. She lives in Negaunee with her husband (a police officer), two children, and two dogs. A lifelong Upper Peninsula resident from a union household, she launched her campaign in September 2025. The 109th District covers much of the central U.P., including Marquette, Ishpeming, Negaunee, Munising, and Norway, spanning Alger, Baraga, and Marquette counties plus part of Dickinson.\n\nRink worked for 17 years as a physician assistant at the Planned Parenthood Marquette Health Center until the facility closed in April 2025. She has cited that closure and concerns about access to rural healthcare as central motivations for running. She is challenging incumbent Republican Rep. Karl Bohnak, a former television weatherman; news coverage has framed the contest as a competitive race in a swing district that Democrats are seeking to reclaim.\n\nHer stated priorities include: protecting union jobs and workers\\\' rights; affordability, with a focus on reducing housing and energy costs; strengthening public schools through improved teacher compensation and student resources; expanding healthcare access across the Upper Peninsula; environmental protection of water, air, and the Great Lakes; and public safety, including support for first responders and addressing the root causes of crime. Her campaign messaging emphasizes \\\"putting people over politics\\\" and fighting for the U.P.\n\nNo public campaign phone number or specific endorsements were found on her website at the time of research. Her campaign contact email is AnnaAhoRink@gmail.com, with a mailing address of P.O. Box 252, Marquette, MI 49855. She maintains a campaign website and an X/Twitter account (@AnnaAhoRink4MI) and a campaign Facebook page.\'','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(202,254,'Brian Irizarry','D','https://www.voteirizarry.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','\'Brian Irizarry is a Democratic candidate for Michigan State Representative in House District 110, running in the August 4, 2026 primary. District 110 covers Michigan\\\'s western Upper Peninsula, including Houghton, Keweenaw, Ontonagon, Gogebic, Iron, and Dickinson counties.\n\nIrizarry describes himself as a public school teacher, U.S. Marine veteran, city councilor, coach, husband, and father. His campaign emphasizes creating local jobs and supporting local families in the Upper Peninsula.\n\nHis platform spans several issue areas. On jobs and education, he supports building workforce skills, helping small businesses grow, and expanding access to affordable childcare. On housing and taxes, he calls for lowering the cost of living, a fairer distribution of taxes, and increasing the housing supply. On law and order, his website references police funding, Second Amendment protections, and support for drug enforcement. On energy, he advocates for both renewable-energy jobs and traditional resource jobs, with a goal of energy independence. On social issues, his site references protecting civil rights, access to reproductive health, and support for the social safety net. His site also touches on foreign policy themes including border security and immigration reform.\n\nHis campaign accepts contributions through an ActBlue donation page and maintains a Facebook presence. No campaign phone number or email address was published on his website\\\'s main or contact pages; the contact page offers only a form for invitations and volunteering.\n\nNote: No public endorsements were listed on the campaign site at the time of research. The available campaign image is a 2025 family photo rather than a standalone studio headshot.\'','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/6802dd526a174623927a1e83/11b4a652-2cef-4980-b0e6-737ad785cd3d/IrizarryFamily2025-153.jpeg'),(203,5710,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 23:43:08','','',0,'',''),(204,5711,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 23:43:08','','',0,'',''),(205,5712,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 23:43:08','','',0,'',''),(206,5713,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 23:43:08','','',0,'',''),(207,5227,'','','','','','','2026-06-17 23:43:11'