ho has held the seat through prior elections. He is among the candidates for the road commission in the 2026 cycle.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(309,14666,'Russell D. Krish','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(310,5568,'Charles Allen','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(311,14667,'Dorothy Yope','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Dorothy Yope is the Democratic candidate for St. Clair County Commissioner, District 5, in 2026. District 5 (the Kimball area) became vacant after commissioner Robert Fielitz resigned in August 2025, and is being contested by multiple candidates in 2026.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(312,5591,'Jennifer Vandenbossche','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Jennifer Vandenbossche is the incumbent Mayor of Marine City in St. Clair County, Michigan, and is running for re-election in 2026. She has served as mayor since 2022, when she was first elected, and was reelected in 2024 with about 72% of the vote to a two-year term expiring in 2026; the nonpartisan mayoral seat is again up for a two-year term.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(313,5598,'Kathleen L. Hayman','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Kathleen (Kathy) L. Hayman is the incumbent Mayor of Marysville, Michigan, in St. Clair County, and is seeking the nonpartisan mayoral seat in 2026. She previously appeared on the ballot for Marysville mayor in 2024 and serves as the city\'s presiding official alongside the city council.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(314,5609,'Greg Devoogd','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Greg (Gregg) DeVoogd is a candidate for Port Huron City Council in St. Clair County, Michigan, a nonpartisan office. He appeared as a Port Huron City Council candidate in prior local election coverage of the Blue Water area.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(315,5612,'Bill Cedar, Jr.','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Bill Cedar Jr. is the incumbent Mayor of the City of St. Clair in St. Clair County, Michigan, and is running for the nonpartisan mayoral seat in 2026. He presides over St. Clair City Council meetings and was previously on the ballot for mayor in 2024.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(316,7700,'Jessica Totty','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Jessica Totty is a member of the Port Huron Area School District Board of Education in St. Clair County, Michigan, and is a candidate for the nonpartisan school board in 2026. The board consists of seven members serving six-year terms.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(317,14668,'Antonio Pedini','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(318,4298,'Emily S. Olson','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Emily S. Olson is the Democratic candidate for Shiawassee County Road Commissioner (6-year term) in the 2026 election, appearing on the August primary candidate filings. No additional biographical details or campaign presence were found online.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(319,14669,'Nancy Barrios','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Nancy Barrios is a Tuscola County Commissioner representing District 1 (Akron, Columbia, Elkland, Elmwood, Fairgrove, Gilford and Wisner townships) and is seeking election in 2026. She has been an active participant in 2026 Board of Commissioners meetings, including discussions of county road-safety improvements.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(320,13338,'Rachel Chisholm','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(321,13345,'Beth A. Duet','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(322,13371,'Jodi Barrons','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(323,5736,'Desirae Simmons','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Desiraé Simmons is a Third Ward Democrat on the Ypsilanti City Council (Washtenaw County) and Director of the Interfaith Council for Peace & Justice. A community organizer active in affordable-housing and racial-equity work, she survived a May 2024 recall election and is a 2026 city council candidate. She has a campaign Facebook page, \"Desiraé Simmons for Ypsilanti\" (@Desirae4Ypsi).','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(324,7168,'Elise Bruderly','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Elise Bruderly is a 2026 nonpartisan candidate for the Dexter Community Schools Board of Education in Washtenaw County, Michigan, on the November 3, 2026 ballot.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(325,7796,'Yvonne M. Fields','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Yvonne M. Fields is a 2026 nonpartisan candidate for the Ypsilanti Community Schools Board of Education in Washtenaw County, Michigan, on the November 3, 2026 ballot.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(326,4536,'Barbara Calleja','D','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Barbara Calleja is a Democratic candidate for Webster Township Clerk in Washtenaw County, Michigan, in the August 4, 2026 primary, and has previously served as the township\'s clerk.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(327,5808,'Mark Jacobs','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Mark Jacobs is the incumbent Mayor of Garden City in Wayne County, Michigan, whose term runs through 2026. A lifelong Garden City resident, he served seven years on the City Council before being elected mayor in November 2022, and is associated with the 2026 mayoral election.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(328,5879,'Maureen Tobin','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Maureen Tobin is the Mayor of Lincoln Park, Michigan, presiding over city council meetings through 2026, and is a candidate for the Lincoln Park mayoral seat in the 2026 election. A Lincoln Park resident for over 20 years, she previously worked as a city event coordinator and was elected to city council in 2018.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(329,5790,'Kimberly R. Whitsett','N','https://whitsettforecorse.com/','','(313) 386-2520','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','Kimberly R. Whitsett is the incumbent City Clerk of Ecorse, Michigan, where she chairs the Ecorse Election Commission. She filed on March 4, 2026 as a candidate for City Clerk in the August 4, 2026 primary election, seeking a two-year term.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(330,5878,'Kerry Kehrer','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:18','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(331,5792,'Gayle Trotter','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(332,5880,'Patricia Lulko','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(333,5919,'Michael D. Bowdler','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(334,5789,'Stacy Wheeler','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(335,14670,'Bob Constan','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','Bob Constan is a longtime Dearborn Heights, Michigan politician and a candidate for City Council. He previously served in the Michigan House of Representatives representing the 16th district (Dearborn Heights, Garden City, Inkster, Allen Park) and has served as a Dearborn Heights City Council member, including as Chair Pro Tem.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(336,5916,'Kevin Trigge','N','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:19','','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(337,1,'Andrew J. Lievense','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Andrew J. Lievense is an incumbent judge on the Michigan Court of Appeals, First District, seeking election in 2026 to a partial term ending January 1, 2031. He was appointed to the seat by Governor Gretchen Whitmer on March 18, 2026, to fill the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Kirsten Frank Kelly. His appointed term runs until noon on January 1, 2027, after which he must stand for election to remain on the bench, which is the basis for his nonpartisan candidacy in the August 4, 2026 primary.\n\nLievense is from Northville, Michigan. Before his appointment, he served as an Assistant United States Attorney. Earlier in his career he was a litigation associate at Honigman LLP in Detroit and served as a judicial law clerk to U.S. District Judge Avern Cohn. He earned a bachelor\'s degree in politics and government and Spanish from Ohio Wesleyan University and a law degree from the University of Michigan.\n\nHe has been active in the legal community, serving as a member of the State Bar of Michigan\'s U.S. Courts Committee, as a past president of the Federal Bar Association, and as a volunteer with Big Brothers Big Sisters of Metro Detroit.\n\nUpon his appointment, Lievense stated, \"I am honored to serve the people of Michigan as a judge on the Michigan Court of Appeals, and grateful to Governor Whitmer for the responsibility she has entrusted to me.\" The Michigan Court of Appeals First District serves southwest Michigan counties.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, or campaign email was found, which is typical for recently appointed judges running to retain a seat. A clear, direct headshot URL from an official or campaign source was also not located. Note: a partial-term election date listed in the candidate filing (term ending 01/01/2031) differs from the January 1, 2027 expiration cited in the appointment announcement; both relate to the same First District seat he was appointed to fill.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(338,421,'Sara S. Lisznyai','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Sara S. Lisznyai is the sitting judge of Michigan\'s 1st Judicial Circuit Court, which serves Hillsdale County, and is running as the incumbent for a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. She earned her undergraduate degree from Eastern Michigan University in 1986 and her J.D. from Wayne State University Law School in 1990. She began practicing law in 1990 and moved to Hillsdale in 1996, where she practiced with the firm Marks & Lisznyai in Jonesville before her election to the bench. In November 2014 she was elected judge of the 2B District Court (Hillsdale County), serving a term that began January 1, 2015. She subsequently moved up to the Hillsdale County Circuit Court bench, where she now presides over felony criminal, civil, and family matters as Circuit Judge.\n\nDuring her tenure she has been active in problem-solving and specialty courts. In 2017 she helped establish the Hillsdale County Drug Court to address the local impact of the opioid crisis, and she has been credited locally with pioneering a court-connected program intended to help parents resolve conflicts and access services before family-law cases escalate. She has also served in an administrative capacity, including appointment as chief judge for the local courts.\n\nAs an incumbent judicial candidate, Lisznyai does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website, and no public campaign phone number or email was identified in the sources reviewed; this is typical for sitting nonpartisan judges who file by affidavit of incumbency. Michigan judicial candidates are barred from making pledges or promises inconsistent with impartial performance of judicial duties, so a detailed policy platform is not expected. Based on available sources, her record emphasizes criminal justice, treatment-oriented drug court programming, and family/juvenile matters in Hillsdale County. No specific endorsements were found in the sources reviewed. Note: contact details and a headshot URL could not be confirmed from authoritative public sources, so those fields are null.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(339,435,'Jennifer L. Smith-DenDooven','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Jennifer L. Smith (also appearing as Jennifer L. Smith-DenDooven) is an incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 2nd Circuit Court, which serves Berrien County, and is seeking election to a six-year term in 2026. She was appointed to the bench by Governor Rick Snyder in September 2018 and currently serves in the court\'s criminal division, having previously served in the family division.\n\nA native of Chelsea, Michigan, Smith graduated from Chelsea High School in 1989. She earned a Bachelor\'s Degree in Criminal Justice summa cum laude from Wayne State University in 1993, attending on a softball scholarship and receiving the Howard Donnelly Award as the top female graduate. She earned her Juris Doctorate from Wayne State University Law School in 1996. During law school she interned with the Wayne County Prosecutor\'s Office and clerked at Chambers Steiner, P.C. in Detroit.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Smith spent 21 years with the Berrien County Prosecutor\'s Office. She advanced from assistant prosecuting attorney (1997-2007) to Chief Trial Attorney (2007-2013) and then Chief Assistant Prosecuting Attorney (2013-2018), and provided training to local law enforcement throughout her tenure.\n\nSmith has been active in community service, having served on the boards of Safe Shelter, Inc. and the Children\'s Advocacy Center for Southwest Michigan, participated in the Southwest Michigan Human Trafficking Task Force, and volunteered with HOSTS and Junior Achievement. She has served on the Board of Directors for the Lakeshore Youth Baseball and Softball Association and is a member of the Michigan Judges Association, the State Bar of Michigan, and the Berrien County Bar Association. She resides in Lincoln Township with her husband Mike and their three children.\n\nAs a nonpartisan judicial incumbent, she is running by affidavit of candidacy for re-election. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone, email, or direct headshot image URL was located; the summary above is drawn from her official Berrien County court biography. Specific 2026 campaign priorities or endorsements were not found.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(340,33,'Aliyah S. Sabree','','https://judgesabree.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Aliyah S. Sabree is an incumbent judge of Michigan\'s Third Judicial Circuit Court (Wayne County), running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a partial term ending January 1, 2031. Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed Sabree to the 3rd Circuit Court in May 2025, with her term commencing June 9, 2025; the appointment filled a partial-term vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Charles Hegarty.\n\nBefore her circuit court appointment, Sabree served as a judge on Detroit\'s 36th District Court, where she was appointed to the bench in 2017 and served as chief judge pro tem alongside Chief Judge William C. McConico. Her earlier career included roles as associate general counsel at the Detroit Water and Sewerage Department, a liaison to the City Council in the Detroit Mayor\'s Office, and an Assistant Wayne County Prosecutor.\n\nSabree earned her Juris Doctor from Michigan State University College of Law and holds a Bachelor of Science in biology from Youngstown State University. As a circuit judge in Wayne County, she has presided over criminal matters, including high-profile cases reported in Detroit-area media.\n\nHer official campaign website, judgesabree.com, presents her under the banner \"Retain Judge Aliyah Sabree\" and includes a section to contact her campaign; however, specific campaign phone, email, and a direct headshot image URL could not be confirmed because the site was not reachable at the time of research. Detailed platform statements, priorities, and endorsements were likewise not independently confirmed and are therefore not asserted here. This summary is a best-effort synthesis from publicly available news and reference sources, and identity is confirmed by the matching office (3rd Circuit Court, Wayne County), incumbency, and partial-term details.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(341,14276,'John G. McBain Jr.','','','','517-788-4390','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','John G. McBain Jr. is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 4th Circuit Court, which serves Jackson County, and is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. He was first elected to the Circuit Court in November 2002 and took office in January 2003, and he served as the court\'s chief judge from January 2010 through December 2011.\n\nBefore joining the bench, McBain built a career in criminal law and public service. He graduated from Michigan State University in 1982 and earned his Juris Doctor from Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1987. He was admitted to the Florida Bar in 1988 and worked as an Assistant State Attorney in Florida from 1988 to 1993. In 1993 he returned to Michigan, was admitted to the State Bar of Michigan, and served as Chief Assistant Prosecutor for Jackson County. He was elected Jackson County Prosecuting Attorney in 1996, serving in that role until his election to the Circuit Court in 2002.\n\nAs a sitting circuit judge in Jackson County, McBain presides over the trial court that handles felony criminal cases, major civil litigation, and family matters in the jurisdiction. He files for re-election as an incumbent judge by affidavit, which is standard for sitting Michigan judges.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone, or campaign email was located in public sources; judicial incumbents in Michigan frequently run without a separate campaign site. The contact phone listed above (517-788-4390) is his chambers/court direct line at the Jackson County Circuit Court, 312 S. Jackson Street, Jackson, MI 49201. No specific 2026 platform statements, priorities, or endorsements were found in available sources, so none are asserted here. Identity is confirmed: the 4th Circuit Court corresponds to Jackson County, and McBain is the long-serving incumbent judge there, matching the office, district, and incumbent status in the candidate record.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.co.jackson.mi.us/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=10933'),(342,14276,'Allison L. Bates','','https://www.electallisonbates.com/','nbullinger@mijackson.org','517-788-4380','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Allison L. Bates is the incumbent candidate for Judge of the 4th Circuit Court in Michigan (the 4th Circuit covers Jackson County) in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary, seeking the partial term ending January 1, 2031. Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed Bates to the 4th Circuit Court in April 2026 to fill the seat vacated by Circuit Judge Thomas Wilson; her appointed term began April 13, 2026 and runs through January 1, 2027, making the 2026 election the contest to retain the seat for the remainder of the term.\n\nBefore her elevation to the Circuit Court, Bates served as a judge on the 12th District Court in Jackson County, a position to which she was first elected in 2020 and took the bench in 2021. On the District Court she presided over the domestic violence docket. Earlier in her career she worked at the 4th Circuit Court as a judicial referee handling juvenile matters, giving her prior experience with the court she now serves on.\n\nBates holds a Bachelor of Arts in economics from the University of Michigan and a Juris Doctor from the McGeorge School of Law at the University of the Pacific. She lives in Grass Lake. Outside the courtroom she is active in the dog-show community, serving as president of the Mid-Michigan Labrador Retriever Club and holding a judging license with the American Kennel Club.\n\nBates ran a campaign website (electallisonbates.com) during her District Court candidacy; at the time of this research the site was unreachable, so current campaign-specific platform statements, priorities, and endorsements for the 2026 Circuit Court race could not be verified. No detailed 2026 platform, endorsement list, or campaign contact email/phone was located beyond her official judicial chambers contact information at the Jackson County Circuit Court (312 South Jackson Street, 4th Floor, Jackson, MI 49201; chambers phone 517-788-4380, with judicial secretary Nadeen Bullinger reachable at nbullinger@mijackson.org). This summary is therefore primarily a factual record of her background and offices rather than a campaign platform.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(343,480,'Vicky L. Alspaugh','','','','269-945-1400','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Vicky L. Alspaugh is the incumbent judge of the 5th Judicial Circuit Court, which serves Barry County, Michigan, and is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed Alspaugh to the 5th Circuit Court bench effective January 1, 2020. She was subsequently elected in November 2020 and began her elected term on January 1, 2021.\n\nAlspaugh earned a Bachelor\'s degree in Criminal Justice from Michigan State University in 1985 and a Juris Doctor from Thomas M. Cooley Law School in January 1989. Her legal career has been rooted in public service: she began as an Assistant Prosecuting Attorney for Ogemaw County in 1989, then moved to Barry County as an Assistant Prosecuting Attorney in 1991. In 2000, she was selected to fill the newly created position of Attorney Referee/Attorney Magistrate for the county, and in 2011 the role of Probate Register was added to her responsibilities. She served in that combined capacity until her appointment to the circuit bench in 2020.\n\nAs a circuit court judge, she presides over felony criminal cases, higher-value civil matters, and family/domestic relations matters within Barry County\'s single-judge circuit. According to her official county biography, she and her husband Micheal have been married for many years and have two adult daughters.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone number, or campaign email was located in public sources; the contact information available is for the Barry County courthouse (220 W. State St., Hastings, MI 49058; 269-945-1400). A separately operated website critical of the judge (\"disqualifyalspaugh.com\") exists but is not affiliated with her campaign and is not a source of her platform. No formal campaign platform statements, priorities, or endorsements for the 2026 race were found in the sources reviewed, so this summary is limited to her verified professional background and judicial record. Identity is confirmed with high confidence based on the matching office (5th Circuit / Barry County), incumbent status, and judicial role.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.barrycounty.org/Courts%20&%20Law%20Enforcement/2020_Hon_VickyAlspaugh_Square.jpg'),(344,497,'Gary C. Giguere Jr.','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Gary C. Giguere Jr. is an incumbent judge on Michigan\'s 9th Circuit Court, which serves Kalamazoo County. He is running for re-election in the nonpartisan August 4, 2026 primary for a six-year term. Giguere was first appointed to the 9th Circuit Court by Governor Jennifer Granholm on February 21, 2007, and was subsequently elected to a full six-year term in November 2008, with re-elections following. He became presiding judge of the court\'s trial division in 2010 and served as Chief Circuit/Probate Judge Pro Tempore in 2020.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Giguere earned his B.A. from the University of Michigan-Flint in 1988 and his J.D. from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1992. He spent roughly a decade in private legal practice (reported as 1997-2007) prior to his judicial appointment.\n\nAs a sitting circuit judge filing as an incumbent for the 2026 cycle, Giguere does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign website, and no public campaign contact phone, email, or headshot URL was located in available sources. This is typical for incumbent judicial candidates in Michigan, who often file by affidavit of candidacy and run with limited or no separate campaign web presence. No specific 2026 platform statement, endorsements, or campaign materials were found online at the time of research. Voters seeking more information may consult the Kalamazoo County and 9th Circuit Court official pages or the candidate\'s Ballotpedia profile.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(345,14,'Manvel Trice III','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Manvel Trice III is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s Tenth Judicial Circuit Court, which serves Saginaw County, and is seeking election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. He was appointed to the Circuit Court by Governor Rick Snyder in 2017. Before that, he served as a judge on the Seventieth District Court in Saginaw County, having been appointed to that bench by Governor Snyder in 2016.\n\nPrior to his judicial career, Trice was an Assistant United States Attorney with the U.S. Attorney\'s Office for the Eastern District of Michigan beginning in 2015. Before that, he worked for approximately four years (2011-2015) as an assistant prosecutor in the Saginaw County Prosecuting Attorney\'s Office, serving in the Major Crime Unit.\n\nTrice earned a bachelor\'s degree in criminal justice from Saginaw Valley State University in 1998 and a Juris Doctor from Michigan State University College of Law in 2001.\n\nOn the bench, he presides over the Saginaw County Sobriety Treatment Court, for which he secured provisional certification from the Michigan Supreme Court in February 2018, reflecting an interest in treatment-oriented and rehabilitative approaches within the criminal justice system. He is a member of the Saginaw County Bar Association.\n\nAs a sitting incumbent in a nonpartisan judicial race, Trice does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign website, and no public campaign contact phone or email was identified. No formal 2026 campaign platform statement or list of endorsements was located. The information above is drawn from his official county court biography and bar association listing rather than campaign materials.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(346,423,'Brittany A. Bulleit','','','','906-482-5420','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Brittany A. Bulleit is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 12th Circuit Court, which serves Baraga, Houghton, and Keweenaw counties in the Upper Peninsula. She was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in 2023 to fill the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Charles Goodman. She is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary to retain the seat for a full six-year term.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Bulleit served as the elected Houghton County Prosecuting Attorney, a role she held beginning in 2019. Prior to that, she worked as chief assistant prosecutor in Houghton County for roughly a decade, and earlier served as a judicial advisory assistant in the Genesee County Circuit Court.\n\nBulleit earned her Bachelor of Arts from DePauw University and her Juris Doctor from Michigan State University College of Law. She has been active in the Copper Country community, having served on the board of Copper Country Habitat for Humanity and as vice president of the Houghton Hancock Lions Club.\n\nAs a circuit court judge, she presides over felony criminal cases, higher-value civil matters, and family-division proceedings across the three-county jurisdiction. Local coverage in 2026 noted her involvement in community corrections programming in the region.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located through public searches; judicial candidates in Michigan\'s nonpartisan races frequently do not maintain separate campaign sites. The contact information available is for her official court chambers at the 12th Circuit Court, 401 E. Houghton Avenue, Houghton, MI 49931, phone 906-482-5420. No specific platform statement, endorsements, or campaign priorities were found online beyond her record as an appointed incumbent judge and former county prosecutor. This summary is drawn from official court directory listings, regional news coverage of her appointment, and her Ballotpedia profile.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(347,15,'Kevin A. Elsenheimer','','','','231-922-4701','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Kevin A. Elsenheimer is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 13th Circuit Court, which serves Antrim, Grand Traverse, and Leelanau counties. He is running unopposed-style as the incumbent in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. He has served as Chief Judge of the 13th Circuit Court and the associated Antrim, Grand Traverse, and Leelanau Probate Courts.\n\nElsenheimer was first appointed to the 13th Circuit Court bench by Governor Rick Snyder on January 9, 2017, filling the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Philip Rodgers. He subsequently won election to the seat in 2018 and was retained in 2020. He is widely known in the region for presiding over the high-profile Antrim County election lawsuit (Bailey v. Antrim County) following the 2020 election, in which he handled litigation concerning a forensic examination of Dominion voting equipment.\n\nBefore joining the judiciary, Elsenheimer served as a Republican member of the Michigan House of Representatives, representing the 105th District (covering northern Michigan) from 2005 to 2011, where he rose to House Republican Floor Leader. After leaving the Legislature and prior to his judicial appointment, he served as Executive Director of the Michigan State Housing Development Authority (MSHDA). His earlier career included private legal practice in northern Michigan.\n\nAs a sitting circuit judge, Elsenheimer\'s role is nonpartisan, and judicial ethics rules limit the kind of campaign platform and policy advocacy typical of other races. He does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website; voters can find official information through the 13th Circuit Court and Grand Traverse County government resources. His judicial contact is via the 13th Circuit Court in Traverse City (Grand Traverse County Governmental Center).\n\nNote: This summary is synthesized from publicly available biographical and news sources confirming his identity as the incumbent 13th Circuit Court judge. Specific 2026 campaign messaging, endorsements, and contact details beyond the court office were not located, consistent with a sitting nonpartisan judge seeking reelection.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(348,424,'Kathy Hoogstra','','','','231-724-6251','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Kathy L. Hoogstra is an incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 14th Circuit Court, which serves Muskegon County, and is a nonpartisan candidate for re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary (six-year term). She presides over Family Division matters, including domestic relations, neglect and abuse, and delinquency cases, sitting in Courtroom C at the Muskegon County courthouse (990 Terrace Street, Muskegon, MI).\n\nHoogstra was first appointed to the 14th Circuit Court by Governor Rick Snyder on May 20, 2013, filling the seat vacated by the retirement of Judge John Ruck. She served out the remainder of that unexpired term and was subsequently elected to a full term of her own on November 4, 2014, taking office January 1, 2015. She has continued to serve on the court since then.\n\nHer professional background includes earning an undergraduate degree from Calvin College and a J.D. from the Illinois Institute of Technology\'s Chicago-Kent College of Law. Before becoming a judge, she worked as a judicial law clerk for the 14th Circuit Court, as a public defender, and as a family court referee for Muskegon County, giving her substantial experience in the family-law areas she now oversees from the bench.\n\nNo active 2026 campaign website, dedicated campaign phone, or campaign email was located in public sources; as a sitting judge, her publicly available contact point is the 14th Circuit Court office (231-724-6251). No specific 2026 platform statement or endorsements were found beyond her record as an incumbent seeking another term. This summary is a factual synthesis of her judicial record and background rather than a campaign platform.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(349,425,'Zachary William Stempien','','','circuitcourt@branchcounty.gov','517-279-4304','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Zachary W. Stempien is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 15th Circuit Court, which serves Branch County, and is running for a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 primary (nonpartisan race). A lifelong Coldwater resident and 2007 graduate of Coldwater High School, he was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in April 2026 to fill the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge William O\'Grady. He took his oath early to comply with state law and his judicial duties officially began April 13, 2026.\n\nStempien earned a Bachelor of Arts in Organizational Administration from Central Michigan University and his Juris Doctor from Western Michigan University Cooley Law School. He began his legal career as a law clerk for Judge O\'Grady while in law school. Before his appointment, he served as Branch County\'s elected Prosecuting Attorney beginning in 2020, where he handled high-profile felony cases and argued before the Michigan Supreme Court.\n\nStempien announced his candidacy in December 2025 and filed to run for the full term. He has been endorsed by former 15th Circuit Court Judge William O\'Grady, the predecessor whose seat he now holds. Beyond his legal career, Stempien is active in the Coldwater community, serving as a junior varsity baseball coach at Coldwater High School and coaching youth football, baseball, and basketball in Coldwater and Tekonsha.\n\nNote: No dedicated 2026 campaign website was found in available sources. The contact phone and email listed are for the 15th Circuit Court chambers (general court channels), not a personal campaign line, as judicial candidates typically route inquiries through the court. No direct headshot image URL was located; news coverage includes photos but no clean direct portrait link from his official bio. Detailed platform/priority statements specific to his campaign were not found beyond his record as prosecutor and his recent appointment.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(350,433,'Michael Huber','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Michael (Mike) Alan Huber is a candidate in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary for Judge of the 18th Circuit Court, a non-incumbent six-year-term position. The 18th Judicial Circuit serves Bay County, Michigan. He is running as a nonpartisan candidate, as is standard for Michigan judicial races.\n\nHuber is an attorney based in Bay City, Michigan (1230 Washington Ave, Bay City, MI 48708). He was admitted to the State Bar of Michigan in 2012. Public records indicate he works in the Bay County Public Defender\'s office, where he supervises the office and primarily handles felony cases in District and Circuit Court. This criminal trial experience in the same court he is seeking to join is directly relevant to the office sought.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone number, campaign email, or candidate headshot photo was located through public web searches. As is common for local trial-court judicial candidates, his online footprint consists mainly of attorney directory listings (Martindale, Avvo, Lawyer.com) and references to his role at the Bay County Public Defender\'s office rather than campaign-specific materials.\n\nNo specific platform statements, stated priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources, so none are asserted here. Identity is confirmed by the match between this candidate (18th Circuit Court / Bay City) and the Bay City attorney Michael Alan Huber who practices criminal law in Bay County\'s Circuit Court; confidence is high on identity but the candidate-specific campaign details (website/contact/photo/platform) appear not to be published online at this time. Note: there are several unrelated individuals named \"Michael Huber\" who serve or served as judges in other states (e.g., Wyoming, Illinois) — those are not this candidate.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(351,434,'David A. Thompson','','https://www.reelectjudgedavidthompson.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','David A. Thompson is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 19th Circuit Court, which serves Benzie and Manistee counties. He is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. Thompson was first elected to the 19th Circuit Court on November 4, 2014, taking office January 1, 2015. On January 1, 2016, the Michigan Supreme Court appointed him Chief Judge, a role in which he provides administrative leadership and oversight for the 19th Circuit Court, the 85th District Court, and the Probate Courts serving Manistee and Benzie counties.\n\nThompson earned his undergraduate degree from Lake Superior State University and his J.D. from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1993. He served in the United States Coast Guard Reserve from 1986 to 1994. Before his election to the bench, Thompson served as director of the 19th Circuit Court\'s Family Division.\n\nHe maintains a campaign site, \"Re-Elect Judge David Thompson\" (reelectjudgedavidthompson.com), focused on his record on the 19th Circuit Court. Specific 2026 platform priorities, endorsements, and direct campaign contact details could not be retrieved (the campaign site refused automated fetching), so this summary draws on his judicial record and public biography rather than detailed 2026 campaign messaging.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(352,437,'Jon Hulsing','','','circuitcourt@miottawa.org','(616) 846-8320','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Jon H. Hulsing is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 20th Circuit Court, which serves Ottawa County, and is seeking re-election (nonpartisan, six-year term) in the August 4, 2026 primary. He was appointed to the bench by Governor Jennifer Granholm on April 26, 2006, to succeed retiring Judge Wesley Nykamp, and has been re-elected since, most recently winning unopposed in 2014. His docket includes both criminal and civil matters, and he has served as Chief Judge pro tem of the court.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Hulsing earned his undergraduate degree from Grand Valley State University and his J.D. from Thomas M. Cooley Law School. He worked in private practice before serving as an assistant prosecuting attorney in Ottawa County from 1995 until his 2006 judicial appointment.\n\nHulsing has held a statewide judicial-governance role: he was appointed to the Michigan Judicial Tenure Commission as the commissioner representing the state\'s circuit court judges, beginning a three-year term on January 1, 2019, and has served as the commission\'s chairperson.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign-specific email, or campaign phone number was located. As a sitting judge running in a nonpartisan judicial race, his public-facing contact information is through the 20th Circuit Court (414 Washington Ave, Suite 300, Grand Haven, MI 49417; (616) 846-8320; circuitcourt@miottawa.org). No specific campaign platform statements, priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources; this summary is based on his judicial biography and public record rather than campaign materials.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://miottawa.org/wp-content/uploads/Jon-H.-Hulsing.jpg'),(353,441,'Timothy C. Wrathell','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Timothy C. Wrathell is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 24th Circuit Court, which serves Sanilac County. He is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term, listed as the incumbent. Wrathell was born and raised in Sanilac County and resides in Sandusky. He first won election to the Sanilac County Circuit Court bench after running in the August 2020 primary.\n\nWrathell brings an unusual educational background to the bench. He earned a Bachelor of Science in Surveying Engineering from Ferris State University and a Master of Science in Engineering (Civil Engineering) from Purdue University before earning his Juris Doctor from Western Michigan University Cooley Law School. Prior to becoming a judge, his legal career included work as a litigator, mediator, case evaluator, and arbitrator, with jury trial experience in District, Probate, and Circuit Courts.\n\nAs circuit judge, he presides over felony criminal matters and major civil cases in Sanilac County, and local news coverage reflects his involvement in significant sentencing decisions in the county.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, email, or headshot image was located in this research. A candidate campaign committee, the \"Committee to Elect Timothy C. Wrathell for Circuit Court Judge,\" is registered in Michigan (per Transparency USA), but no direct public contact details were confirmed. Voters seeking current information may consult the Sanilac County Circuit Court official website or the Michigan Bureau of Elections candidate listing. This summary is limited by the available public information; specific 2026 platform positions, priorities, or endorsements were not found and are not asserted here.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(354,442,'Matt Wiese','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Matthew \"Matt\" Wiese is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 25th Circuit Court, which serves Marquette County, and is seeking a full term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed Wiese to the circuit bench in October 2023 to fill the vacancy created by the retirement of Judge Jennifer Mazzuchi. He was invested and sworn in before a packed Marquette County courtroom in late 2023/early 2024.\n\nBefore his appointment, Wiese spent more than 30 years in the Marquette County Prosecuting Attorney\'s Office, serving as the elected Marquette County Prosecuting Attorney. He previously held the role of Chief Assistant Prosecuting Attorney (2009-2011). Earlier in his career he worked as a staff attorney for the Battered Women\'s Justice Project and as Associate Dean of Students at Northern Michigan University. In 2022 he received the Career Prosecutor Service Award recognizing three decades of prosecutorial service.\n\nWiese earned a Bachelor of Science from Northern Michigan University and his Juris Doctor from Vermont Law School. During his prosecutorial career he authored or co-authored grant proposals under the federal OVW Rural Sexual Assault, Domestic Violence, Dating Violence, and Stalking Grant Program and the Blueprint for Safety initiative, and helped develop countywide law enforcement domestic violence policies for Marquette County.\n\nIn remarks around his appointment, Wiese emphasized fairness and respect on the bench, stating he would \"strive to make decisions that are fair and just, while treating all who come before the Court with dignity and respect.\" He noted a particular focus on children and families, expressing concern that \"kids don\'t get lost in the process\" in family law matters.\n\nAs a sitting circuit judge in a nonpartisan judicial race, Wiese does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website, and no public campaign phone, email, or headshot URL was located. Official contact for his courtroom would run through the Marquette County Circuit Court. This summary is drawn from Upper Michigan news coverage of his 2023 appointment and 2024 investiture; no detailed 2026-specific campaign platform was found online as of the research date.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(355,443,'K. Edward Black','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','K. Edward \"Ed\" Black is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 26th Circuit Court, which serves Alpena and Montmorency counties. He is seeking re-election to a six-year term as a nonpartisan judicial candidate in the August 4, 2026 primary.\n\nBlack was appointed to the 26th Circuit Court by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in February 2020, filling the vacancy created by the retirement of Judge Michael Mack. He won election to the seat later in 2020 and has served on the bench since his appointment. The Michigan Supreme Court subsequently named him chief judge of the 26th Circuit Court, the 88th District Court, and the Alpena and Montmorency County Probate Courts. He also presides over the court\'s Family Division for Montmorency County.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Black built a career in public-sector and private legal work in northeast Michigan. He served as the elected Alpena County Prosecutor beginning in 2009. Earlier in his career he worked as an assistant prosecutor in Montmorency County and maintained a private law practice. He also holds a commission as a judge advocate general (JAG) officer in the U.S. Army Reserve. He is a graduate of Michigan State University College of Law.\n\nIn describing his approach to public service, Black has emphasized listening to and genuinely caring about the people he serves, stating that serving the community means \"not just hearing, but actually listening to each individual,\" and a willingness to pursue what is right over what is easy.\n\nBlack lives in Alpena with his wife, Meaghan, and their three children.\n\nAs is typical for sitting trial-court judges in Michigan, no dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, or campaign email was located in available public sources. Voters in Alpena and Montmorency counties can find official ballot and court information through the Michigan court system and county clerk offices. This summary is synthesized from local news coverage and official court listings; the campaign-specific contact details and any 2026 endorsements or platform statements were not available at the time of research.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://ogden_images.s3.amazonaws.com/www.thealpenanews.com/images/2020/02/14125046/Ed-Black.jpg'),(356,444,'Jason J. Elmore','','','circuit@missaukee.org','(231) 839-4967','','2026-06-24 13:24:20','Jason J. Elmore is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 28th Circuit Court, which serves Wexford and Missaukee Counties, and is running in the August 4, 2026 primary to retain the nonpartisan circuit judge seat (six-year term). He currently serves as Chief Circuit Court Judge and Presiding Family Court Judge for the Wexford/Missaukee circuit. Prior to taking the bench, Elmore worked as a prosecutor; local reporting (Cadillac News) covered his initial campaign for the 28th Circuit Court judge\'s seat.\n\nIn his administrative role, Elmore has chaired Wexford County\'s Courthouse Security Committee, which has worked to improve courthouse safety through measures such as upgraded scanning technology, window tinting, improved holding cells, and revised courtroom seating. He has also been active in addressing pandemic-era case backlogs as Northern Michigan courts resumed in-person proceedings.\n\nThe court maintains a public-facing YouTube channel (\"Judge Elmore\") featuring circuit court proceedings. A 2025 Michigan Court of Appeals decision (People v. Plomb) was critical of the trial judge\'s conduct in that case; this is noted here only as part of the public record and not as a characterization of his candidacy.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, personal campaign phone, personal email, or candidate headshot was located in public sources. The contact details provided above are for the 28th Circuit Court office (Missaukee County location). As an incumbent judge, Elmore appears on the ballot under the nonpartisan judicial section. Specific platform statements, priorities, or endorsements for the 2026 campaign were not found in available sources, so this summary reflects his record and current office rather than stated campaign positions.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(357,445,'Shannon L.W. Schlegel','','https://shannonschlegelforcircuitcourtjudge.com/','circuitcourt@gratiotmi.com','989-449-4225','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Shannon L.W. Schlegel is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 29th Judicial Circuit Court, which serves Clinton and Gratiot Counties, and is running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. She was first invested as a 29th Circuit Court judge on September 10, 2021. On the bench she is assigned to both the Civil and Criminal Divisions and serves as a Family Court judge under the \"one family, one judge\" model; she alternates weeks between the two counties, sitting in Gratiot County during the first and third weeks of each month and in Clinton County during the second and fourth weeks, sharing the circuit with Judge Cori Barkman.\n\nBefore her appointment, Schlegel practiced law as the owner of Shannon L.W. Schlegel, PLLC beginning in 2001. According to publicly available professional listings, she also served as a Case Evaluator for civil litigation cases and worked as a Special Prosecutor for the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services in child welfare cases beginning in 2009, reflecting a focus on family and child-welfare matters that carries into her current role as a Family Court judge.\n\nSchlegel maintains an official 2026 campaign website (shannonschlegelforcircuitcourtjudge.com) and has a registered candidate campaign committee, \"Shannon Schlegel for Circuit Court Judge,\" on file with Michigan campaign-finance reporting. Detailed platform statements, priorities, and endorsements were not available in the sources reviewed; as an incumbent judge running nonpartisan, her candidacy emphasizes continued service on the 29th Circuit bench. The phone number and email listed here are the official 29th Circuit Court contacts in Gratiot County rather than dedicated campaign contacts; no separate campaign phone or email was located. This summary is limited to verifiable public information and does not include unverified platform claims or endorsements.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.gratiotmi.com/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=8519'),(358,54,'Patricia Tremblay','','','','517-483-6500','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Patricia A. Tremblay is a judge on Michigan\'s 30th Judicial Circuit Court, which serves Ingham County (the Lansing area). Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed her to the bench in February 2025, with her term commencing March 3, 2025. She is running as the incumbent in the August 4, 2026 primary for the remaining partial term (two years ending January 1, 2029). She is permanently assigned to the court\'s Family Division.\n\nBefore her judicial appointment, Tremblay spent more than two decades in Michigan public service across both the legislative and executive branches. She worked in the Michigan House of Representatives for nearly twenty years in a variety of roles, including Chief Legal Counsel, and most recently served as a staff attorney/legislative affairs official in the Governor\'s executive office. As a trained lawyer, she has developed experience in statutory interpretation, ethics, juvenile justice, election law, and complex civil and administrative matters. She earned her Juris Doctor from Michigan State University College of Law.\n\nThis is a best-effort summary drawn from her official Ingham County court biography and the Governor\'s appointment announcement. As is common for sitting judges, no dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or detailed published platform was found; her court bio\'s education, professional associations, and community involvement sections were still marked \"coming soon\" at the time of research. Specific campaign priorities or endorsements were not located and are not asserted here. The contact phone listed (517-483-6500) is the general 30th Judicial Circuit Court number, not a dedicated campaign line.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://docs.ingham.org/Department/30th%20Judicial%20Circuit%20Court/images/Judge.Tremblay_04.16.25.jpg'),(359,466,'Daniel A. Damman','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Daniel A. \"Dan\" Damman is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 31st Circuit Court, which serves St. Clair County, and is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. He was first elected to the circuit bench in 2020, when he ran unopposed, and took office in January 2021.\n\nDamman is a longtime St. Clair County figure with a substantial public-service record before joining the judiciary. He served three terms as Mayor of the City of Marysville. Professionally, he spent his pre-judicial career as a trial attorney in private practice, work he has described as a career he cherished, and he draws on the litigation and trial skills he developed during those years in his judicial role serving the people of St. Clair County.\n\nHis educational background is rooted locally: he began his higher education at St. Clair County Community College (SC4), crediting the college with giving him a cost-effective start and supportive faculty. He transferred to Michigan State University, earning a B.A. in psychology with a secondary major in law and society, and then attended Wayne State University Law School, graduating with a J.D. in 2002. His Michigan attorney bar number is 64585.\n\nAs an incumbent circuit judge, Damman presides over felony criminal cases, civil litigation, and family-division matters in St. Clair County. Public reporting reflects his handling of criminal sentencings on the circuit bench. Like most sitting judges, he runs on his judicial record, experience, and qualifications rather than a partisan platform, consistent with the nonpartisan nature of Michigan judicial elections.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, or campaign email was located in available sources; incumbent Michigan circuit judges frequently do not maintain standalone campaign sites. Voters seeking official filing and ballot information can consult the St. Clair County Clerk\'s Office. This summary is a best-effort synthesis of publicly available biographical and news sources and does not include any specific endorsements, as none were found.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://sc4.edu/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/Daniel-Damman-e1673878299375.jpg'),(360,467,'Michael K. Pope','','','','(906) 663-4211','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Michael K. Pope is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 32nd Circuit Court, which serves Gogebic and Ontonagon counties in the western Upper Peninsula. He is filing as an incumbent for a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan judicial primary. Pope was appointed to the bench by Governor Rick Snyder on January 5, 2016, to replace retiring Judge Roy Gotham, and won election later that year (November 8, 2016) to complete the term. He has served continuously on the 32nd Circuit Court since 2016 and also handles probate matters for Gogebic and Ontonagon counties.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Pope practiced law for more than two decades. He earned a bachelor\'s degree in biology and history from Alma College and a Juris Doctor from the University of Detroit Mercy School of Law. He was an attorney with the law firm of Dean and Pope from 1993 until his judicial appointment in 2016, and has taught criminal law at Gogebic Community College.\n\nThe 32nd Circuit Court is located at 200 N. Moore St., Bessemer, MI 49911 (phone (906) 663-4211; fax (906) 667-1102). As a sitting judge running for retention/re-election, Pope does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website, and no campaign-specific phone, email, or headshot was located in public sources; the listed contact is the official court office. No specific 2026 campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were found in available sources. This summary is based on Ballotpedia and the official Gogebic County court website; the campaign-specific details are limited because, as is common for incumbent judicial candidates in small jurisdictions, little dedicated campaign material is published online.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(361,468,'Roy Charles Hayes III','','','circuitcourt@charlevoixcounty.org','231-547-7243','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Roy Charles Hayes III (Roy C. Hayes III) is the incumbent Chief Judge of Michigan\'s 33rd Circuit Court, which serves Charlevoix County, and is running for re-election to a six-year term in the nonpartisan judicial race on the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary ballot. He was first elected to the circuit court in 2014.\n\nBefore taking the bench, Hayes practiced law as the owner of The Hayes Law Firm in Charlevoix, Michigan, and served as a public administrator for Charlevoix County. He began his legal career in 1994 as a law clerk to former Missouri Supreme Court Justice William Ray Price, and subsequently practiced in a partnership with his father until 2000. He is a member of the Emmet-Charlevoix Bar Association.\n\nAs a circuit judge, Hayes handles felony criminal cases, civil litigation, and family matters for the county. He has been active in establishing and presiding over a substance abuse treatment court program in Charlevoix County, an effort aimed at ending what he has described as the \"revolving-door cycle\" of controlled-substance and drunk-driving offenders. The treatment court is intended to serve roughly 10 to 15 participants per year through court-supervised treatment rather than repeated incarceration.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone number, or campaign email could be located for Hayes, which is typical for sitting Michigan trial-court judges seeking re-election. The contact details listed here are for the 33rd Circuit Court itself (301 State St., Charlevoix, MI 49720), not a campaign organization. No specific 2026 platform statement or list of endorsements was found in available public sources beyond his record on the bench. This summary is necessarily brief given the limited campaign-specific material currently online.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(362,469,'Matthew J. Stewart','','','','(989) 743-2222','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Matthew J. Stewart is the incumbent Chief Judge of the 35th Judicial Circuit Court in Michigan, which serves Shiawassee County. He is seeking re-election to a six-year term as Circuit Judge in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Stewart was first elected to the 35th Circuit Court on November 4, 2014, taking office January 1, 2015, and has since served as the presiding judicial officer for the circuit.\n\nAccording to his official court biography, Stewart received his J.D. from Thomas M. Cooley Law School. Before joining the bench, he worked as an attorney in private practice, including criminal defense work. He served in the United States Navy and received an honorable discharge after serving during Operation Desert Shield / Desert Storm.\n\nAs Chief Judge, Stewart oversees the court\'s Civil, Criminal, and Family divisions, which handle civil cases exceeding $25,000 and felony criminal matters. He maintains administrative oversight of court-related departments including the Friend of the Court Office and the County Jury Commission, and presides over Family Court matters such as divorce, paternity, child support, and child welfare cases. Stewart has been closely involved with the Shiawassee County Drug Court since its founding around 2010, when he first participated as a defense attorney placing a client into treatment; the program celebrated its 10-year anniversary in recent years. He has also spoken publicly on sentencing-guideline issues in local cases.\n\nHis office is located at the Circuit Courthouse, 208 North Shiawassee Street, 2nd Floor, Corunna, MI 48817, with a public phone of (989) 743-2222.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located; the contact information above is for his official judicial office. As a sitting judge in a nonpartisan race, Stewart does not appear to maintain a separate campaign site, which is typical for incumbent judicial candidates. Information here is synthesized from his official Shiawassee County court bio and public records; no specific 2026 platform statement or endorsements were found.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://shiawassee.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Judge-Stewart-e1776263772212.jpg'),(363,470,'Kelly Ward','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Kelly Ward is a Michigan attorney and judicial officer running as a nonpartisan, non-incumbent candidate for Judge of the 36th Circuit Court (Van Buren County) in the August 4, 2026 primary, for a 6-year term. Hartford, her listed city, is in Van Buren County, consistent with this office.\n\nWard earned her law degree from Thomas M. Cooley Law School (2011) and practiced in Three Rivers, focusing on estate planning, family law, and probate matters. Since 2021 she has served as the Family Division Referee (attorney referee) for the 36th Circuit Court in Van Buren County, the same court she now seeks to join as judge. Her appointment was formalized by court administrative order (LAO-C36-2021-05). In that role she presides over domestic relations, child protective, and juvenile delinquency matters, and has reportedly conducted thousands of hearings. She has led problem-solving/specialty courts including Family Reunification, Family Recovery, and Adult Recovery courts. She is a member of the Referee\'s Association of Michigan and received that group\'s most valuable membership award for a non-committee member in 2024.\n\nIn 2024, Ward ran for St. Joseph County Probate Judge, seeking to succeed retiring Judge David Tomlinson. In that campaign she emphasized a commitment to fairness and impartiality, protecting vulnerable community members (children, the elderly, and individuals with developmental disabilities), streamlining truancy and guardianship proceedings, improving court accessibility, and collaborating with community stakeholders. She described her career as centered on \"helping those who cannot help themselves.\" These themes are likely to carry into her 2026 circuit court candidacy, though no 2026-specific campaign platform was located in available public sources.\n\nNote: A campaign website used during her 2024 probate run (electkellywardprobatejudge.com) appears to be offline, and no 2026 campaign website, public contact email/phone, or current headshot image URL could be confirmed. As a sitting court referee, she also has an official court/staff directory presence in Van Buren County. Identity confidence is high based on the match between her referee role in the 36th Circuit Court, the Van Buren County/Hartford location, and the judicial office sought.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(364,471,'Sarah S. Lincoln','','','','(269) 969-6502','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Sarah S. Lincoln is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 37th Judicial Circuit Court, which serves Calhoun County, and is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. She is based at the Calhoun County Justice Center in Battle Creek and resides in Marshall, Michigan.\n\nLincoln earned a B.A. from the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor (1995) and a J.D. from Wayne State University Law School in Detroit (2000). Before joining the bench, she built a career as a prosecutor: she served in the Muskegon County Prosecutor\'s Office (2000-2001) and then spent over a decade as an Assistant Calhoun County Prosecuting Attorney (2001-2014). She has also taught as an adjunct instructor in the Criminal Justice Program at Kellogg Community College.\n\nLincoln was elected to the 37th Circuit Court in November 2014, succeeding Judge Kingsley, and took office in January 2015. With that election she became the first female circuit judge in Calhoun County history and one of only a handful of women to have served as a judge in any Calhoun County court. She has served as Presiding Circuit Court Judge since 2016. She is a member of the State Bar of Michigan and the Calhoun County Bar Association.\n\nAs an incumbent circuit judge running a nonpartisan re-election campaign, Lincoln does not appear to maintain a dedicated public campaign website, and no public campaign-specific contact email or phone was located; the contact information available is her official judicial chambers line at the Calhoun County Justice Center, (269) 969-6502. No specific 2026 campaign platform statements or endorsements were found in available public sources, so this summary reflects her judicial record and background rather than campaign claims.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(365,473,'Michael R. Olsaver','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Michael R. Olsaver is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 39th Circuit Court, which serves Lenawee County, and is seeking a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. He was appointed to the bench in 2019 by Governor Gretchen Whitmer, sworn in on April 1, 2019, to fill a vacancy on the 39th Circuit Court. The appointment initially filled a term scheduled to expire at the start of 2021, and he has since continued serving on the court.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Olsaver practiced law as an attorney with the firm Robison, Curphey and O\'Connell. He was also active in his community, serving in connection with the City of Adrian Downtown Development Authority. According to publicly available biographical information, he earned his bachelor\'s degree from Michigan State University and his Juris Doctor from DePaul University College of Law.\n\nAs a sitting circuit judge, Olsaver hears felony criminal cases, higher-value civil disputes, and family-division matters within Lenawee County. Like most Michigan judicial candidates, he runs on a nonpartisan basis, and as an incumbent he appears on the ballot with the incumbency designation.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located. He maintains a public-facing \"Judge Michael R. Olsaver\" presence on Facebook and a YouTube channel under the same name, which are tied to his judicial role rather than an official campaign organization. No public campaign contact phone number, campaign email address, or direct headshot image URL was found in the sources reviewed.\n\nThis summary is a factual, best-effort synthesis based on his 2019 gubernatorial appointment announcement, the Lenawee County court staff directory, and related public listings. No specific 2026 campaign platform, endorsements, or policy statements were located, which is typical for incumbent trial-court judges seeking re-election.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(366,475,'Mike Hodges','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Mike (Michael) Hodges is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 40th Circuit Court, which serves Lapeer County, and is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. He first won the seat in 2020, defeating then-incumbent Judge Byron Konschuh in a nonpartisan race (reported as roughly 23,687 votes to 14,775) after a three-way primary. His current six-year term expires at the end of 2026, consistent with this re-election bid.\n\nBefore taking the bench, Hodges built a roughly 25-year legal career rooted in Lapeer County. He worked in private practice and spent extensive time in prosecution: he served with the Lapeer County Prosecutor\'s Office (1996–2009), rising to chief assistant prosecutor (2005–2009); the Tuscola County Prosecutor\'s Office (2012–2013); and returned to the Lapeer County Prosecutor\'s Office (2013–2017). From January 2017 until his election to the bench, he served as Lapeer County Friend of the Court, where he managed the office\'s budget and staff. He is also a past president of the Lapeer County Bar Association.\n\nLocal reporting from his 2020 campaign emphasized his deep local roots, prosecutorial and family-law (Friend of the Court) experience, and broad familiarity with the county\'s legal community as reasons voters supported him. As a sitting circuit judge, he handles felony criminal cases, higher-value civil matters, and family-division proceedings within the 40th Circuit.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located in this research. A Facebook page titled \"Mike Hodges for Judge\" exists from his prior candidacy but could not be independently confirmed as an active 2026 campaign presence, and no public campaign phone number, email, or direct headshot image URL was found. As a judicial incumbent filing for re-election, Hodges may not maintain a separate campaign site; voters seeking official contact information can reach his chambers through the 40th Circuit Court / Lapeer County government. No specific 2026 platform statements, priorities, or endorsements were found in available sources; this summary is therefore a factual background synthesis rather than a campaign platform.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(367,62,'Christopher S. Ninomiya','','','','(906) 774-2266','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Christopher S. Ninomiya is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 41st Circuit Court, which serves Dickinson, Iron, and Menominee counties in the Upper Peninsula. He is running unopposed-style as an incumbent for a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. The 41st Circuit Court handles civil cases seeking damages over $25,000, all felony criminal matters, personal protection order cases, and family/domestic matters; he serves alongside Chief Judge Mary Brouillette Barglind.\n\nNinomiya was appointed to the 41st Circuit Court by Governor Rick Snyder, taking office in January 2018, and was sworn in shortly thereafter. Before joining the bench, he served as the elected Dickinson County Prosecuting Attorney, having worked in that prosecutor\'s office since 1993. He earned a B.A. in Business and Pre-Law from Michigan State University in 1990 and a Juris Doctor from Wayne State University Law School in 1993. He is based in Iron Mountain.\n\nBeyond his trial court duties, Ninomiya has served on statewide bodies. He was appointed (and later reappointed) to the Governor\'s Task Force on Child Abuse and Neglect, representing criminal court judges, with a term running through December 31, 2026. He has remained actively engaged in criminal sentencing and circuit court matters into 2026.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone, or campaign email was located in public sources; as a sitting judge running for retention/re-election in a nonpartisan judicial race, he does not appear to maintain a public campaign site. The contact number listed above is the official 41st Circuit Court office in Iron Mountain (705 S. Stephenson St., Iron Mountain, MI 49801), not a campaign line. No headshot image was found at a stable direct URL. No specific 2026 campaign platform statements or endorsements were found; this summary is drawn from his judicial record and official court information rather than from campaign materials.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(368,476,'Michael J. Beale','','','pczerwinski@co.midland.mi.us','(989) 832-6735','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Michael J. Beale is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 42nd Circuit Court, which serves Midland County, and is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary for a six-year term. The seat is nonpartisan.\n\nBeale was appointed to the 42nd Circuit Court by Governor Jennifer Granholm on October 23, 2007, to fill the vacancy left by retiring Judge Paul Clulo. He assumed office on December 3, 2007, was elected to a full term on November 4, 2008, and was re-elected on November 4, 2014, with subsequent terms following.\n\nBeale earned his bachelor\'s degree from Michigan State University in 1986 and his J.D. from the University of Detroit School of Law in 1990. He began his legal career in 1990 as a judicial law clerk for Michigan Supreme Court Justice James Brickley. In 1992 he joined the Detroit firm Plunkett & Cooney, P.C. as an associate attorney, where he practiced until 1995. He then practiced with the Midland firm of Handlon, Eastman, DeWitt & Beale until his appointment to the bench in 2007.\n\nThe 42nd Circuit Court is located at 301 W. Main Street, Midland, MI 48640. As a circuit court judge, Beale presides over felony criminal cases and civil cases exceeding $25,000, among other matters within the court\'s general jurisdiction.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign-specific phone, or campaign email was located; judicial incumbents in Michigan frequently run without a separate campaign web presence. The contact information provided reflects the official 42nd Circuit Court (court administrator), not a campaign office. No public platform statement, endorsements, or campaign priorities specific to the 2026 election were found in available sources. This summary is therefore primarily a factual record of his judicial background and incumbency rather than a campaign platform.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(369,478,'George J. Mertz','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','George J. Mertz is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 46th Circuit Court, which serves Otsego, Crawford, and Kalkaska counties in northern Michigan, and is running for reelection to a six-year term in the nonpartisan August 4, 2026 primary. He currently serves as Chief Judge of the circuit.\n\nMertz was appointed to the Circuit Court bench by Governor Rick Snyder in January 2013, then elected to a full six-year term on November 4, 2014. He earned his undergraduate degree from Michigan State University in 1996 and his Juris Doctor from the Detroit College of Law at Michigan State University in 2001.\n\nHis legal career began as a judicial law clerk for the 46th Circuit Court in 2001, where he worked primarily for Circuit Court Judges Alton Davis and Dennis Murphy. In 2002 he joined the Gaylord office of Plunkett & Cooney, P.C. as an associate attorney, practicing insurance defense litigation and general civil matters. In 2004 he became Assistant General Counsel for the Police Officers Association of Michigan, where he practiced labor law, criminal law, and litigation across central and northern Michigan. He also taught business law as an adjunct professor at North Central Michigan College.\n\nJudge Mertz resides in Gaylord with his wife Amy and their two children. His listed recreational interests include fishing, hunting, golf, skiing, hockey, curling, triathlons and marathons, aviation, woodworking, and music.\n\nAs a sitting judge seeking reelection, Mertz files as an incumbent. No detailed 2026 campaign platform or list of endorsements was found in available public sources; his reelection presence online consists primarily of a Facebook campaign page (\"Keep Judge George Mertz\"). No standalone campaign website, public campaign phone number, or campaign email was located. Note: this summary is drawn from his official court biography and ballot-reference listings rather than campaign-issued platform material.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(370,67,'Matt Antkoviak','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Matthew (Matt) Antkoviak is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 48th Circuit Court, which serves Allegan County, running for a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed him to the circuit bench to fill a partial term following the retirement of Judge Roberts Kengis; he began serving on August 28, 2023. As of January 1, 2026, the Michigan Supreme Court reappointed him Chief Judge of the 48th Circuit Court.\n\nBefore taking the bench, Antkoviak practiced law for roughly 24 years as an attorney and partner at Antkoviak and Antkoviak, PC in Allegan, joining his father\'s practice in 1999. His practice focused on felony and misdemeanor criminal defense, DUI/DWI defense, family law, general civil litigation, domestic violence matters, and driver\'s license restorations.\n\nHe earned a Bachelor of Arts from Michigan State University and a Juris Doctor from the New England School of Law in Boston.\n\nAntkoviak has been active in the Allegan County legal and civic community. He served as president of the Allegan County Bar Association (2001-2002), and has held leadership roles including board member and secretary of Reach the Forgotten (a faith-based organization focused on reducing incarceration and recidivism), former board member of Allegan General Hospital, and chair of the Community Corrections Advisory Board.\n\nAt the time of his appointment, Antkoviak stated that he would \"endeavor to treat all persons with respect, fairness, and equal access to justice under the law.\" His judicial profile emphasizes his deep local roots in Allegan County and decades of courtroom experience across both criminal and civil practice.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone, email, or direct headshot image URL was located in this research; judicial incumbents in Michigan frequently run without a standalone campaign site. As a sitting circuit judge running for retention/election as an incumbent, his official contact and biographical information are maintained through the Allegan County 48th Circuit Court. (Note: this summary is a factual synthesis from local news coverage of his appointment; specific 2026 campaign platform statements were not found.)','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(371,479,'Dennis L. Duvall Jr.','','','','(231) 796-4510','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Dennis L. DuVall Jr. is a candidate for Judge of the 49th Circuit Court (Non-Incumbent, 6-year term) in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary. The 49th Circuit Court serves Mecosta and Osceola counties, based in Big Rapids, Michigan.\n\nDuVall is a long-practicing attorney based in Big Rapids. According to legal-directory listings, he has more than 25 years of experience handling a wide range of criminal cases in Mecosta and Osceola counties, the same two-county jurisdiction covered by the 49th Circuit Court. He operates a solo criminal-defense practice, Dennis L. DuVall Attorney at Law, P.C., located at 128 N. Warren Avenue, Big Rapids, MI 49307. His practice emphasizes criminal defense, including charges such as DUI/OWI, assault, and other felony and misdemeanor matters.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or candidate headshot was located in public search results, and no published platform, priorities, or endorsements were found. As a nonpartisan judicial candidate, he may not yet have a formal campaign presence online. The phone number listed above is his law-office contact line, not a confirmed campaign line.\n\nIdentity is confirmed with high confidence: the candidate\'s name, the office (49th Circuit Court), and the Big Rapids/Mecosta-Osceola location all match the practicing attorney Dennis L. DuVall Jr. documented in multiple legal directories. No specific platform claims, quotes, or endorsements are asserted here because none were found in available sources.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(372,481,'Susan Kasley Sniegowski','','','51stcircuitcourt@masoncountymi.gov','231-845-0516','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Susan Kasley Sniegowski is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 51st Circuit Court, which is a single-judge circuit covering Mason and Lake counties. She is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. She has served on the bench since January 1, 2015, after being first elected November 4, 2014, becoming the first female circuit court judge in the 51st Circuit; she is currently serving her second term.\n\nBefore the bench, Sniegowski made history in 2005 as Mason County\'s first female prosecuting attorney. She has practiced law locally since 1999. She earned a Bachelor of Arts in journalism from Michigan State University (1990) and a Juris Doctor from the University of Denver Sturm College of Law (1999), and interned at the Colorado State Public Defender\'s Office during law school, reflecting an early focus on criminal law.\n\nAs a single-judge circuit, she presides over the full range of circuit court matters, including felony criminal cases, civil cases involving claims over $25,000, family-law cases, lower-court and administrative appeals, and requests for injunctive relief.\n\nIn public remarks, Sniegowski has emphasized that it is important for all people, especially women, to feel empowered to pursue their goals, and she advocates for combining strength and assertiveness with compassion in the practice of law. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, separate campaign contact, or specific platform planks or endorsements were found in available sources; the contact information listed here is the official 51st Circuit Court office in Ludington. As an incumbent judge, she filed by affidavit of candidacy for re-election.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://i0.wp.com/freshwater-reporter.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Judge-Sniegowski-for-Freshwater-Reporter-web.jpg'),(373,482,'Gerald M. Prill','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Gerald M. Prill is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 52nd Circuit Court, which serves Huron County, and is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. He was first elected to the bench in 2014 and has served as a circuit judge since January 1, 2015.\n\nPrill earned his undergraduate degree from Michigan State University in 1991 and his Juris Doctor from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1995. Before joining the bench, he practiced law in Huron County and served as President of the Huron County Bar Association. He has been active in community and professional organizations, including serving as Co-Chair of the Judicial Outreach Committee for the Michigan Judges Association.\n\nAs a circuit court judge, Prill presides over felony criminal cases, higher-value civil matters, family/domestic relations, and appeals from lower courts in Huron County, located in Michigan\'s Thumb region. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, or email was located; as a sitting judge running for re-election, he files by affidavit of incumbency, and judicial incumbents in Michigan commonly run without a standalone campaign web presence. No detailed 2026 campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources. This summary is a factual synthesis based on the official Michigan courts listing and Ballotpedia; specific policy positions or campaign claims should not be inferred beyond what is stated here.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(374,484,'Tara S. Hovey','','','','989.426.9237','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Tara S. Hovey is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 55th Circuit Court, which serves Clare and Gladwin Counties. She was appointed to the bench in September 2022 by Governor Gretchen Whitmer, and is seeking election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Hovey practiced law in private practice beginning in 1996, handling a broad range of matters including criminal law, family law, real estate, probate, and civil litigation, and representing local governments. She served as city attorney for the City of Beaverton, as corporate counsel for Gladwin County, and worked with the indigent defense program in the Clare County Circuit and District Courts. She is also a co-owner of the Clare County Title Company.\n\nHovey earned her Juris Doctor from Ohio Northern University College of Law and holds a Bachelor of Science in Business Administration from Central Michigan University.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was found in public sources; as a sitting judge she may run without a separate campaign web presence. The phone number listed above is the official 55th Circuit Court (Gladwin County) chambers line. No specific 2026 platform statements, priorities, or endorsements were located in available sources, so no such claims are asserted here. This summary is a factual synthesis of her professional background and current judicial office rather than a campaign platform.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(375,73,'Kelly E. Morton','','','','517-543-4325','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Kelly E. Morton is an incumbent judge of the 56th Circuit Court serving Eaton County, Michigan, running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. She was appointed to the Circuit Court bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer on July 2, 2024, joining Judge Janice K. Cunningham on the court.\n\nMorton\'s judicial career began when she was elected to the 56A District Court in November 2020, taking the bench on January 1, 2021. On the Circuit Court she oversees the Domestic Violence Court and the Felony Sobriety Court, building on more than 17 years of work with Eaton County\'s specialty courts.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Morton spent her career in prosecution. She served as an Assistant Prosecuting Attorney in Eaton County from 2003 to 2020, and previously as an Assistant Prosecuting Attorney in Alpena County (2002-2003), where she handled district and circuit court cases. Earlier in her career she also worked as a law clerk and as an adjunct professor teaching business law and criminal justice.\n\nHer education includes a Bachelor\'s degree from Oakland University (with prior coursework at Oakland Community College) and a Juris Doctor from the Michigan State University College of Law (MSU-Detroit College of Law), where she graduated magna cum laude and had legal scholarship published in the MSU Law Review.\n\nMorton is active in the community and in legal/advocacy organizations, including involvement with human trafficking task forces and domestic violence prevention councils. She has served on the Board of Directors for the Siren Shelter, including as Secretary.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign-specific phone number was located. The contact phone listed is her official Eaton County Circuit Court chambers line. As a sitting judge running for retention/re-election, she appears not to maintain a separate public campaign site at this time. This summary is synthesized from her official Eaton County court biography and state appointment announcements; no campaign platform statement or endorsements were found.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.eatoncounty.org/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=6475'),(376,610,'Mabel Johnson Mayfield','','','','(269) 983-7111','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Mabel Johnson Mayfield is the incumbent Judge of Probate for Berrien County, Michigan, and serves as Chief Judge of the Berrien County Trial Court (appointed to that role by the Michigan Supreme Court effective January 1, 2020). She is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term in the Berrien County Probate Court.\n\nJudge Mayfield was first appointed to the Berrien County Probate Bench by Governor John Engler in January 2000 and has been re-elected to the position in subsequent elections. Before her current role as Chief Judge, she served as Presiding Judge of the Family Division of the Berrien County Trial Court. Prior to taking the bench, she spent seven years as a Juvenile Court Attorney Referee and was a ten-year veteran of Berrien County Legal Services.\n\nShe earned a Bachelor of Science in Economics from the Krannert School of Management at Purdue University and a Juris Doctor from Valparaiso University School of Law. Her professional affiliations include the State Bar of Michigan, the Berrien County Bar Association (of which she is a former president), the Michigan Probate Judges\' Association, the Southwestern Michigan Probate Judges\' Association, and the Association of Black Judges of Michigan. She has also been named a Fellow of the Michigan State Bar Foundation and received the Bernard C. Radde Distinguished Service Award from Lake Michigan College.\n\nJudge Mayfield is active in community organizations including service on boards such as the Area Agency on Aging, and is involved with Delta Sigma Theta Sorority and the NAACP. She regularly provides educational presentations to schools and community groups.\n\nAs an incumbent judicial candidate, she does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign website; the information here is drawn from her official Berrien County court biography and public profiles. No specific 2026 campaign platform statement was located online, which is typical for sitting judges running for re-election on a record of service.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.berriencounty.org/ImageRepository/Document?documentId=1252'),(377,167,'Eric G. Blubaugh','','','','906-635-6314','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Eric G. Blubaugh is the incumbent Judge of Probate Court for Chippewa County, Michigan (17th Probate Court), seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. As an incumbent in a nonpartisan judicial race, he does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website; his contact information is through the Chippewa County Probate Court (phone 906-635-6314).\n\nBlubaugh was appointed to the Chippewa County Probate Court bench by Governor Rick Snyder on May 8, 2017, filling the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Elizabeth Biolette Church. He subsequently ran for and won election in 2018 to retain the seat. At the time of his 2017 appointment, he served as magistrate for the 91st District Court, a juvenile referee/officer for the Chippewa County Family Court, and an adjunct professor at Lake Superior State University. His earlier legal career included work as an assistant prosecutor for Chippewa County and as chief prosecutor for the Bay Mills Indian Community.\n\nEducationally, Blubaugh holds a bachelor\'s degree from Central Michigan University, a J.D. from Western Michigan University\'s Thomas M. Cooley Law School, and a master of laws (LL.M.) degree from Georgetown University Law Center.\n\nNo specific 2026 campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were located in available public sources. This summary is drawn from his official court directory listing and biographical records rather than from campaign materials, reflecting the limited online presence typical of incumbent judges running in nonpartisan races.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(378,613,'Richard J. Garcia','','','','517-483-6300','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Richard J. Garcia is the incumbent Judge of the Ingham County Probate Court (Mason, Michigan) seeking re-election in the nonpartisan August 4, 2026 Michigan primary for a six-year term. His current term expires in January 2027.\n\nGarcia was appointed to the Ingham County Probate Court bench by Governor John Engler in February 2000 and retained by voters that November. He has since been re-elected to full terms in 2002, 2008, 2014, and 2020, making the 2026 race a bid for continued service on a court where he has presided for more than two decades. Over his tenure he has held a series of leadership roles, including Chief Judge of the Circuit Court (4 years), Chief Judge of the Probate Court (8 years), and Presiding Judge of the Family Division (4 years). He currently serves as Chief Probate Judge Pro Tempore at the Mason Historical Courthouse.\n\nHe earned his undergraduate degree from the University of Notre Dame (1983) and his J.D. from the University of Michigan Law School (1985). Before becoming a judge, Garcia practiced law in private firms, working as an associate at Howrey & Simon (Washington, D.C.) and Foster, Swift, Collins & Smith (Lansing), and as a partner at Adkins & Garcia and at Lynch, Gallagher, Lynch and Martineau.\n\nGarcia has been active in legal education and civil rights work. He has served as an adjunct professor at Western Michigan University Cooley Law School, teaching juvenile law, child abuse and neglect, children and the law, family law, and family violence practice. His broader public service includes serving as Chairman of the Michigan Civil Rights Commission, Co-Chair of the Michigan Alliance Against Hate Crimes, and Chair of the Michigan Bias Crime Task Force. He has also been involved with community organizations such as Farm Workers Legal Services, the Cristo Rey Community Center, the Community Corrections Advisory Board, and Big Brothers Big Sisters.\n\nAs is typical for sitting probate judges running for re-election, no dedicated 2026 campaign website was located; the most authoritative public information comes from the Ingham County court\'s official judicial biography and Ballotpedia. The phone number listed is the Ingham County Probate Court\'s general line. No specific 2026 campaign platform statement, endorsements, or personal contact email were found in available sources.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://docs.ingham.org/Department/30th%20Judicial%20Circuit%20Court/Judges%20Files/Garcia/IMG_1034.jpeg'),(379,614,'Tiffany A. Ankley','','','','269-384-8171','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Tiffany A. Ankley is a sitting judge in Kalamazoo County, Michigan, running as an incumbent for the nonpartisan Kalamazoo County Probate Court seat (6-year term) in the August 4, 2026 primary. Ankley was first elected to the Kalamazoo County bench on November 4, 2014, defeating Namita Sharma with about 55.9% of the vote, for a term beginning January 1, 2015. Although she originally ran for retiring Probate Judge Patricia N. Conlon\'s seat, the Kalamazoo County Executive Judicial Council reassigned judicial duties so that Ankley took over district court responsibilities, while another judge moved into the probate opening; her current docket has been associated with the 8th District Court at the Judge Charles A. Pratt Justice Center in Kalamazoo. She has been recognized locally, including being honored by a Kalamazoo organization as a \"Trailblazer of HOPE\" (Second Wave, 2023). Reporting indicates she has been involved with the county\'s specialty/treatment court programs, including its OWI (Operating While Intoxicated) Court and drug treatment court efforts.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located. The contact details available are for her official court chambers (8th District Court, 330 Eleanor St., Kalamazoo, MI 49007; phone 269-384-8171). As is common for incumbent judicial candidates running in nonpartisan races, she does not appear to maintain a separate public campaign site, and detailed campaign platform statements or endorsements for the 2026 cycle were not found. This summary is a best-effort, factual synthesis from her official Kalamazoo County court bio page, Ballotpedia, and local news coverage; specific 2026 campaign positions could not be confirmed and are therefore not asserted.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://kalamazoo.courts.michigan.gov/ImageRepository/Document?documentId=1939'),(380,615,'David M. Murkowski','','','','616-632-5428','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','David M. Murkowski is an incumbent judge of the Kent County Probate Court in Michigan, seeking re-election in 2026 for a six-year term. He has served on the Kent County Probate bench since August 2006, when he was appointed by then-Governor Jennifer Granholm to fill the vacancy created by the retirement of Judge Janet A. Haynes.\n\nBorn and raised in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, Murkowski graduated from Marquette University High School in 1975 and earned his undergraduate degree from Marquette University in 1979. He received his J.D. from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School (now affiliated with Western Michigan University) in 1983.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Murkowski served as a law clerk to the Michigan House of Representatives Civil Rights Committee and practiced as a solo attorney in Grand Rapids. In 1993 he joined the law firm of Dilley & Dilley, specializing in criminal defense, juvenile neglect and delinquency, and probate law, eventually becoming managing partner of Dilley, Dilley, Murkowski & Goller until his 2006 appointment.\n\nMurkowski served as Chief Judge of the Kent County Probate Court from January 1, 2008, through December 31, 2024, and transitioned to Chief Judge Pro Tempore beginning January 1, 2025. His leadership roles in the broader legal community include serving as President of the Michigan Probate Judges Association in 2017 and election to the Judicial Section of the State Bar of Michigan. He also serves as an Adjunct Assistant Professor in the College of Human Medicine at Michigan State University.\n\nThis is a nonpartisan judicial office. As a sitting incumbent, Murkowski does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website; his public profile is documented primarily through the Kent County government website, Ballotpedia, and Michigan legal press. No specific 2026 campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were located in available public sources. His record centers on his long tenure in probate court administration, including guardianship, conservatorship, estate, and juvenile/mental-health matters typical of Michigan probate courts.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.kentcountymi.gov/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=2828'),(381,616,'Sara A. Schimke','','','','586-469-7180','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Sara A. Schimke is the incumbent Judge of the Macomb County Probate Court, seeking re-election as a nonpartisan candidate in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary for a six-year term. She was appointed to the bench in April 2022 by Governor Gretchen Whitmer to fill the vacancy created by the retirement of Judge Kathryn George.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Schimke spent her legal career concentrating on probate law, estate planning, and advocacy. She practiced at three firms: Chalgian & Tripp, PLLC; Jaffe, Raitt, Heuer & Weiss, P.C.; and Barron, Rosenburg, Mayoras & Mayoras, P.C. She also served as an adjunct professor at Western Michigan University Thomas M. Cooley Law School. Schimke earned a Bachelor of Science from Northern Michigan University and her Juris Doctor from Thomas M. Cooley Law School.\n\nShe has been active in legal and community organizations, including serving as a board member of the Michigan Parkinson\'s Foundation, a member of the Institute for Continuing Legal Education\'s Elder Law Advisory/Planning Committee, and as former chair of the State Bar of Michigan\'s Elder Law & Disability Rights Section.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 re-election campaign website was located at the time of research; as a sitting judge she is profiled primarily through the official Macomb County Probate Court site and Michigan legal-community publications. The phone number listed (586-469-7180) is for her judicial chambers (judicial secretary), not a campaign office. No specific 2026 campaign platform statement or endorsements were found in available sources.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.macombgov.org/sites/default/files/styles/crop_widget_4_5/public/images/2025-10/PC_20251007_JudgeSchimke_SQ.JPG'),(382,617,'Cheryl R. Sweeney','','','','734-240-7160','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Cheryl R. Sweeney is the incumbent Judge of Probate Court for Monroe County, Michigan, seeking election to a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. A lifelong resident of LaSalle, Michigan, she was appointed to the Monroe County Probate Court by Governor Gretchen Whitmer on November 6, 2025, filling a partial term that expires January 1, 2027. She is the fifth woman appointed as a judge in Monroe County history.\n\nSweeney was the 1985 valedictorian of Monroe High School and earned a Bachelor of Arts in English from the University of Michigan and a Juris Doctor from the University of Toledo College of Law. Before her appointment, she practiced law privately for about 26 years, concentrating on probate and family law, including work as an associate attorney at the Law Offices of Terri Hall. For roughly six years she served within the Monroe County court system as Chief Juvenile Court Referee for the 38th Judicial Circuit Court, Family Division, and as Deputy Probate Register, where she handled minor guardianship, conservatorship, and related matters and made recommendations to the bench. She previously ran unsuccessfully for circuit court judge in 2012.\n\nShe is a member of the State Bar of Michigan Children\'s Law Section and the Referees Association of Michigan. Her community involvement includes membership at St. Paul\'s United Methodist Church and prior service on the Monroe Public Schools Board of Education (2016-2019). She is married to Craig Prater and has two adult sons.\n\nIn describing her appointment, Sweeney noted that the probate seat aligns closely with her career, saying it covers the areas of law she practiced throughout her private practice. As an incumbent, she now stands for election to continue serving on the Monroe County Probate/Juvenile Court, where she sits alongside Chief Judge Cheryl E. Lohmeyer. The court\'s stated mission emphasizes serving the community with integrity, compassion, and accountability through restorative justice.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or official online headshot URL was located through available public sources. The phone number listed is the Monroe County Probate Court contact associated with her, not a campaign line.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(383,212,'Nicole S. Huddleston','','https://www.electhuddlestonforjudge.com','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Nicole S. Huddleston is the incumbent Judge of the Oakland County Probate Court, running in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary for a partial term ending January 1, 2029 (this is a nonpartisan judicial race). Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed her to the Probate Court on April 1, 2026, with her term commencing April 17, 2026, filling a vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Kathleen Ryan.\n\nA resident of West Bloomfield, Huddleston is an attorney and social justice advocate. She earned her B.A. from Oakland University and her J.D. from the University of Detroit Mercy School of Law, where she served on the Moot Court Board and interned with federal judges (the Hon. Victoria Roberts and the Hon. Helene White). Before her appointment she owned Huddleston Law, PLLC, a firm focused on probate, family, and civil law. Her prior legal career includes serving as Managing Director of the Detroit Justice Center (overseeing its Legal Services Practice), as an Assistant Wayne County Prosecutor in the domestic violence division, and as a staff attorney at Lakeshore Legal Aid and at Legal Aid and Defender. She is an ABA-certified mediator and has served on the Michigan Supreme Court\'s Justice for All Commission since 2021.\n\nIn her prior 2024 campaign for Oakland County Circuit Court (Family Division), she articulated three core judicial principles that reflect her stated approach to the bench: critical thinking to handle difficult cases, the right temperament (treating all parties with kindness, decency, and respect), and justice under the law (ensuring personal biases do not influence court decisions). She is active in the community as a board member of The Youth Connection and Matrix Theatre, an advisory board member of the Center for Employment Opportunities, and a member of the Wolverine Bar Association, Oakland County Bar Association, Straker Bar Association, and Alpha Kappa Alpha Sorority, Inc. She lives in West Bloomfield with her husband and son.\n\nNote on sourcing: The linked campaign website (electhuddlestonforjudge.com) and headshot date to her 2024 Circuit Court candidacy; she now serves on, and is running to retain, the Probate Court seat. No public campaign phone or email was found for the 2026 probate race.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/65ca490d26c67146b2c1b611/d1dd3b84-aed3-432e-89ee-2d8853e39665/nicolehheadshot.jpg'),(384,619,'Barbara L. Meter','','','','(989) 790-5285','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Barbara L. Meter is the incumbent Judge of the Saginaw County Probate Court in Michigan, seeking reelection to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. She was first elected to the Saginaw County Probate Court on November 4, 2014, for a term beginning January 1, 2015. Her judicial work focuses on the court\'s Juvenile and Family Division, with practice areas including adoption, family law, and juvenile law.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Meter served as an assistant prosecutor in Saginaw County for approximately nineteen years. She earned a bachelor\'s degree in elementary education, with a minor in mathematics, from Michigan State University in 1984, and her J.D. from the University of New Hampshire (Franklin Pierce) in 1990. She is a member of the Saginaw County Bar Association.\n\nAs a sitting probate judge running as an incumbent, no dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign-specific platform statement, or list of endorsements was located in public sources. Michigan judicial candidates frequently do not maintain separate campaign sites, and judges typically refrain from publishing detailed policy platforms due to judicial ethics constraints. The contact phone and address listed here are the official court/bar-association listings, not a campaign office. No specific 2026 platform priorities or endorsements were found and none are asserted here.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.saginawbar.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/metterBarb-1024x810.png'),(385,620,'Jennifer Deegan','','https://deeganforjudge.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Jennifer Smith Deegan is the incumbent judge of the St. Clair County Probate Court, seeking election to a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary (a nonpartisan judicial race). She was appointed to the probate bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in March 2024 and subsequently won the November 2024 special election to fill the seat.\n\nDeegan holds a bachelor\'s degree from Alma College and a law degree from Wayne State University Law School. She brings approximately 25 years of courtroom experience. Before becoming a judge, she spent her career largely in the St. Clair County Prosecuting Attorney\'s Office, where she worked beginning in 1999 and rose to senior assistant prosecuting attorney. Her campaign materials state she tried over 100 bench and jury trials, with particular focus on cases involving child abuse and impaired-driving fatalities. Earlier in her career she served as a law clerk for three judges in the 31st Circuit Court and as a staff attorney for Consolidated Legal Services in Southfield. She received the David M. Schieber Life Saver Award in 2014.\n\nHer campaign emphasizes courtroom expertise, community service, and integrity grounded in honesty, empathy, and fairness, with a stated commitment to child protection. Community involvement cited on her campaign site includes serving as Board Chair of Lake Huron Medical Center, membership on the St. Clair County Child Abuse and Neglect Council, and past work with the YMCA and a domestic violence council. She is also a foster and adoptive parent.\n\nHer campaign lists a physical address of 4092 Gratiot Ave, Port Huron, MI 48060, and a campaign Facebook page; no public campaign phone or email was found on her website. Identity is confirmed by the match of name, the St. Clair County Probate Court office, and her incumbent status.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://deeganforjudge.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/F11A0039-8x10-1-scaled.jpg'),(386,621,'Sara L. Grout','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Sara L. Grout is a non-incumbent candidate for Judge of Probate Court in Sanilac County, Michigan, in the nonpartisan August 4, 2026 primary, seeking a six-year term. Her candidate filing lists a Croswell (Sanilac County) address.\n\nBased on available public records, Grout appears to be a practicing Michigan attorney. A Sara Lynn Grout is listed in legal directories as an attorney with a probate, estate planning, trusts, and business law practice in the Thumb/Port Huron region of eastern Michigan (associated in directory listings with the firm Touma, Watson, Whaling, Coury, Stremers & Thomas, PC in Port Huron). That attorney was admitted to the State Bar of Michigan in 2015 after graduating from Case Western Reserve University School of Law. Her concentration in probate and estate-planning law is consistent with a candidacy for a probate judgeship, and the Port Huron/Thumb geography is adjacent to and overlaps the broader region that includes Croswell and Sanilac County. However, I was not able to directly confirm through an accessible source that the directory-listed attorney and the Croswell-based probate-judge candidate are the same individual, so this attorney background is provided as a likely (not certain) match.\n\nNo campaign website, campaign phone number, campaign email, or candidate headshot photo could be located through public web searches. Michigan probate judgeships are nonpartisan elective offices with six-year terms, and Grout is filing as a non-incumbent, meaning she is not the sitting judge. No platform statement, endorsements, or stated campaign priorities were found in available sources; none should be assumed. Voters seeking authoritative confirmation of her identity, qualifications, and contact information should consult the Sanilac County Clerk\'s office, the Michigan Bureau of Elections candidate listing, or the State Bar of Michigan attorney directory.\n\nNote: identity match between the candidate and the directory-listed attorney is plausible based on profession and region but not independently verified.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(387,498,'Michael Brown','','','','734-240-7125','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Michael C. Brown is the Chief Judge of Michigan\'s 1st District Court, which serves Monroe County, and is running as an incumbent in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan judicial primary for a six-year term. He was appointed to the district court bench on August 13, 2018, and his current elected term commenced January 1, 2021.\n\nJudge Brown earned a Bachelor of Science degree from Purdue University and a Juris Doctor degree from the University of Michigan Law School. In addition to his general district-court docket, he presides over the 1st District Court\'s Veterans\' Treatment Court, a specialty/problem-solving court serving justice-involved veterans. As district court is a court of limited jurisdiction in Michigan, his work encompasses misdemeanors, civil matters under the statutory limit, small claims, landlord-tenant disputes, traffic, and preliminary examinations in felony cases.\n\nAs a sitting nonpartisan judge filing for re-election by affidavit of incumbency, Judge Brown does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website. Detailed platform statements, endorsements, or stated priorities for the 2026 race were not located in public sources at the time of this research; this summary is therefore drawn from his official court biography and public records rather than campaign materials. His public contact is through the 1st District Court / Monroe County government. No campaign-specific email or fundraising committee site was confirmed.\n\nThis candidate is confidently identified as the incumbent Chief Judge Michael C. Brown of the 1st District Court (Monroe County), matching the office, district, and incumbent status in the candidate record.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.co.monroe.mi.us/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=1358'),(388,517,'Todd M. Morgan','','','','517-264-4675','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Todd M. Morgan is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 2A District Court, which serves Lenawee County, and is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. Morgan was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer to succeed Judge Jonathan L. Poer and was sworn in as district judge in April 2022. Later that year he ran to complete the unexpired term (which ends January 1, 2027); he led a four-candidate field in the primary with roughly 6,380 votes and won the general election against opponent Ashley Hanson-Grimes.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Morgan was a local attorney who worked as a public defender (2020-2022). His earlier career spanned varied public-service and technical roles, including service in the U.S. Navy as a nuclear machinist mate (active duty 1986-1992, plus reserve service), work as a forensic security aide at a mental-health hospital/prison facility (1994-2004), and a position as a financial analyst with Michigan Rehabilitation Service. The District Court he presides over handles matters such as misdemeanors, traffic, civil disputes, small claims, landlord-tenant cases, and preliminary felony proceedings; local coverage has noted his role, alongside fellow Lenawee judges, in handling DUI/OWI cases.\n\nAs a nonpartisan judicial incumbent, Morgan has not published a formal campaign platform or policy agenda online, and no dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or candidate headshot could be located in public sources. His official contact point is the Lenawee County District Court (phone 517-264-4675). A \"Judge Todd M. Morgan\" Facebook page exists but was not confirmed as an active 2026 campaign account. This summary is drawn from the Lenawee County staff directory and local news coverage of his 2022 appointment and election; details specific to a 2026 re-election campaign were limited at the time of research. No specific endorsements or new campaign priorities were found and none are asserted here.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(389,518,'Megan R.M. Stiverson','','https://stiversonforjudge.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Megan R.M. Stiverson is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 2B District Court, which serves Hillsdale County. She is seeking re-election (nonpartisan) in the August 4, 2026 primary for a six-year term. A Hillsdale County native, Stiverson graduated from Jonesville High School, earned a B.A. in political science from Hope College (1999), and received her Juris Doctor from Michigan State University College of Law (Detroit College of Law). Before taking the bench, she built a career spanning private law practice, court administration, and judicial roles. She served as a family court referee and juvenile court administrator in Hillsdale County, working under Probate Judge Michelle Bianchi, and had earlier worked as defense counsel for juvenile defendants in the county\'s juvenile drug court. She also previously served as a chief administrative officer for a multi-state private-duty home health care company, overseeing personnel, quality assurance, legal/legislative affairs, and budgeting.\n\nStiverson was elected to the 2B District Court in November 2020 and took office January 1, 2021. As judge, she secured a four-year grant of roughly $499,000 to establish a domestic violence court in Hillsdale County and to fund a dedicated probation officer and case manager.\n\nIn her prior campaign, Stiverson emphasized her breadth of judicial and legal experience, stating she had \"served in really all capacities,\" and stressed fairness and impartiality—that no party should leave her courtroom feeling treated unfairly. She highlighted the importance of separating judicial decisions from personal beliefs and of recognizing when recusal is appropriate (noting, for example, that her husband works for the county Sheriff\'s Office). She also emphasized accessibility to the community. Her earlier candidacy was endorsed by Probate Judge Michelle Bianchi.\n\nSpecific 2026 re-election platform details and endorsements were not located in available public sources; much of the campaign content found dates to her initial 2020 candidacy. Her official campaign domain (stiversonforjudge.com) and a campaign Facebook page (facebook.com/stiversonforjudge) appear to be hers, though the website was not reachable at the time of research. No verified public campaign phone, email, or direct headshot image URL was confirmed.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(390,538,'Brent R. Weigle','','','','517-279-4328','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Brent R. Weigle is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 3-A District Court, which serves Branch County, and is running unopposed for re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary, seeking a fourth consecutive six-year term in this nonpartisan office. He has served as district judge since January 1, 2009.\n\nWeigle\'s legal career in Branch County spans roughly four decades. He earned his undergraduate degree from Grove City College and his Juris Doctor from the Thomas M. Cooley School of Law. In 1986 he began work as an assistant prosecuting attorney in Branch County, later spending about five years in private practice at the Coldwater firm Stevens and Hayes. Before taking the bench, he served approximately 13 years as the county\'s District Court Magistrate under Judge David T. Coyle.\n\nWeigle frequently describes the district court as \"The People\'s Court,\" reflecting its broad, high-volume docket of civil disputes, traffic matters, and misdemeanor cases, and has expressed appreciation for the opportunity to continue serving the community in this role. A longtime Coldwater resident, he and his wife Margaret raised four sons, most of whom remain in the area.\n\nThe 3-A District Court is located at 31 Division St., Coldwater, MI 49036 (main line 517-279-4328). As is common for sitting trial judges, Weigle does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign website, and no public campaign phone, email, or candidate headshot was located. Identity is confirmed by the match on Michigan, Branch County, the 3-A District Court, and his status as the incumbent filing for a fourth term in 2026. No specific campaign platform, priorities beyond continued service, or endorsements were found in available sources.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(391,539,'Tim George','','','','(269) 651-2445','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Timothy R. (\"Tim\") George is a candidate for Judge of the 3B District Court (a non-incumbent, six-year-term seat) on the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary ballot. The 3B District Court serves St. Joseph County, Michigan, which includes the city of Sturgis. The seat is nonpartisan, as are all Michigan judicial races.\n\nGeorge is a practicing attorney and partner/shareholder at the Sturgis Law Firm, formally Bird, Scheske, Reed, Beemer & George, P.C., with offices at 227 W. Chicago Rd., Sturgis, MI 49091 and 28 W. Chicago St., Ste. 2A, Coldwater, MI 49036. His practice areas include criminal law, divorce, custody, adoption and guardianship matters, and civil litigation.\n\nBefore entering private practice, George served as an Assistant Prosecuting Attorney for St. Joseph County, Michigan, giving him courtroom and prosecutorial experience directly within the district where he is now seeking a judgeship. He earned a Bachelor of Science from Wayne State University in Detroit and a Juris Doctor from Western Michigan University Thomas M. Cooley Law School. He resides in Three Rivers, Michigan (also within St. Joseph County) with his wife, Mary, and their children.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email address, or published campaign platform statement was located at the time of this research. His listed professional contact phone number is (269) 651-2445 (Sturgis Law Firm). No formal endorsements or detailed policy priorities specific to his judicial candidacy were found in available public sources; this summary is therefore based on his professional biography and the official 2026 candidate filing rather than campaign materials. This is a factual, best-effort summary; additional platform details may become available closer to the primary.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/68001304c4e4345489e277eb/571b103f-ad9d-4e4f-b9ea-3a4336798737/CX0A8390.jpg'),(392,540,'Stacey A. Rentfrow','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Stacey A. Rentfrow is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 4th District Court, which serves Cass County. She is running unopposed-by-default as a nonpartisan incumbent for a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 primary. Rentfrow was first elected to the court on November 4, 2008, and re-elected on November 4, 2014, making 2026 part of her continued service on the Cass County bench.\n\nAccording to publicly available records, Rentfrow earned her undergraduate degree from Michigan State University and her J.D. from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School. Before her election to the bench, she practiced law at the Laaksonen Law Offices in Paw Paw, Michigan, and previously served as a family court referee in Van Buren County. She began her legal career doing public-interest work as an attorney for Legal Aid of Western Michigan.\n\nAs a 4th District Court judge, Rentfrow hears district court matters including traffic violations, misdemeanor criminal cases, small claims, and civil disputes (up to $25,000 in jurisdictional limit). She also presides over Cass County\'s Adult Treatment Court (ATC) and Sobriety Court, problem-solving courts that serve individuals facing criminal charges who struggle with substance abuse; the county courts have publicized these programs as helping lower recidivism and unemployment rates. She is supported by three magistrates in handling the district court\'s caseload.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, or campaign email address was located in available sources. As a sitting judge, Rentfrow does not appear to maintain a distinct candidate website; her official role is documented through the Cass County Courts site. Contact for the court is through the Law and Courts Building in Cassopolis, Michigan. No headshot image URL was found on the court\'s public pages. This is a best-effort factual summary based on the limited public information available for a judicial incumbent; specific 2026 campaign platform statements or endorsements were not found and are not asserted here.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(393,586,'Rachel Keeley','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Rachel Keeley is a nonpartisan candidate for Judge of Michigan\'s 7th District Court (which serves Van Buren County), seeking the non-incumbent 6-year term position on the August 4, 2026 primary ballot. A Van Buren County native and graduate of Gobles Public Schools, she earned her undergraduate degree from DePaul University and her law degree from Thomas M. Cooley Law School. Her family has roots in the area spanning more than a century.\n\nKeeley has more than a decade of courtroom experience as a prosecutor. She has served as a Van Buren County Assistant Prosecutor since 2021 and previously worked in the Allegan County Prosecutor\'s Office (roughly 2015-2021), as well as in private practice in South Haven. Over her career she has handled some of southwest Michigan\'s most serious criminal matters, including child abuse, sexual assault, and domestic violence cases. She has been part of the Safe Harbor victim-advocacy team since 2015 and has served in Family Reunification Court.\n\nIn announcing her candidacy, Keeley emphasized a commitment to protecting children and standing with victims, and stated her goal of bringing courtroom experience to the District Court bench, particularly in criminal cases where accountability and public safety are at issue. In late March 2026 she reported filing the maximum 800 nominating-petition signatures, clearing a key milestone to qualify for the ballot.\n\nPer local news reporting, her campaign listed endorsements from Judge Michael McKay, Judge Susan Metzger, Van Buren County Prosecuting Attorney Susan Zuiderveen, and Sheriff Dan Abbott.\n\nNo official campaign website, public campaign phone number, email address, or candidate headshot image was located in publicly available online sources at the time of research; the available information comes from southwest Michigan local news coverage and the Michigan Bureau of Elections candidate listing.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(394,504,'Anna Maria Frushour','','https://frushourforjudge.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Anna Maria Frushour is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 14A District Court in Washtenaw County, seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. She was appointed to the 14A District Court bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer on December 17, 2019, filling the vacancy created by the resignation of Hon. Richard Conlin, Jr. The 14A District Court serves all of Washtenaw County except the City of Ann Arbor (15th District) and Ypsilanti Township (14B District), with court locations in Pittsfield Township, Chelsea, Saline, and Ypsilanti.\n\nFrushour earned a B.A. in political science and communications from the University of Michigan in 2003 and a J.D. from Wayne State University Law School in 2009. Before joining the bench, she was a partner at Reiser & Frushour, PLLC (2013-2019), focusing on criminal defense. She also served as assigned defense counsel for several of Washtenaw County\'s specialty/problem-solving courts, including Mental Health Court, Veterans Treatment Court, Sobriety Court, and Street Outreach Court. According to local legal press coverage, as a judge she has emphasized expanding and strengthening these specialty treatment courts, which address underlying issues such as substance use disorder, mental health, and homelessness as alternatives to incarceration.\n\nShe maintains an active campaign presence through her official website (frushourforjudge.com) and a campaign Facebook page (facebook.com/frushourforjudge). She is a member of the Washtenaw County Bar Association.\n\nNote: This is a nonpartisan judicial race. No specific 2026 endorsements or a public campaign email/phone were confirmed from the sources reviewed; the campaign website was reachable in search results but could not be directly retrieved in this session. Identity is confirmed with high confidence by the match on Michigan, Washtenaw County, the 14A District Court, and her incumbent status.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(395,505,'Erane C. Washington','','https://www.eraneforjudge.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Erane C. Washington is the incumbent Chief Judge of the 14B District Court, located in Ypsilanti Township, Washtenaw County, Michigan. She is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for the 14B District Judge seat (6-year term). She was first elected to the court on November 4, 2020 and took the bench on January 1, 2021.\n\nOn the bench, Judge Washington presides over landlord-tenant, criminal, and general civil matters. She manages the court\'s Recovery and Human Trafficking Court and a Domestic Violence specialty docket, reflecting a focus on specialty/treatment-court approaches to justice.\n\nBackground and education: She graduated from the James Madison Residential College at Michigan State University (Class of 1985), where she studied Justice, Morality and Constitutional Democracy, and earned her law degree from the University of Michigan Law School in 1993.\n\nProfessional experience: Before becoming a judge, she served as an Assistant Public Defender for the Washtenaw County Public Defender\'s Office for approximately seven years (1994-2001). She was then recruited by then-Chief Judge of the Washtenaw Circuit Court, Donald E. Shelton, to serve as his Judicial Attorney for about six years. She subsequently left public service to start her own law practice, handling criminal defense, general civil, probate, and real estate matters until taking the bench in 2021.\n\nShe maintains an official campaign website (eraneforjudge.com) and a campaign Facebook presence (Judge Erane C. Washington). Specific 2026 campaign contact details (phone/email), a direct headshot image URL, and a detailed 2026 platform statement could not be confirmed from accessible sources at the time of research; the summary above reflects her record and background as reported by Washtenaw County Legal News and related local sources. No fabricated endorsements or claims are included.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(396,506,'Tamara Garwood','','https://www.garwoodforjudge.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Tamara A. Garwood is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 15th District Court, which serves the City of Ann Arbor in Washtenaw County. She was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer on January 6, 2026, and is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary to retain the seat for a full six-year term. The 15th District Court handles criminal, traffic, and landlord-tenant matters, and Garwood presides over those dockets as well as the court\'s specialized Mental Health Treatment Court and Veterans Treatment Court.\n\nGarwood served as magistrate of the 15th District Court from 2016 until her 2026 appointment, giving her roughly a decade of experience inside the same court she now leads. Before becoming a magistrate, she was in private legal practice for 17 years, working as a mediator, arbitrator, and guardian ad litem. She earned a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science from the University of Michigan in 1995 and her Juris Doctor from the Detroit College of Law at Michigan State University in 1999.\n\nShe is a member of the State Bar of Michigan, the Washtenaw County Bar Association, and the Women Lawyers Association of Washtenaw County, and has served on state bar committees and boards related to judicial education and county legal services. Garwood first announced her candidacy for the 15th District Court in 2024, seeking to replace a retiring Ann Arbor judge, and campaigned on her courtroom experience and work with the court\'s treatment-court (mental health and veterans) programs.\n\nNote: This summary is synthesized from her official Ann Arbor court bio and local news coverage. Her campaign website (garwoodforjudge.com) was unreachable at the time of research, so specific 2026 platform planks, endorsements, and direct campaign contact details (phone/email) could not be confirmed and are reported as null rather than guessed.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.a2gov.org/media/cjgpmcgh/tamara-garwood-4x5.jpg'),(397,507,'Sean Patrick Kavanagh','','','','(734) 466-2200','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Sean P. Kavanagh is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 16th District Court, which serves the City of Livonia in Wayne County, and is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. The court handles misdemeanor criminal cases, civil matters, traffic and ordinance violations, and conducts preliminary examinations for felony cases.\n\nKavanagh has a long history with the 16th District Court and the Livonia legal community. He began as a court officer for the 16th District Court (1982-1983), then served as a court magistrate from 1983 to 1986. He maintained a private legal practice from 1983 to 2008 and served as Livonia City Attorney from 1995 to 2008. He was first elected to the district court bench in November 2008 and has served as a judge since taking office, making him a long-tenured member of the court. He is married to Mary and has three children, Carolyn, Shane, and Kayleigh.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or published platform/endorsement information was located through public searches. As a sitting judge running for re-election in a nonpartisan race, his public-facing presence is primarily his official court biography on the City of Livonia website. Contact information listed here is the official court office (33000 Civic Center Drive, Livonia, MI 48154; (734) 466-2200), not a campaign line. No specific campaign priorities or endorsements were found in available sources; this summary is therefore largely a factual biography rather than a synthesis of a campaign platform.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://livonia.gov/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=123'),(398,508,'Krista Haroutunian','','','','313-387-2794','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Krista Haroutunian is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 17th District Court, located in Redford Township, Wayne County, and is seeking reelection (nonpartisan) to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 primary. She has served as a 17th District Court judge since October 2018, when she was appointed by Gov. Rick Snyder.\n\nHaroutunian earned a bachelor\'s degree from the University of Michigan in 1993 and a Juris Doctor from the Detroit College of Law at Michigan State University in 1998. Before joining the bench, she spent about 20 years in private practice alongside her parents and served as a Special Assistant Attorney General working with Adult Protective Services.\n\nOn the court, she launched the 17th District Court\'s Hybrid Treatment Court, a specialty program designed to help participants address substance abuse issues and related driver\'s license matters. She has also been active in the broader legal community, serving eight years on the State Bar of Michigan\'s Representative Assembly and three years on its Board of Commissioners, and previously chairing the Armenian American Bar Association. She maintains memberships in bar associations in Wayne and Oakland counties.\n\nOutside of the law, Haroutunian has been an active member of a chapter of the Armenian Relief Society since 1998 and served on the Michigan Women\'s Commission from 2011 to 2018.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located. As a sitting district judge running for reelection, her public-facing information is primarily through the court itself; the court office is located at 15111 Beech Daly Road, Redford, MI 48239. No specific 2026 campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources, so this summary reflects her judicial record and background rather than campaign-specific statements.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.redfordtwp.gov/ImageRepository/Document?documentId=1338'),(399,509,'Mark A. McConnell','','','','(734) 595-8720','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Mark A. McConnell is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 18th District Court, which serves the City of Westland in Wayne County (court located at 36675 Ford Rd., Westland, MI 48185). He is seeking re-election to a nonpartisan six-year term in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary.\n\nMcConnell was first elected to the 18th District Court in 2008 and was most recently re-elected in the November 3, 2020 general election; his current term ends January 1, 2027. As a district court judge, he handles the court\'s general docket, including criminal misdemeanors, traffic and OWI/DUI matters, civil cases, and small claims typical of a Michigan district court.\n\nBefore joining the bench, McConnell built a legal career rooted in the Westland community. He began as an associate attorney at Angelo A. Plakas and Associates, P.C. (starting in 1995), served as an Assistant Westland City Attorney and as a prosecutor in the 18th District Court, and worked as a research attorney for the Michigan Court of Appeals. He has also served as an adjunct faculty member at the Thomas M. Cooley Law School (Ann Arbor campus).\n\nHe earned a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science (with a minor in History) from Bowling Green State University and a Juris Doctorate, cum laude, from the University of Detroit Mercy School of Law, where he received the American Jurisprudence Award for the highest grades in Constitutional Law and Trial Practice and was listed in the 1992 Who\'s Who in American Law Students.\n\nMcConnell is active in community and professional organizations. He is a past president of the Westland Rotary Club and S.P.A.R.K., has served on advisory boards for the Chamber of Commerce and the Police Department, and is a member of advisory boards for Youth Assistance and Families Against Narcotics. He is a member of the Michigan District Judges Association and the Wayne County District Judges Association. In 2007 he was named \"Westland\'s First Citizen\" by the Observer and Eccentric newspaper.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or candidate headshot image was located in public sources. The contact phone listed is the 18th District Court\'s official line; a campaign-specific contact was not found. As an incumbent judge running unopposed-style affidavit filings are common, his platform emphasizes continued judicial service rather than a published policy agenda.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(400,510,'Mark W. Somers','','','','313-943-2150','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Mark W. Somers is a nonpartisan incumbent judge of the 19th District Court in Dearborn, Michigan, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary for a six-year term. He has served on the court since January 1, 2003, having been elected to four consecutive six-year terms (2002, 2008, 2014, and 2020). During his tenure he served six years as Chief Judge and an additional six years as Chief Judge Pro Tem.\n\nBefore taking the bench, Somers practiced law for nearly 20 years in general civil and criminal practice, representing clients in more than 40 state and federal courts and tribunals. He earned his undergraduate degree from James Madison College and the Honors College at Michigan State University, where he was elected to both the Phi Beta Kappa and Phi Kappa Phi honor societies, and his J.D. from Wayne State University Law School.\n\nA hallmark of his judicial service has been a focus on court-supervised rehabilitation and treatment for individuals with substance use disorders. He has been a member of the Michigan Association of Treatment Court Professionals since 2004 and served roughly ten years as presiding judge of Dearborn\'s drug court. He has lived in Dearborn since 1980, when he began law school, and has been married to his wife Jennie since 1978; the couple has two children and four grandchildren.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone, or campaign email was located. The phone number listed is the general 19th District Court office line. Specific platform statements, priorities for the 2026 campaign, and endorsements were not found in available public sources; the summary above reflects his official court biography and ballot record rather than campaign-specific material.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://dearborn.gov/sites/default/files/styles/team_people/public/2024-01/SomersWEB.jpg'),(401,511,'Mark J. Plawecki','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Mark J. Plawecki is the incumbent Chief Judge of Michigan\'s 20th District Court, which serves the city of Dearborn Heights in Wayne County. He is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Born April 25, 1961, Plawecki grew up in the Dearborn Heights area and attended Detroit Catholic Central and Dearborn Heights Riverside High School, where he earned All-League honors in tennis. He received a bachelor\'s degree in business administration from Michigan State University in 1983 and a Juris Doctor from Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1987.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Plawecki practiced general law and served as president of the firm Rombach, Plawecki, and Viggiani. He also worked as a prosecutor for the city of Hazel Park, Michigan. He was first elected to the 20th District Court in 1994 at age 33, reportedly the youngest judge in Dearborn Heights history at the time, and has been re-elected without opposition in 1996, 2002, 2008, 2014, and 2020. He serves as the court\'s Chief Judge.\n\nPlawecki has held leadership roles in the legal community, including past president of both the Wayne County District Judges Association and the Polish American Legal Society (PALS) of Michigan. In 2016 he briefly ran for the Michigan Supreme Court but withdrew that June following the death of his wife, Julie. He has also authored two books: \"How Could You Trade Billy Pierce?\" and \"Notes from Outside the Truman Show,\" a collection of essays on American democracy.\n\nAs is common for long-serving incumbent district judges, no dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone, campaign email, or headshot image was located in publicly available sources during this research. Specific 2026 campaign priorities, platform statements, or endorsements were not found and are therefore not reported here. Voters seeking official contact information can reach his court chambers through the 20th District Court / City of Dearborn Heights.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(402,512,'Nicholas Opalewski','','','','734-822-1432','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Nicholas Ryan Opalewski is a Garden City, Michigan attorney running as a nonpartisan, non-incumbent candidate for Judge of the 21st District Court (a six-year term) in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary. The 21st District Court serves Garden City; its current chief judge is Richard L. Hammer, Jr.\n\nOpalewski is a partner at the law firm Debolski, Debolski, & O\'Connor (also branded \"Top Michigan Lawyers\"), located at 30551 Ford Road, Garden City, MI 48135. His practice focuses on estate planning and probate, consumer bankruptcy, family law, plaintiff-side civil litigation, criminal defense, and estate and trust litigation.\n\nHe earned his J.D. from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 2014 and was admitted to the State Bar of Michigan in 2015, giving him roughly a decade of legal practice. Before his legal career, according to his firm bio, he served five years in the United States Army, including two tours of duty in Iraq. He has been recognized as a Super Lawyers \"Rising Star\" for 2023-2025 and holds a favorable peer rating on attorney directories such as Avvo.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email address, or published campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were located in available public sources at the time of this research. The contact information listed here is his law firm\'s public business phone; voters seeking campaign-specific details may need to consult the Wayne County or Michigan Secretary of State candidate filings closer to the primary. This summary is based on professional/attorney-directory listings rather than campaign materials, so specific judicial-campaign positions are not yet documented.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://cdn.superlawyers.com/image/upload/q_auto,f_auto,w_200/v20201001/p/attorney_by_uuid/8e892cc8-2992-4f16-b1eb-7c9917512de5/nicholas-r--opalewski-lrinvdr9.png'),(403,513,'Brittany A. Johnson','','','','734-374-1334','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Brittany A. Johnson is a sitting judge of Michigan\'s 23rd District Court, which serves the City of Taylor in Wayne County. She was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer and confirmed by the Michigan Supreme Court in early 2026, taking the oath of office on March 14, 2026. Her appointment filled the vacancy created by the resignation of former Judge Joseph Slaven, and she is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary as the incumbent for a full six-year term.\n\nA Taylor resident, Johnson became only the sixth person, and the second woman, to serve on the Taylor court. Before her appointment, she served as an assistant prosecuting attorney with the Wayne County Prosecutor\'s Office beginning in 2019. Earlier in her career she worked as a law clerk in Dearborn and as a legislative extern for the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) of Michigan. She has also served as a board member of the Government Bar Association.\n\nJohnson\'s educational background includes a Juris Doctor from the Michigan State University College of Law, a Master of Social Work (MSW) from Michigan State University, and a Bachelor of Science in psychology and criminal justice from Grand Valley State University. This combination of legal and social-work training reflects a background spanning both criminal prosecution and human-services perspectives.\n\nIn announcing the appointment, Governor Whitmer described Johnson as a \"skilled legal professional\" who brings years of experience to the role. As of this research no dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located; the contact information available is for the 23rd District Court itself (23365 Goddard Road, Taylor, MI 48180; 734-374-1334), which is typical for judicial incumbents who do not maintain a separate campaign web presence. No specific campaign platform statement or list of endorsements was found in available public sources, so detailed policy priorities are not documented here. Voters seeking additional information should consult official ballot materials and local Wayne County election resources closer to the primary.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(404,514,'John T. Courtright','','','','(313) 928-0535','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','John T. Courtright is a sitting judge of Michigan\'s 24th District Court, which serves the cities of Allen Park and Melvindale in Wayne County. He is seeking re-election as an incumbent for a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 Michigan primary, running in this nonpartisan judicial contest.\n\nCourtright was first appointed to the 24th District Court by former Governor John Engler in June 2000 and has served on the bench since. His current term ends January 1, 2027, making 2026 his re-election year. He has served as Chief Judge of the court, working alongside Judge Richard A. Page. The court is located at 6515 Roosevelt Road in Allen Park and handles civil cases, traffic and ordinance matters, misdemeanors, and the preliminary stages of felony cases arising within its jurisdiction.\n\nAccording to publicly available biographical information, Courtright earned his undergraduate degree from the University of San Francisco and his J.D. from Creighton University School of Law.\n\nAs a long-serving incumbent district judge running in a nonpartisan election, Courtright has not published a dedicated campaign website, and no public campaign contact email or headshot was located in this research. The primary public point of contact associated with him is the 24th District Court office in Allen Park, reachable at (313) 928-0535. No detailed 2026 campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were found in available sources; this summary is therefore a factual account of his judicial record and incumbency rather than a campaign-issued statement.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(405,516,'Elisabeth M. Mullins','','','info@28dc.com','(734) 258-3068','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Elisabeth M. (Mimi) Mullins is the sitting judge of Michigan\'s 28th District Court in Southgate (Wayne County) and is running as the incumbent in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. She first assumed office on January 1, 2021, after winning election on November 3, 2020; her current term ends January 1, 2027, which aligns with her 2026 candidacy.\n\nMullins earned a bachelor\'s degree in political science from Boston College (2003) and a J.D. from Suffolk University Law School (2008). Before joining the bench, she built her career in public-sector law in the Detroit area. She served as a prosecutor for the City of Detroit and as a special assistant prosecutor for Wayne County, and was recognized as Detroit\'s Prosecutor of the Year in both 2015 and 2016. In 2014 she was named an assistant corporation counsel in the City of Detroit Law Department.\n\nAs a district court judge, Mullins presides over the 28th District Court, which handles traffic violations, civil infractions, misdemeanors, small claims, and landlord-tenant matters for the City of Southgate. The court is located at 14720 Reaume Parkway, Southgate, MI 48195.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located. Mullins maintains an official \"Judge Elisabeth Mullins\" Facebook page. As a sitting judge bound by Michigan\'s Judicial Canons, she is restricted in campaign messaging and public commentary, and the court explicitly cautions the public against emailing the judge about pending cases. No specific 2026 platform statement, priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources; this summary is therefore primarily a factual profile of her background and current office rather than a campaign platform. The contact phone and email listed are the general 28th District Court lines, not a personal campaign contact.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(406,101,'Alexis Grace Krot','','','info@31stdistrictcourt.net','(313) 800-5248','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Alexis G. Krot is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 31st District Court, which serves the city of Hamtramck in Wayne County. She is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the nonpartisan judicial race on the August 4, 2026 primary ballot. Krot was originally appointed to the bench by Governor Rick Snyder and has served on the 31st District Court since. Her current term expires December 31, 2026, prompting the 2026 re-election contest.\n\nIn early 2022, Krot drew national attention and significant criticism for remarks she made during a virtual hearing to an elderly, ill defendant in a property-maintenance case. The incident generated a public backlash and online petitions. The matter was reviewed by the Michigan Judicial Tenure Commission, which subsequently cleared her of formal misconduct charges.\n\nFor the 2026 cycle, Krot faced a potential challenger, attorney Michael Koroi, but local reporting indicates Koroi was disqualified from the ballot after state election officials determined his nominating petitions fell short of the required 100 valid signatures and that he did not meet residency qualifications by one day. If Koroi remains off the ballot, Krot is positioned to win another six-year term largely unopposed.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located for Judge Krot. The contact information provided here is for the 31st District Court (3401 Evaline St., Hamtramck, MI 48212), not a campaign office. No specific campaign platform, policy priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources, which is typical for sitting district judges running in nonpartisan races. This summary is a brief factual account drawn from local news coverage and the court\'s official site; specifics about her judicial philosophy or campaign messaging were not available online at the time of research.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(407,519,'Rebekah Ruth Coleman','','','','(313) 343-2597','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Rebekah Ruth Coleman is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 32A District Court, which serves Harper Woods in Wayne County, and is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. She assumed office on January 1, 2021, after winning the November 3, 2020 general election, and is the first female and first African American judge to serve at the 32A District Court. Her current term ends in January 2027.\n\nColeman was born and raised in Detroit, Michigan. She earned a bachelor\'s degree from Michigan State University in 2007, a J.D. from Wayne State University Law School in 2010, and a master\'s degree (MBA) from the University of Detroit Mercy in 2014. Before taking the bench, she worked in private practice, specializing in criminal law, probate law, and bankruptcy law.\n\nHer swearing-in, on December 28, 2020, drew local and national attention because she was administered the oath of office by her father, who is also a judge, making them part of a notable father-daughter judicial family in the area. As a judge, Coleman has expressed a focus on cultivating community programs that better address drug treatment, mental health, and literacy.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located. The contact phone listed is the public number for the 32A District Court (19617 Harper Ave., Harper Woods, MI 48225), where she presides. As a sitting judge, she does not appear to maintain a separate candidate website, which is common for judicial incumbents running on the nonpartisan ballot.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://32adc.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/Judge-Coleman.jpg'),(408,521,'Lisa Martin','','http://lisamartinforjudge.com','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Lisa Martin is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 34th District Court, which serves the western Wayne County communities of Belleville, Huron Township, Romulus, Sumpter Township, and Van Buren Township. She is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term in the incumbent position. Martin assumed office on January 1, 2021, and her current term ends January 1, 2027.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Martin served as a magistrate at the 34th District Court. According to her Ballotpedia profile, she earned a Bachelor\'s degree in Psychology from Harvard University and a Juris Doctor from the University of Michigan Law School. She has practiced law since 1998, beginning her career as a law clerk for a Kalamazoo County Circuit Court judge and later working with the Legal Aid and Defenders Association of Detroit and in collections practice. She was a candidate for the same 34th District Court seat in 2014 before winning election to the bench.\n\nMartin maintains a campaign Facebook presence (\"Lisa Martin for Judge\") and a judicial Facebook page (\"Judge Lisa Martin\"), and a campaign website at lisamartinforjudge.com was referenced in search results. As an incumbent in a nonpartisan judicial race, her party affiliation does not appear on the ballot.\n\nNote: Detailed, current platform statements, endorsements, and specific 2026 campaign priorities were not directly accessible from the sources reviewed (the campaign website and Facebook pages did not return readable content during research). This summary is a factual synthesis of her office, district, background, and incumbency, and avoids attributing specific campaign claims that could not be verified. No public campaign phone, email, or a direct headshot image URL was confirmed.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(409,522,'Jim Plakas','','','','734-459-4740','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','James A. \"Jim\" Plakas is the incumbent judge seeking reelection to the 35th District Court (District 35) of Michigan in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary, for a 6-year term. The 35th District Court is located in Plymouth, Michigan, and serves the communities of Canton, Northville Township, City of Northville, Plymouth Township, and the City of Plymouth in western Wayne County.\n\nPlakas was first elected to the bench on November 4, 2008, at age 40, and was sworn in on February 4, 2009, becoming the sixth judge elected to the 35th District Court. His current term ends January 1, 2027, consistent with his appearance on the 2026 ballot. He brought 13 years of legal experience to the bench, having worked as a prosecutor, criminal defense attorney, assistant city attorney, and civil litigator.\n\nHe is a graduate of Central Michigan University and earned his law degree from the University of Detroit School of Law. He is admitted to practice before the Michigan state and federal courts, the U.S. Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals, and the Supreme Court of the United States.\n\nPlakas has served multiple terms as Chief Judge of the 35th District Court, including leading the court during the COVID-19 pandemic, and was appointed by the State Court Administrative Office to begin a fourth term as Chief Judge on January 1, 2025. He currently also serves as Chief Judge Pro Tem. He has been involved with the court\'s Juvenile Teen Court Program, has served as an officer of the Wayne County District Judges Association, and participates as a community mentor, volunteer, and law school moot court judge.\n\nHis professional affiliations include the American Judges Association, the American Bar Association, the State Bar of Michigan, the Hellenic Bar Association, the Michigan Judges Association, and the Wayne County District Judges Association.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located; as a sitting judge, his public presence is primarily through the official court website. The phone number listed is the 35th District Court\'s main number. No specific 2026 campaign platform statement or endorsements were found beyond his record as the incumbent judge running on his judicial experience.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.35thdistrictcourt.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/Plakas.png'),(410,534,'Michael C. Chupa','','','Courtinfo@37thdistrictcourt.org','586-574-4951','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Michael C. Chupa is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 37th District Court, which serves the cities of Warren and Center Line in Macomb County. He is running for re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term.\n\nChupa was appointed to the 37th District Court bench by Governor Rick Snyder on December 18, 2013, and was unanimously elected to continue in the position in November 2014. He was subsequently re-elected in November 2020.\n\nA Warren native, Chupa graduated from Immaculate Conception School and earned a Bachelor of Science from Wayne State University and his Juris Doctorate from the Detroit College of Law. He began his legal career on June 3, 1991, prosecuting cases on behalf of the city of Warren in the same courtroom he now presides over. In 1995 he founded the law firm Chupa and Associates, where he practiced criminal defense and handled complex real estate matters before assuming the bench.\n\nOn the court, Chupa has been active in problem-solving courts. Since April 2022 he has volunteered to serve as the 37th District Court\'s judge for the treatment/sobriety court programs, reflecting a stated commitment to helping court-involved people improve their lives. He has also been elected by his peer judges to serve multiple terms as president of the Macomb County District Judges Association.\n\nOutside the courtroom, Chupa has been involved in his community, coaching basketball and baseball for many years with the Warren Police Athletic League and coaching youth soccer for AYSO Region 708 in Warren. According to his official court biography, he is married to a second-grade teacher and has three children.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign-specific phone number, or campaign email was located; the contact information provided above is the official 37th District Court office line and general court email. As a sitting incumbent judge in a nonpartisan judicial race, Chupa does not appear to maintain a separate candidate site, which is common for judicial incumbents.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://37thdistrictcourt.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Honorable.Michael.C.Chupa_.headshot-240x300.jpg'),(411,541,'Joseph Craigen Oster','','','','586-445-5385','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Joseph Craigen Oster is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 40th District Court in St. Clair Shores (Macomb County), seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. He was first elected to the 40th District Court in November 1996 and has been re-elected since.\n\nOster earned a B.A. in History from the University of Michigan (1986) and his law degree from the University of Detroit School of Law (1992). A defining focus of his judicial career has been domestic violence prevention. He served on the inaugural Macomb County Domestic Violence Fatality Review team, received the 2007 Tracy Minnella award for his leadership on domestic violence issues, and has served as president of the Macomb Community Domestic Violence Council since 2008. He authored \"Stop the Blaming: Rethinking Responsibility in Domestic Violence Cases,\" published in the State Bar of Michigan\'s Family Law Journal in May 2012. He also sits on the Macomb County Community Corrections advisory board.\n\nAs a long-serving district court judge, Oster handles the typical 40th District Court caseload of misdemeanors, traffic and civil matters, and preliminary felony proceedings for St. Clair Shores. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located; the contact information available is for his official court office (586-445-5385). A specific campaign platform statement for the 2026 cycle was not found online; this summary is drawn from his official court biography and publicly available records.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.scsmi.net/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=6097'),(412,542,'Annemarie Marino Lepore','','','JudgeLeporeClerk@sterlingheights.gov','(586) 446-2500','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Annemarie Marino Lepore is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 41A District Court, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. The 41A District Court serves Sterling Heights and Sterling Township in Macomb County, located at 40111 Dodge Park Road, Sterling Heights, Michigan 48313.\n\nLepore was appointed to the 41A District Court on December 21, 2018 by Governor Rick Snyder to fill an open judicial seat, and she has since been retained by voters. She currently serves as Chief Judge Pro Tem of the court.\n\nShe earned a Bachelor of Arts in political science from Oakland University and a Juris Doctor from the University of Detroit Mercy School of Law. Before her appointment to the bench, she practiced law in the Macomb County area.\n\nLepore is a member of the State Bar of Michigan, the Women Lawyers Association of Michigan–Macomb Region, the Macomb County Bar Association, the Macomb County Bar Foundation, and the Italian American Bar Association. She serves on the Board of Directors for both the Macomb County Bar Foundation and Families Against Narcotics (FAN), a community organization focused on combating substance abuse.\n\nAs a district court judge, her docket includes misdemeanor criminal cases, civil matters, traffic offenses, and small claims for the communities the 41A District Court serves. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, separate campaign phone, or campaign email was located; the contact information listed here is for her official court chambers/clerk. District and judicial races in Michigan are nonpartisan, and incumbent judges commonly run without a standalone campaign web presence. No specific endorsements or detailed 2026 campaign platform were found in available public sources beyond her record of service on the bench.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.sterlingheights.gov/ImageRepository/Document?documentId=12757'),(413,543,'Jacob Michael Femminineo Jr.','','','femminineoclerk@41bcourt-mi.us','586-469-9300','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Jacob Michael Femminineo Jr. is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 41B District Court, which has jurisdiction over civil and criminal matters arising in Clinton Township, Harrison Township, and Mt. Clemens in Macomb County. He is seeking reelection in the nonpartisan judicial race on the August 4, 2026 primary ballot for a six-year term.\n\nFemminineo was appointed to the 41B District Court bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in April 2019 to fill a vacancy, and subsequently won election to the seat. He has since served as Chief Judge of the court. A lifelong resident of Macomb County, he has practiced law since 1995.\n\nHe earned his bachelor\'s degree and a Master of Public Administration (2013) from Wayne State University, and a Juris Doctor from the Detroit College of Law in 1995. Before taking the bench, he practiced with the Mount Clemens firm Michigan Divorce Help alongside his brother David Femminineo.\n\nFemminineo has been active in the legal community, serving in leadership roles with the Macomb County Bar Association (MCBA), where, according to the court\'s biography, he became the youngest president in the association\'s then-104-year history. His community involvement includes service on the Mt. Clemens Planning Commission and volunteering as a Meals on Wheels driver since 2016. He is affiliated with the Knights of Columbus and the State Bar of Michigan.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located; as a sitting judge running for reelection, his public-facing presence is primarily through the official 41B District Court website. The contact phone and email listed reflect his court chambers/clerk rather than a campaign committee. No detailed campaign platform statement or specific endorsements for the 2026 cycle were found in the sources reviewed. This summary is based on the court\'s official biography and Michigan state appointment records.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://41bdistrictcourt.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Femminineo-photo-2026.jpg'),(414,544,'Jennifer Andary','','','','586-752-9679','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Jennifer A. Andary is the incumbent judge of the 42-1 District Court (Division I) in Romeo, Macomb County, Michigan, and is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for the \"42nd District - 1st Division Judge of District Court\" position.\n\nAndary earned a BFA (cum laude, with a minor in politics) from New York University and a Juris Doctor from Thomas M. Cooley Law School. Before law school, she taught in inner-city schools in New York and Philadelphia. She joined the Macomb County Prosecutor\'s Office in 2003, where she was assigned to the 16th Judicial Circuit Court and tried numerous felony cases, winning jury convictions on major offenses, including life offenses, as well as lesser felonies and misdemeanors. She later led the office\'s Domestic Violence and Child Abuse Unit. In private practice at The Andary Law Group, she handled criminal law, family law, labor law, and federal and state matters across Michigan.\n\nIn 2017, Andary was appointed Magistrate of the 42-1 District Court, serving in that role until she took office as Judge of the 42-1 District Court on January 1, 2020. As an incumbent, she is filing for re-election by affidavit.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located, which is typical for sitting district court judges running for re-election. A candidate committee (\"Committee to Elect Jennifer Andary for District Court Judge\") is on record with Michigan campaign-finance filings. The court is located at 14713 33 Mile Rd., Romeo, MI 48065 (phone 586-752-9679). No specific 2026 platform statements, priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources; this summary is based on her official court biography and ballot listings.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.macombgov.org/sites/default/files/styles/large/public/images/2022-10/RC_20221014_JudgeJenniferAndary.png'),(415,545,'Brian Christian Hartwell','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Brian Christian Hartwell is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 43rd District Court, seeking re-election to a 6-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. The 43rd District Court serves Hazel Park, Ferndale, and Madison Heights in Oakland County; Hartwell presides over the Hazel Park division (43 E. Nine Mile Rd., Hazel Park, MI 48030). The court handles criminal matters, civil cases under $25,000, and civil infractions.\n\nHartwell was appointed to the bench in 2020 by Governor Gretchen Whitmer to fill the vacancy created by the retirement/resignation of Judge Chuck Goedert, and he was subsequently elected to a 6-year term in November 2020. Before becoming a judge, he served as Mayor of the City of Madison Heights, a position to which he was elected in 2015. He ran his own private practice, the Law Office of Brian C. Hartwell, PLLC, in Madison Heights, which he opened in 2013.\n\nAs a judge, Hartwell oversees the court\'s Hybrid Drug/DWI Treatment Court, a specialty program that integrates substance-abuse treatment with accountability to address underlying causes of criminal behavior. He is known on the bench for demanding thorough preparation and professionalism from attorneys and for a firm posture on bond/probation violations and drunk-driving cases. In community involvement, he has continued a \"Rake with the Mayor\" volunteer program assisting residents and, as mayor, established a pro bono legal clinic at the Madison Heights Senior Center serving low-income seniors.\n\nNo active 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone, public campaign email, or direct headshot image URL was located in available public sources. (An older fairferndale.org page references his earlier judicial run, and he maintains a LinkedIn profile, but neither provided current 2026 campaign contact details.) This summary is a best-effort factual synthesis from court profile pages and local news coverage; specific 2026 platform statements or endorsements were not found and are not asserted here.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(416,546,'Jaimie Powell Horowitz','','https://www.facebook.com/horowitzforjudge/','','(248) 691-7440','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Jaimie Powell Horowitz is the incumbent Judge of Michigan\'s 45th District Court, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a 6-year term. The 45th District Court is based in Oak Park (Oakland County) and serves the communities of Oak Park, Pleasant Ridge, Huntington Woods, and Royal Oak Township.\n\nHorowitz was first elected to the bench in 2020. Before becoming a judge, she spent roughly 15 years in public service. From 2004 she served as an assistant prosecutor with the Wayne County Prosecutor\'s Office, where she was assigned to the Homicide Unit. She also worked as a special prosecutor for the Fair Michigan Justice Project, a nonprofit through which she helped prosecute hate crimes committed against the LGBTQ community. She earned her J.D. from the University of Detroit Mercy School of Law. During her judicial tenure she has served as Chief Judge Pro Tem of the 45th District Court.\n\nHorowitz\'s primary online presence is her campaign Facebook page, \"Hon. Jaimie Powell Horowitz, Judge of the 45th District Court\" (handle \"horowitzforjudge\"), and her X/Twitter account @JPH_justice. No standalone dedicated campaign website was located. Her campaign messaging has emphasized her record of public service and her intent to continue serving as Judge of the 45th District Court.\n\nA detailed re-election platform or list of 2026 endorsements was not located in available public sources. The phone number listed here is the main administrative line for the 45th District Court, not a dedicated campaign line; no separate public campaign phone or email was found. This summary is a best-effort, factual synthesis drawn from publicly available background and social-media information.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(417,547,'Shelia Johnson','','','','(248) 796-5810','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Judge Shelia R. Johnson is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 46th District Court in Southfield (Oakland County), seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. The 46th District Court serves Southfield, Lathrup Village, Bingham Farms, Beverly Hills, Franklin, and Southfield Township.\n\nFirst elected to the bench in 2002, Johnson made history as the first African American judge to serve on the 46th District Court and the first African American female district judge in Oakland County. She has served as Chief Judge of the court and was re-elected, including running unopposed in 2014. In 2012 she was a Democratic Party nominee for the Michigan Supreme Court.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Johnson practiced law for roughly 18-20 years, handling complex criminal and civil litigation in state and federal courts. She earned her undergraduate degree from Dartmouth College and her law degree from the University of Michigan Law School, where she was the first African American elected President of the Law School Senate and delivered her class commencement address. Earlier in her career she served as a law clerk to U.S. District Judge Benjamin F. Gibson in the Western District of Michigan.\n\nA longtime Southfield resident, Johnson has been active in community and professional organizations, including the NAACP, the local MLK Task Force, and Delta Sigma Theta Sorority. She is a past president of the Michigan District Judges Association and has received recognition for community service, including a 2018 Community Service Award from the Detroit Urban League. Coverage of her tenure describes her as known for a \"tough but fair\" approach on the bench.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign-specific phone number was located. The contact details provided are her official court office. As a nonpartisan judicial incumbent, she does not appear to maintain a public campaign platform statement online; this summary is synthesized from her official court biography and news coverage rather than a campaign manifesto.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.cityofsouthfield.com/sites/default/files/styles/content_image_900px_/public/2019-07/court_johnson.jpg'),(418,549,'Kimberly Small','','','','248-647-1141','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Kimberly F. Small is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 48th District Court, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. The 48th District Court is located at 4280 Telegraph Road, Bloomfield Hills, MI 48302, and serves the communities of Birmingham, Bloomfield Hills, Bloomfield Township, West Bloomfield, Keego Harbor, Sylvan Lake, and Orchard Lake in Oakland County. Judge Small has served on this bench since 1996 and was most recently re-elected in 2014. She earned a Bachelor\'s degree from the University of Michigan and her Juris Doctor from the Detroit College of Law (now Michigan State University College of Law). Over her tenure she has built a public reputation as a strict, no-nonsense judge, particularly known for tough sentencing in operating-while-intoxicated (OWI/DUI) and other criminal cases. As a sitting district judge running as an incumbent, she does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website; the most reliable public contact point is the 48th District Court office (248-647-1141). No specific 2026 campaign platform statement, endorsements, or candidate-issued priorities were located in available public sources beyond her record of incumbency and judicial service. This summary is a brief factual synthesis; detailed campaign materials for the 2026 cycle were not found online.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(419,559,'Daniel Bain','','','','(517) 540-7644','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Daniel B. Bain is the incumbent Presiding Judge of the 53rd District Court in Livingston County, Michigan, seeking re-election to a nonpartisan six-year term in the August 4, 2026 primary. He was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in September 2019 to fill the remainder of former Judge Theresa Brennan\'s term, and was elected to the seat in 2020.\n\nA lifelong Livingston County resident, Bain graduated from Hartland High School in 1985, earned a B.A. from Michigan State University (1989), and received his J.D. from Thomas M. Cooley Law School (1993). Before becoming a judge, he spent roughly 25 years in private practice at the family firm Bain & Bain, P.C., working alongside his late father, Jack, and his brother, John. His general-practice background included criminal defense (from misdemeanors through capital felonies), commercial litigation, landlord-tenant and probate matters, and family law. He tried cases throughout Michigan and appeared frequently before township boards, city councils, zoning boards of appeals, the Michigan Liquor Control Commission, and the Department of State.\n\nAs a judge, Bain presides over the 53rd District Court and oversees the Misdemeanor Adult Drug Court (a treatment court program). He co-authored an Institute of Continuing Legal Education (ICLE) publication on Michigan criminal procedure and speaks to students about criminal law. He is a member of the State Bar of Michigan, is admitted to the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Michigan, and belongs to the Livingston County Bar Association. His community involvement includes the Livingston Sunrise Rotary Club, Michigan United Conservation Clubs, Ducks Unlimited, and board service with the Livingston County Community Alliance and the Arc of Livingston County.\n\nThe 53rd District Court is located at the Judicial Center, 204 S. Highlander Way, Howell, MI 48843. No dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or detailed candidate platform statement was located; the summary above is drawn from his official court biography and county/local news sources rather than campaign materials.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://milivcounty.gov/wp-content/uploads/Judge-Bain-150x150.jpg'),(420,135,'Stacia Buchanan','','','','(517) 483-4423','','2026-06-24 13:24:21','Stacia J. Buchanan is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 54A District Court, based in Lansing (Ingham County), and is running unopposed-eligible for reelection in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. She was appointed to the bench by Governor Rick Snyder on August 22, 2017, to fill the vacancy created by the retirement of Judge Patrick Cherry, and has since been retained by voters.\n\nBuchanan earned a B.A. in psychology from Oakland University in 2000 and a J.D. from Michigan State University College of Law in 2003. Before joining the bench, she spent more than a decade in private practice in the Lansing area, concentrating on criminal defense and family law. Her practice history includes positions as an attorney at Merchant & Maddaloni, P.C. (2003-2007), founding the Buchanan Law Office, PLLC (2007-2013), and serving of counsel at Mallory, Lapka, Scott & Selin, PLLC (2013-2017).\n\nAs a district court judge, she has handled the court\'s general caseload, which includes misdemeanors, civil matters, traffic, and preliminary felony proceedings for the City of Lansing. She has been associated with court modernization efforts, including the implementation of electronic filing at the 54A District Court. She is a member of the Ingham County Bar Association.\n\nThe 54A District Court is located at 124 W. Michigan Ave., Lansing, MI 48933; the court\'s main phone number is (517) 483-4423. As a sitting judge seeking reelection, Buchanan does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone line; the phone number provided is the court\'s official public number, not a campaign contact. No specific 2026 campaign platform statement, endorsements, or campaign materials were located in public sources. This summary is drawn from public court and reference listings rather than candidate-issued campaign materials.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(421,562,'Richard L. Hillman','','','','517-676-8400','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Richard L. Hillman is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 55th District Court, which serves Ingham County (based in Mason, Michigan), and is running for re-election as a nonpartisan candidate in the August 4, 2026 primary for a six-year term. His current term expires December 31, 2026.\n\nHillman was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in April 2020 and was subsequently elected to a six-year term in November 2020. Before becoming a judge, he spent 32 years in private practice in the Greater Lansing area, representing individuals, businesses, and municipalities in courts throughout Michigan. For more than 20 years he was a shareholder at the Lansing firm Foster, Swift, Collins & Smith, P.C., and earlier was a shareholder at the McGinty law firm in East Lansing.\n\nOn the bench, Hillman presides over the full range of cases within the 55th District Court\'s jurisdiction. He also presides over the court\'s Mental Health Court, a specialty/problem-solving court that assists individuals facing criminal charges while managing mental illness. According to the court\'s official biography, he also oversaw the court\'s domestic violence cases during his term.\n\nHillman is a graduate of Lansing Catholic Central High School, Michigan State University, and Marquette University Law School.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located; as a sitting judge he does not appear to maintain a separate campaign site. The contact phone listed above is the general number for the 55th District Court. This is a best-effort factual summary drawn from the court\'s official biography and a Foster Swift announcement of his appointment; no campaign platform statement or endorsements were found in public sources.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://docs.ingham.org/Department/55th%20District%20Court/Images/CD154-0049.jpg'),(422,563,'Adrianne K. Van Langevelde','','','','517-543-7500','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Adrianne K. Van Langevelde is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 56A District Court, which serves Eaton County, and is seeking election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed her to the bench on July 3, 2024; she took office July 22, 2024, filling a seat with a term set to expire January 1, 2027, which is why the position is on the 2026 ballot.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Van Langevelde built a career in criminal justice and public service. Beginning in December 2020 she served as a member of the Michigan Parole Board within the Michigan Department of Corrections. Earlier she worked as an assistant prosecuting attorney in both the Mecosta County and Eaton County prosecutor\'s offices. At the Eaton County Prosecutor\'s Office she was designated the child abuse and neglect prosecutor for three years and also served as the domestic violence prosecutor, handling intimate-partner cases.\n\nVan Langevelde has also held local elected office: in November 2021 she was elected to a two-year term on the Charlotte City Council. Charlotte is the Eaton County seat where the 56A District Court is located.\n\nHer educational background is rooted in Michigan State University. She graduated cum laude in 2006 with a Bachelor of Arts in Social Relations from James Madison College, MSU\'s residential public-affairs college, and earned her Juris Doctorate from Michigan State University College of Law in 2008.\n\nAs of this research, no dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located online; the contact information available is for the Eaton County 56A District Court / county administrative offices. Detailed platform statements, top priorities, or endorsements for her 2026 campaign were not found in public sources beyond her professional and judicial record summarized above. This summary is therefore drawn primarily from her official county bio and the gubernatorial appointment announcement, and reflects her experience and record rather than specific campaign-platform claims.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.eatoncounty.org/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=7959'),(423,563,'Reid S. Felsing','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Reid S. Felsing is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 56A District Court, which serves Eaton County (Charlotte area). He is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a partial two-year term ending January 1, 2029. Felsing was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in December 2024 and began judicial service on January 6, 2025, filling the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Julie A. O\'Neill.\n\nA Saginaw native, Felsing built a varied legal career before joining the bench. He began as supervising attorney and public interest fellow for the Small Business and Nonprofit Clinic at Michigan State University College of Law, then spent about five years as an associate at Knaggs Brake, P.C. in Lansing. He later opened his own law office (2017) and served as a Michigan Appellate Assigned Counsel System (MAACS) roster attorney representing indigent clients, and was on assigned-counsel lists in Ingham and Eaton Counties. Earlier, he served as a magistrate at the 56A District Court. Felsing has also taught as an adjunct professor at Michigan State University, Saginaw Valley State University, and Lansing Community College.\n\nHis education includes a Bachelor of Arts in political science and criminal justice from Saginaw Valley State University, a Juris Doctor from Michigan State University College of Law, and an LL.M. in Corporate Law and Finance from Western Michigan University\'s Thomas M. Cooley Law School.\n\nAs a sitting judge seeking to retain his seat, Felsing does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign website; no public campaign phone or email was located. No detailed 2026 campaign platform or endorsement list was found in available sources. Note: some national/political-advocacy outlets have published critical commentary about the circumstances of his appointment; these are partisan opinion sources and are not reflected as factual platform claims here.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.eatoncounty.org/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=8482'),(424,572,'Pablo Cortes','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Pablo Cortes is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 62A District Court, which serves the City of Wyoming in Kent County. He is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. Judges in Michigan typically run by affidavit of candidacy and rarely maintain campaign websites; no 2026 campaign site, phone, or email was located.\n\nCortes was appointed to the 62A District Court bench by Governor Jennifer Granholm in October 2005 and has subsequently been elected to the seat (reported elections in 2006, 2008, and 2014). He has served as Chief Judge of the 62A District Court. Before becoming a judge, he served as an Assistant Prosecuting Attorney for Kent County from 1995 until his judicial appointment.\n\nHe earned an undergraduate degree from the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor (graduated 1989, with honors) and a law degree from Wayne State University Law School in Detroit (1995).\n\nCortes has been active in statewide judicial governance. He served on the Michigan Judicial Tenure Commission beginning January 2011, holding leadership roles including Vice-Chairperson and Chairperson, and has represented District and Municipal judges in that capacity. He has also held leadership positions within the Michigan District Court Judges Association and its Legislative Committee. In addition to his judicial duties, he has served as an adjunct professor at the Thomas M. Cooley Law School in Grand Rapids and at the Grand Rapids Community College Police Academy.\n\nThe 62A District Court is a court of limited jurisdiction located at 2650 DeHoop Avenue SW in Wyoming, handling misdemeanors, civil matters, traffic, and the preliminary stages of felony cases for the City of Wyoming.\n\nNo specific 2026 campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources beyond his record as a sitting judge running for re-election. This summary is a factual synthesis of his official biographical record rather than campaign messaging.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(425,573,'Amanda H. Sterkenburg','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Amanda H. Sterkenburg is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 62-B District Court, based in Kentwood (Grand Rapids area, Kent County), seeking reelection in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. She first took the bench on January 1, 2021, making history as the first woman to serve on the Kentwood 62-B District Court, and serves as Chief Judge.\n\nSterkenburg graduated cum laude from Franklin College and cum laude from Western Michigan University Thomas M. Cooley Law School. Before becoming a judge, she ran a solo legal practice representing criminal and civil defendants, with jury trial experience in assault, theft, and retail fraud cases, and also conducted civil and domestic mediations. As a district court judge she presides over matters including drunk driving, domestic violence, and retail fraud under $1,000.\n\nDuring her tenure she has emphasized rehabilitative and problem-solving justice. Her initiatives include implementing a Domestic Violence treatment court for high-risk offenders, maintaining and expanding the West Michigan Regional Sobriety Court, and developing an \"On the Road\" program to help individuals restore driving privileges. She established an Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) plan allowing parties to resolve disputes through mediation, and she negotiated the appropriation of $35,000 in Opioid Settlement Funding from the City of Kentwood to support local probationers struggling with opioid addiction. She has pursued community outreach through partnerships such as Fox 17 Youth with Potential and the Kentwood Farmers Market.\n\nSterkenburg is a member of the State Bar of Michigan, the Grand Rapids Bar Association, and the Michigan District Judges Association, and a member of Kentwood Community Church. She relocated to Kentwood about 15 years ago with her two children, citing the community\'s diversity and opportunity.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was found; she maintains a campaign Facebook page (\"Sterkenburg for District Court Judge\") and an Instagram presence. No public campaign phone or email was located in the sources reviewed. This summary is drawn primarily from her official City of Kentwood judicial biography and local news coverage.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.kentwood.us/judgesterkenburg/Headshot 2024 in Robes.jpg'),(426,574,'Jeffrey J. O\'Hara','','','','(616) 632-7770','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Jeffrey J. O\'Hara is the incumbent Chief Judge of Michigan\'s 63rd District Court, based in Kent County (Grand Rapids area), and is running unopposed-or-as-an-incumbent for re-election in the nonpartisan August 4, 2026 primary for a six-year term. He was first elected to the 63rd District Court bench in 2014.\n\nO\'Hara is a graduate of Michigan State University and earned his Juris Doctorate from Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1985. Before joining the bench, he worked as a private-practice trial attorney. In 2012, he was admitted as a Fellow of the Michigan State Bar Foundation in recognition of his legal ability. He has been rated \"AV Preeminent\" by Martindale-Hubbell, the directory\'s highest rating for legal ability and ethical standards, consistently from 2016 onward.\n\nAs a judge, O\'Hara founded the court\'s Recovery Court in 2019, a specialty/treatment court program serving individuals struggling with addiction and alcoholism. He currently serves as Chief Judge of the 63rd District Court, which sits at 1950 E. Beltline Ave NE, Grand Rapids, MI 49525.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was found; as a sitting judge his public contact point is the 63rd District Court main line, (616) 632-7770. This is a nonpartisan judicial office, and detailed campaign platform or endorsement information was not available in the sources reviewed. The information above is drawn from the Kent County government court pages and publicly available legal-directory and Ballotpedia listings.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(427,574,'Kirsten L. Holz','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Kirsten L. Holz is an incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 63rd District Court, which serves the majority of Kent County\'s townships and suburban cities, including Rockford, East Grand Rapids, Cedar Springs, and Lowell. She is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary to fill a partial term ending January 1, 2029, the seat she currently holds.\n\nHolz was appointed to the 63rd District Court bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in 2024. Prior to her appointment, she served for many years as a public defender, working to ensure competent legal representation for individuals in need. She earned a Bachelor of Arts in Government and a Bachelor of Arts in Spanish Language from Cornell University, and in 2007 received her Juris Doctorate from the Washington College of Law at American University.\n\nAs a sitting district court judge, she presides over criminal, civil, and traffic matters within the court\'s jurisdiction. The 63rd District Court is led by Chief Judge Jeffrey J. O\'Hara and also includes Judge Daniel J. O\'Hara.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone, or campaign email was located. As an appointed incumbent seeking election to retain her seat, her public presence is primarily through the Kent County official court directory and county social media. No specific campaign platform, priorities, or endorsements were found in available public sources, so none are asserted here. This summary is drawn from her official county bio and confirmed Michigan ballot/office information.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.kentcountymi.gov/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=6619'),(428,576,'Raymond Peter Voet','','','','616-527-5346','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Raymond P. Voet is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 64A District Court, based in Ionia County, seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 primary for a nonpartisan six-year term. Voet has served on the 64A District Court bench since 1999. On January 1, 2014, he became chief judge of the circuit, district, and probate courts serving Ionia and Montcalm counties. The 64A District Court is located at 100 W. Main St., Ionia, MI 48846.\n\nVoet gained national attention in 2013 when, during a jury trial, his own cell phone disrupted proceedings; consistent with his courtroom policy on phone interruptions, he held himself in contempt of court and fined himself $25 — a widely reported example of his commitment to applying rules evenly to everyone, including himself. He has been profiled in Michigan judicial publications, including a State Bar/SCAO judicial profile noting his interest in history.\n\nLocal reporting (The Daily News, Montcalm/Ionia area) has also covered Voet in connection with a Michigan Court of Appeals candidacy, including coverage describing him squaring off against another veteran judge. The office tracked in this record, however, is his run as an incumbent for the 64A District Court judgeship (six-year term), which is a nonpartisan position.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located in public sources; like most sitting Michigan district judges, Voet does not appear to maintain a separate campaign site, and contact information available online is for the court itself rather than a campaign. The phone number provided is the publicly listed 64A District Court office line. No direct headshot image URL could be confirmed from an official or campaign source; a profile photo exists in a Michigan Courts judicial-profile PDF, but no stable direct image URL was verified.\n\nConfidence in identity is high: the name, the specific 64A District Court, Ionia County, the incumbent status, and the nonpartisan six-year district-judge term all match the established public record for this individual. Note that some recent news references a Court of Appeals run, which may reflect a separate or evolving candidacy; voters should consult official 2026 ballot/filing records for the definitive office and status.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(429,577,'Adam James Eggleston','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Adam J. Eggleston is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 64B District Court, serving Montcalm County, and is running for re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. He was first elected to the bench in 2020 and took office in 2021.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Eggleston built a career in Montcalm County\'s legal community. He served as a magistrate for the 64B District Court, ran his own private legal practice, worked as an assistant city attorney for the City of Greenville, and held a position with the Montcalm County Prosecuting Attorney\'s Office. Educationally, he earned an associate\'s degree from Montcalm Community College and a bachelor\'s degree from Michigan State University.\n\nAs judge, Eggleston is known for partnering with Montcalm Community College to launch the Academics Changes Everything (ACE) program, which offers educational opportunities to individuals as a component of their probationary terms—an effort aimed at reducing recidivism through education. He has also served as a commencement speaker for the Early College at Montcalm Community College, reflecting his continued emphasis on education in the community.\n\nAs a sitting district court judge seeking re-election, Eggleston handles the typical caseload of a Michigan district court: misdemeanor criminal matters, traffic and civil infractions, small claims, landlord-tenant disputes, and preliminary examinations in felony cases. The 64B District Court is located at 617 N. State Street, Stanton, MI.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located, which is common for incumbent district court judges in smaller Michigan jurisdictions. This summary is drawn from the Montcalm County court website and local news coverage; no campaign-specific platform statement or list of endorsements was found online. The court\'s general office phone (989-831-7450) and inquiry email (64binquiries@montcalmcountymi.gov) are public but are official court contacts rather than campaign contacts.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(430,578,'Andrew M. Stevens','','','','989-224-5150','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Andrew M. Stevens is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 65A District Court, which serves Clinton County (St. Johns). He was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer on a partial term running April 14, 2025 to January 1, 2027, filling the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Michael Clarizio. Stevens is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a full six-year term as an incumbent; he filed on January 23, 2026.\n\nBefore his appointment, Stevens served as an assistant prosecuting attorney in Ingham County, Michigan. He earned his Juris Doctor from Michigan State University College of Law. In February 2025, he received an \"Outstanding\" rating from the Women Lawyers Association of Michigan\'s Candidate Rating and Endorsement Committee.\n\nThe 65A District Court handles civil, criminal misdemeanor, traffic, small claims, and landlord-tenant matters for Clinton County, with the court located at 100 E. State Street, Suite 3400, St. Johns, MI 48879. As a sitting district judge, Stevens does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website, and no public campaign-specific contact email or phone was identified; the court\'s general office line is 989-224-5150. No detailed personal campaign platform statement, list of specific policy priorities, or named endorsements beyond the WLAM rating were located in available public sources. This summary is intentionally factual and limited because little campaign-specific material is published online for this judicial candidate.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(431,579,'Laura M. Bever','','','','(989) 875-5300','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Laura M. Bever is a 2026 nonpartisan candidate for Judge of the 65B District Court (a six-year, non-incumbent open seat). The 65B District Court serves Gratiot County, Michigan, including the cities of Alma, Ithaca, and St. Louis, which matches the candidate\'s listed city of Alma and district.\n\nBever currently serves as the Gratiot County Prosecuting Attorney and, according to local reporting, was the first woman to hold that office in Gratiot County. She has been licensed to practice law in Michigan since 1994, giving her roughly three decades of legal experience, much of it in criminal and juvenile prosecution. As prosecuting attorney, her office reviews complaints from law enforcement and citizens, authorizes warrants, and represents the State of Michigan in criminal and juvenile matters within the county. The prosecutor\'s office is located at the Gratiot County Courthouse, 214 East Center Street, Ithaca, Michigan.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or published campaign platform was located in this research. As a sitting county prosecutor running for a district court judgeship, her professional background in criminal law and county-level public service is the primary publicly available information about her qualifications. No specific campaign priorities, endorsements, or policy statements were found in the sources reviewed, so none are asserted here.\n\nThis is a best-effort factual summary; campaign-specific materials (platform, endorsements, fundraising, contact channels) do not appear to be online yet as of mid-2026. The contact phone and headshot provided are from her official Gratiot County prosecutor\'s office page, not a campaign source. Voters seeking candidate-filing confirmation can consult the Michigan Bureau of Elections public candidate listing and Gratiot County election resources.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://www.gratiotmi.com/ImageRepository/Document?documentID=10213'),(432,590,'Mona S. Armstrong','','https://www.keepjudgearmstrong.com/','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Mona S. Armstrong is the sitting judge of Michigan\'s 72nd District Court, which serves St. Clair County, and is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary to retain her seat for a six-year term. She first reached the bench by gubernatorial appointment: Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed her on March 5, 2020 to fill the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Cynthia Platzer, and she subsequently won election in November 2020.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Armstrong spent nearly 25 years as an Assistant Prosecuting Attorney in the St. Clair County Prosecutor\'s Office, where she handled numerous homicide and high-profile criminal cases. Among the notable prosecutions cited in local coverage was that of former Port Huron Mayor Gerald \"Ajax\" Ackerman, convicted in 1999 of first-degree criminal sexual conduct. Her campaign and local reporting have emphasized this extensive courtroom and prosecutorial experience as a central qualification.\n\nArmstrong has also been active as an educator within the legal community, serving as an adjunct faculty member at St. Clair County Community College and as an instructor for the Prosecuting Attorneys Association of Michigan, the National College of District Attorneys, Michigan State University College of Law\'s Victim Assistance Academy, and the Michigan State Police Fire Investigation School.\n\nShe maintains an official campaign website, \"Keep Judge Armstrong\" (keepjudgearmstrong.com), which includes an endorsements page, consistent with her status as an incumbent seeking re-election. As a District Court judge, her role covers misdemeanors, traffic and civil matters, small claims, landlord-tenant disputes, and felony preliminary examinations within St. Clair County.\n\nNote: This is a best-effort summary drawn from public listings (Ballotpedia, BallotReady), local news (Tri City Times), and her campaign site\'s title/search snippets. The campaign website could not be fully fetched during research, so specific 2026 platform statements, current endorsements, and direct contact details (phone, email, headshot) could not be independently confirmed and are reported as null. Identity is confirmed as the correct person by matching Michigan, the 72nd District Court, St. Clair County, the nonpartisan judicial office, and incumbent status.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(433,592,'Michael D. Carpenter','','','','(989) 832-6700','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Michael D. Carpenter is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 75th District Court, which serves Midland County, and is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Born and raised in the Hillsdale and Jackson County area of Michigan, Carpenter was the first in his family to attend college. He earned a bachelor\'s degree in business from Western Michigan University in 1988, graduating with honors, and a Juris Doctorate, Cum Laude, from Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1994.\n\nCarpenter began his legal career as a law clerk for the Honorable Thomas Beale and the Honorable Thomas Ludington, then worked as an associate attorney at the Mathieu & Lee law firm before opening his own solo practice in 1999. He served as Midland County Prosecuting Attorney from 2004 to 2013, winning re-election unopposed in 2008 and 2012. Governor Rick Snyder appointed him to the 75th District Court in late 2013 (taking the bench in January 2014) to fill the vacancy created by Judge John Hart\'s retirement, and he has since been re-elected unopposed.\n\nCarpenter is active in community and civic organizations, including board service with the Prosecuting Attorneys Association of Michigan (PAAM), Shelter House, Habitat for Humanity (as President), the Health and Human Services Collaborative, Senior Services, and Midland Evangelical Free Church. He also teaches legal update classes to law enforcement agencies across the state. He is married to his wife Terra, his high school sweetheart, and they have three daughters.\n\nAs a sitting judge filing for re-election, Carpenter has not published a separate 2026 campaign website or platform statement; this summary is drawn from his official Midland County court biography and public records. No campaign-specific contact email or phone was located, so the listed phone number is the 75th District Court\'s main office line (301 West Main Street, Midland, MI 48640).','',0,'jon-uncon','https://midlandcountymi.gov/corecode/uploads/sidebar/uploaded_images/corecode/Judge%20Carpenter_293.jpg'),(434,593,'Eric R. Janes','','','','(989) 772-0911','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Eric R. Janes is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 76th District Court, which serves Isabella County (seat in Mount Pleasant). He is running unopposed/as an incumbent for a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary.\n\nJanes was appointed to the 76th District Court by Governor Rick Snyder on November 26, 2013, filling the vacancy created by the retirement of Judge William R. Rush. He was then elected to a full six-year term, unopposed, on November 4, 2014 (term beginning January 1, 2015). He has subsequently served as the court\'s Chief Judge, becoming Isabella County\'s chief judge after Judge Chamberlain stepped down.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Janes was in private practice with his firm Janes, Backus and Janes from 1991 until his 2013 appointment. He earned his undergraduate degree from Michigan State University and his J.D. from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School. He is a past president of the Isabella County Bar Association and a member of the Isabella County Foundation.\n\nAs a sitting district court judge, Janes presides over the matters typical of a Michigan district court, including misdemeanors, civil cases, small claims, traffic, and felony arraignments/preliminary examinations. As is standard for incumbent Michigan judicial candidates, he does not appear to maintain a separate campaign website, and judicial-ethics norms limit public position-taking on contested issues; no specific 2026 campaign platform, endorsements, or policy statements were located in public sources. The listed phone is the official 76th District Court main line (300 N. Main St., Mt. Pleasant, MI 48858), not a dedicated campaign number. No campaign email or headshot URL was found.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(435,594,'Peter Michael Jaklevic','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Peter M. Jaklevic is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 77th District Court, seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. The 77th District Court serves Mecosta and Osceola counties and is located in Reed City, Michigan.\n\nJaklevic earned his bachelor\'s degree from Michigan State University in 1990 and his law degree (J.D.) from the Michigan State University College of Law in 1993. Before becoming a judge, he built his career in the Mecosta County Prosecutor\'s Office, where he served as an assistant prosecutor from 1994 to 1998 and as the chief prosecuting attorney from 1998 to 2014 (he was first appointed chief prosecutor in 1998 at age 29). As a prosecutor, he reportedly handled multiple first-degree murder cases, including cold-case homicide prosecutions.\n\nHe was first elected to the 77th District Court on November 4, 2014, defeating James J. Sims II with roughly 67 percent of the vote, and began his judicial term on January 1, 2015. He has continued to serve on the court since then and is now running as the incumbent for another six-year term.\n\nNo official 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, campaign email address, or candidate headshot was located through public web searches. As is common for sitting district court judges in Michigan, Jaklevic does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign website; voters are typically directed to court and county election resources rather than a candidate-run site. This is a best-effort factual summary based on available public records and news coverage; current 2026 platform statements, priorities, or endorsements were not found and are not asserted here.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(436,595,'Ellsworth J. Stay Jr.','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Ellsworth J. Stay Jr. is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 78th District Court, which serves Newaygo and Lake counties, and is running in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a full six-year term. He was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in February 2024 to fill a partial term created by the resignation of Judge Kevin Drake, and he subsequently appeared on the ballot in a special election on November 5, 2024.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Stay served as the elected Prosecuting Attorney for Newaygo County, a position he held beginning in 2017. He has worked in public service in Newaygo County for more than 20 years in a range of roles, including chief assistant prosecuting attorney and trial court director/friend of the court. He has also served on the Board of Directors of the Prosecuting Attorneys Association of Michigan (PAAM).\n\nAccording to his official biography, Stay earned a Bachelor of Arts in American Government from the University of Virginia and a Juris Doctor from the Indiana University Maurer School of Law.\n\nAs a sitting district court judge, Stay\'s public record centers on local criminal, civil, and traffic matters within the 78th District Court\'s jurisdiction. No 2026-specific campaign website, platform statement, endorsements, or public campaign contact information were located in available online sources; like many trial-court judges seeking re-election, he does not appear to maintain a dedicated campaign site, and his primary public-facing presence is through the Newaygo County District Court and state court system. This summary is intentionally factual and brief because limited campaign-specific material was found for the 2026 cycle.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(437,596,'John D. Middlebrook','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','John D. Middlebrook is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 79th District Court, seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. The 79th District Court serves Mason and Lake counties in western Michigan, with the main courthouse in Ludington.\n\nMiddlebrook was first elected to the 79th District Court in November 2020, defeating opponent Glenn Jackson III by a combined vote of roughly 9,800 to 7,500 across the two counties, and was sworn in on December 30, 2020. Before becoming a judge, he served for many years as an assistant prosecuting attorney with the Mason County Prosecutor\'s Office.\n\nEducationally, Middlebrook graduated from Southfield-Lathrup High School in 1980, earned a bachelor of arts degree in history from Albion College in 1984, and received his juris doctor degree from Wake Forest University School of Law in 1987.\n\nAs a sitting district court judge, his caseload encompasses the typical jurisdiction of Michigan district courts: misdemeanor criminal cases, civil matters up to the statutory limit, small claims, landlord-tenant disputes, traffic and ordinance violations, and the preliminary stages of felony cases.\n\nBecause this is a nonpartisan judicial race, Middlebrook is listed as Nonpartisan and is filing as the incumbent. Detailed 2026 campaign materials, a dedicated campaign website, and published contact information were not located in available public sources; judicial candidates in smaller Michigan districts frequently maintain minimal online campaign presence. A \"Middlebrook for Judge\" Facebook page exists but did not yield extractable contact details or a published platform statement. No specific 2026 policy priorities, endorsements, or campaign quotes were found, so none are asserted here. Voters seeking direct contact information can reach the 79th District Court through the Mason County courthouse at 304 East Ludington Avenue, Ludington, MI 49431.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(438,599,'Joshua M. Farrell','','','80thdistrictcourt@gladwincounty-mi.gov','989-426-9207','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Joshua M. Farrell is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 80th District Court, which serves Clare County and Gladwin County. He was first elected to the bench in 2008 and is seeking re-election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary for a six-year term. The 80th District Court is the court of first instance for criminal, traffic, DNR, animal control, and local municipal matters in its two-county jurisdiction, handling civil infractions, misdemeanors, and the initial stages of felony cases (arraignment and preliminary examination) before they proceed to Circuit Court.\n\nAccording to publicly available biographical information, Farrell earned his undergraduate degree from Central Michigan University and his Juris Doctor from the Thomas M. Cooley Law School. Before joining the bench, he worked as an attorney in private practice.\n\nAs a sitting district judge filing for re-election by affidavit of incumbency, Farrell does not appear to maintain a dedicated 2026 campaign website. The contact information listed here is for his official court office in Gladwin (401 West Cedar Avenue, Gladwin, MI 48624), not a campaign committee. No campaign-specific platform statement, endorsements, or stated priorities were located in the sources reviewed. No direct headshot image URL was found on the court or Ballotpedia pages.\n\nThis is a factual summary; limited campaign-specific material is available online for this judicial incumbent, which is typical for sitting nonpartisan district judges running unopposed or with low-profile races.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(439,600,'Mary A. Beebe','','','','989-275-8021','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Mary A. Beebe (the Honorable Mary Ann Beebe) is the sitting judge of the 82nd District Court in Roscommon County, Michigan, and is running as an incumbent for a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Before becoming a judge, she served as the Roscommon County Prosecuting Attorney. In the 2022 election, she challenged and defeated the incumbent 82nd District Court judge, Troy B. Daniel, and took the oath of office on December 20 of that cycle, with the oath administered by Probate Judge Mark Jernigan. The 82nd District Court is a single-judge district located in Roscommon County, with offices in the Roscommon County Building and Courthouse at 500 Lake Street, Roscommon, MI 48653, and serves the Houghton Lake and surrounding area, handling criminal, civil, traffic, and small-claims matters. A campaign committee, \"The Committee to Elect Mary A. Beebe for 82nd District Court Judge,\" is registered with Michigan\'s campaign finance system, and a related campaign Facebook page exists. Limited additional detail about her educational background, prior legal career, specific platform priorities, or endorsements was found in public sources; this summary is therefore primarily a factual account of her current office, her prior role as county prosecutor, and her status as the incumbent seeking re-election. Voters seeking more detail should consult the court\'s official listings or her campaign committee filings.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(440,601,'Corey J. Wiggins','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Corey J. Wiggins is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 84th District Court, which covers Wexford and Missaukee Counties, and is seeking election to a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 primary. He was appointed to the bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer on January 21, 2025, to fill the partial term created by the resignation of Judge Audrey Van Alst, and was sworn in on January 31, 2025. The appointed term commenced January 22, 2025, and expires at noon on January 1, 2027, which is why the seat appears on the 2026 ballot for a full term.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Wiggins served as the Wexford County Prosecuting Attorney, first elected in November 2020 and re-elected in November 2024. From 2017 to 2020 he served as the county\'s chief assistant prosecuting attorney. Earlier in his career he owned and operated Wiggins Law Firm, PLC, a private practice in the Cadillac area (49601) where he handled criminal defense, business law, real estate/real property law, and municipal law. He is a licensed Michigan attorney (State Bar of Michigan).\n\nAs a sitting district judge, Wiggins presides over the trial-court matters typical of Michigan district courts, including misdemeanor criminal cases, civil claims, traffic matters, and preliminary proceedings in felony cases for the Wexford-Missaukee region.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, public campaign phone number, or campaign email was located, which is common for incumbent judicial candidates running nonpartisan races (often unopposed). A direct headshot image URL from an official court bio or campaign source could not be confirmed. Available reporting indicates his candidacy is associated with running for the full term following his appointment. Voters seeking official contact information can reach him through the 84th District Court. This summary is drawn from news coverage of his appointment and swearing-in and from the Michigan Governor\'s official press release; no specific campaign platform statements, priorities, or endorsements were found in public sources, so none are asserted here.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(441,602,'Michael J. Ekdahl','','','d89@cheboygancounty.net','(231) 627-8809','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Michael J. Ekdahl is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 89th District Court, which serves Cheboygan and Presque Isle counties, and is running for a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary. Governor Gretchen Whitmer appointed Ekdahl to the bench in February 2024 to fill a partial term created by the resignation of Judge Maria Barton; his appointment took effect March 18, 2024. He previously ran as a candidate in 2024 for the same seat. He now serves as Chief District Judge.\n\nBefore joining the bench, Ekdahl was a solo practitioner in the region with a practice emphasizing criminal defense, along with civil litigation, divorce, and estate planning. He earned a Bachelor of Arts in History from the University of Michigan and his Juris Doctor from Wayne State University Law School.\n\nEkdahl has been active in the local legal and civic community. He served as general counsel for Presque Isle Electric and Gas Co-op in Onaway, was a founding member of the 53rd Circuit Court Sobriety Court Team, and is a past president of the Cheboygan/Presque Isle County Bar Association. His community involvement also includes past president of the Cheboygan Lions Club and prior service on the Board of Directors of the Cheboygan Area Arts Council.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website was located. As an incumbent district judge, his public contact information is through the 89th District Court (870 S. Main Street, P.O. Box 70, Cheboygan, MI 49721). Specific 2026 campaign priorities, platform statements, and endorsements were not found in available public sources, so this summary is based on biographical and appointment records rather than campaign materials.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(442,603,'Angela L. Lasher','','https://www.keepjudgelasher.com','','(231) 348-1750','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Angela J. Lasher (the official record uses middle initial \"J.\"; the filing\'s \"L.\" appears to be a transcription variant) is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 90th District Court, seeking election to a full six-year term in the August 4, 2026 primary. The 90th District Court serves Emmet and Charlevoix Counties and is based in Petoskey, Michigan. It is a nonpartisan judicial office.\n\nLasher was appointed to the bench on January 14, 2020 by Governor Gretchen Whitmer to fill the vacancy created by the departure of Judge James N. Erhart, and she assumed office on February 14, 2020. She became the first female judge to serve on the 90th District Court. Her current term ends in 2027.\n\nBefore becoming a judge, Lasher spent approximately fifteen years as an assistant prosecuting attorney for Emmet County. She also served as legal director of the Women\'s Justice Center and has been a member of the steering committee for Northern Community Mediation, a regional nonprofit. She earned a bachelor\'s degree in sociology and political science from Purdue University and her law degree from Thomas M. Cooley Law School.\n\nAs a district court judge, Lasher presides over what is commonly called \"the people\'s court,\" handling traffic violations, civil matters up to $25,000, landlord-tenant disputes, and misdemeanor criminal cases. Her campaign operates under the banner \"Keep Judge Angela Lasher\" with an associated website (keepjudgelasher.com) and Facebook page, reflecting an incumbent-retention message focused on continuity and \"moving the court forward.\"\n\nDetailed campaign platform statements, specific policy priorities, and formal endorsements were not confirmed in the sources reviewed, so they are not asserted here. The phone number listed is the court\'s official public line; no campaign-specific phone or email was located.','',0,'jon-uncon','https://emmetcounty.org/government/courts/90th_district_court/Images/Government/Courts/90th%20District%20Court/lasherfinalfinal@0.33x.png'),(443,604,'Beth Ann Gibson','','','','','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Beth Ann Gibson is the incumbent chief judge of Michigan\'s 92nd District Court, which serves Mackinac and Luce counties in the eastern Upper Peninsula. She is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the nonpartisan August 4, 2026 Michigan primary, running for District Judge in the 92nd District. According to public reporting, both Gibson and another candidate, Thomas North, filed for the seat.\n\nGibson first took the bench in January 2005 after winning the November 2004 general election, and has served as the district\'s judge for roughly two decades. She has held expanded leadership responsibilities within the regional court system: the Michigan Supreme Court appointed her to serve as chief judge not only of the 92nd District Court but also of the eastern Upper Peninsula\'s 11th Circuit Court, the 93rd District Court, and the area\'s two probate districts, consolidating administrative oversight across multiple courts in the region.\n\nLocal coverage from St. Ignace News and the Mackinac Town Crier indicates Gibson has been active in developing court programs and presiding over a range of criminal and civil matters in the 92nd District, including notable felony cases in Mackinac County. As an incumbent judge, her record on the bench and her leadership role across the eastern UP\'s courts form the basis of her candidacy.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign phone number, campaign email, or candidate headshot image was located through public web searches. This is typical for incumbent Michigan district judges in small rural jurisdictions, who often run without standalone campaign sites. Voters seeking direct contact or biographical detail can reference the 92nd District Court offices in Mackinac and Luce counties. No specific 2026 platform statement, endorsements, or campaign materials were found in available sources; the summary above is drawn from news reporting and ballot/candidate listings rather than from a campaign-published statement.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(444,160,'Julie Ann LaCost','','','','(906) 774-0506','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Julie Ann LaCost is the incumbent Chief Judge of the 95B District Court in Dickinson County, Michigan, seeking election in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary to a six-year term. She was appointed to the 95B District Court bench by Governor Rick Snyder in February 2018, filling the vacancy created by the resignation of Judge Christopher Ninomiya, and is the seventh judge to serve that court. She subsequently won election to retain the seat.\n\nThe 95B District Court, located at 705 S. Stephenson St., Iron Mountain, MI 49801, handles landlord-tenant cases, land contract disputes, misdemeanor criminal offenses, civil lawsuits under $25,000, small claims cases ($6,000 or less), civil municipal infractions, civil traffic infractions, and civil weddings.\n\nLaCost earned her undergraduate degree from the University of Michigan in 1984 and her law degree from Thomas M. Cooley Law School in 1988. Before taking the bench, she spent her career in private legal practice in both Michigan and Wisconsin. She is a member of the State Bar of Michigan, the State Bar of Wisconsin, and the Dickinson-Iron County Bar Association.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or candidate headshot was located in public sources at the time of research; judicial candidates frequently run without standalone campaign sites. The phone number listed is the court\'s official line. As the sitting incumbent running for re-election, no specific 2026 campaign platform statements or endorsements were found online. This summary is drawn from news coverage of her appointment and the county court\'s official page.','',0,'jon-uncon',''),(445,609,'Nicholas J. Daavettila','','','','906-482-4980','','2026-06-24 13:24:22','Nicholas J. Daavettila is the incumbent judge of Michigan\'s 97th District Court, which serves Baraga, Houghton, and Keweenaw counties in the western Upper Peninsula. He is seeking re-election to a six-year term in the August 4, 2026 nonpartisan primary.\n\nDaavettila was appointed to the 97th District Court bench by Governor Gretchen Whitmer in April 2020, succeeding retiring Judge Mark Wisti, and was sworn in that spring. Before becoming a judge, he was a private-practice attorney in Houghton, handling a range of matters including criminal law, child protective proceedings, family law, and probate estates. He also served as director and secretary of Tri-County Public Defenders, a nonprofit indigent-defense corporation covering Houghton, Baraga, and Keweenaw counties.\n\nHe holds a Bachelor of Science in Economics from Michigan Technological University and a Juris Doctor from Marquette University Law School.\n\nAs a district court judge in Michigan, his bench handles misdemeanor criminal cases, traffic and civil infractions, small claims, landlord-tenant matters, and felony preliminary examinations for the three-county district. The court\'s main office is located on the third floor of the Houghton County Courthouse, 401 E. Houghton Ave., Houghton, Michigan.\n\nNo dedicated 2026 campaign website, campaign email, or campaign phone number was located in public sources, which is common for sitting district-court judges in small rural Michigan jurisdictions. The phone number listed is the official 97th District Court office line. No specific platform statement, priorities, or endorsements were found in available sources beyond his record as the appointed and sitting judge running to retain the seat. This is a best-effort factual summary based on local news coverage of his 2020 appointment and the court\'s official directory; further campaign-specific detail was not available online as of June 2026.','',0,'jon-uncon','');
